<FIRST>r a AM-FreezerDeath     07-12 0238</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Freezer Death,0244</SECOND>
<HEAD>Former School Administrator Sentenced To 20-40 Years</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A former school administrator who killed his wife
and hid her body in a basement freezer for 3{ years was sentenced
Wednesday to 20 to 40 years in prison.
   Leonard Tyburski, 46, was ordered transferred to the state
Corrections Department from the Wayne County Jail, where he has
remained since his June 26 second-degree murder conviction.
   Dorothy Tyburski, 37, was beaten to death in the basement of the
couple's home in Wayne County's Canton Township in 1985. Her body
was found Jan. 2 when their oldest daughter, Kelly, pried open the
locked freezer.
   Their youngest daughter, Kim, 16, had pleaded in a letter to
Wayne County Circuit Judge Richard P. Hathaway for leniency for her
father.
   ``We're disappointed by the sentence,'' Carole Stanyar said.
Tyburski will be ``well into his 60s'' before he is paroled, she
added.
   Kelly Tyburski said she felt sorry for her sister, but believed
her father should spend some time behind bars. ``It was wrong,'' she
said. ``Even if my mother was the cause of it, he should have
controlled himself.''
   Tyburski testified that he repeatedly smashed his wife's head
into a basement pillar after she taunted him about an affair she was
having with Kelly's 18-year-old boyfriend, who lived at the Tyburski
house.
   Stanyar said her client hasn't decided whether he would appeal
the conviction or his prison term.
</TEXT>
