<FILEID>AP-NR-07-12-89 0023EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-OlivierAppreciation     07-12 0794</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Olivier Appreciation,0815</SECOND>
<HEAD>Complete Man of Theater Best Remembered in America for His Film Work</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Also in Wednesday AMs report.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL KUCHWARA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Drama Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Laurence Olivier was a complete man of the
theater who paradoxically scored some of his biggest successes on
screen.
   His career in England spanned all aspects of the stage _ matinee
idol, classical actor supreme, theater director and producer.
   But American audiences remember him best for his movie work,
particularly a trio of romantic films _ ``Wuthering Heights,''
``Rebecca'' and ``Pride and Prejudice'' _ and a series of
Shakespeare adaptations _ ``Henry V,'' ``Hamlet'' and ``Richard
III'' _ that rank among the best ever done on film.
   Olivier, who died Tuesday at 82, was that rare combination, a
superb classical actor and an extraordinary contemporary actor. He
was at home in the plays of Shakespeare, Shaw and Chekhov as well as
in a modern movie thriller like ``Marathon Man'' or a TV miniseries
like ``Brideshead Revisited.''
   ``It would be the equivalent of him being the greatest opera
singer the world has ever known and a great rock star,'' said
Geraldine Fitzgerald, who appeared with him in ``Wuthering Heights''
50 years ago. ``He was great in pop culture, and he was great in
classical culture.''
   Olivier also was an intelligent actor, single-minded in his
intention to give the best performance possible but also inventive
and original in this thinking.
   ``He was one of those very rare actors _ there may be three or
four in a lifetime _ who were touched by the finger of God,'' said
Hume Cronyn, who first met Olivier in the early 1940s through his
wife, Jessica Tandy. ``He had enormous talent, application, looks _
he had it all. He knew how to use it all. And he was immensely
daring. ... There was nothing that Larry could not do.''
   Cronyn once was considering taking a job as artistic director of
a theater company, but told Olivier he was frightened.
   ``If you won't do it, you don't deserve to have it,'' Olivier
said.
   Olivier embraced all types of theater. In 1957, he allied himself
with a wave of British playwrights, particularly John Osborne. He
scored a huge personal triumph as the seedy has-been Archie Rice in
Osborne's ``The Entertainer,'' appearing in the play in London, New
York and on screen.
   ``If the character was a saint, he would find out how to play him
in a truthful, honest way,'' Miss Fitzgerald said. ``If the
character was a villain, he wouldn't imitate what he thought a
villain might be like, he would play his own villainry. He had the
courage to look into the darker sides of himself and then use them
to illuminate the character he was playing.''
   Olivier took chances off-stage, too. He became the first director
of Great Britain's National Theater, guiding it through its
formative years. And he was enormously generous to other actors,
giving newcomers a chance at the theater he ran.
   ``It feels like the end of an era,'' said Jim Dale, who was hired
by Olivier in the early 1970s to star at the National. ``Larry
depicted everything from actor to producer to theater administrator.
What great moments of instruction and theater this man gave us!''
   ``He was sometimes wrong, which was delightful,'' Cronyn said.
``Here he was, God Almighty among actors, and he was wrong.''
   Cronyn recalled agreeing to play in Moliere's ``The Miser.''
   Olivier was disdainful: ``Moliere? Funny as a baby's open grave.''
   ``Boy, was he dead wrong. We brought down the house,'' Cronyn
said.
   To critics who complained about some of the roles Olivier took in
his later years, Cronyn said: ``You get to be an icon, and it's
almost impossible to maintain. Do you want to work or don't you? The
great roles by great playwrights don't come along too often.''
   Cronyn said he once criticized a job Olivier took. ``It's
garbage,'' Olivier agreed. Then why did he take it? ``Dear boy,
they're paying me a fortune.''
   Olivier worked until the end of his life. Even when he was quite
sick, he would take jobs, mostly in television.
   ``However physically frail he was, once he got on camera, he
burned like a fire,'' said Simon Jones, who played Olivier's son in
``Brideshead Revisited.''
   In his maiden speech to the House of Lords in 1971, Olivier said,
``I believe in the theater. I believe in it as the first glamorizer
of thought. It restores dramatic dynamics and their relationships to
life size. ... I believe in anything that will keep our domains, not
wider still and wider, but higher still and higher in the expectancy
and hope of quality and probity.''
   He could have been talking about his own career.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
