<FILEID>AP-NR-07-12-89 0033EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w AM-SecretService     07-12 0447</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Secret Service,430</SECOND>
<HEAD>White House Guard Accepts Watch, Denies Thefts</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Secret Service officer at the White House
said he accepted an $8,000 Rolex watch from a Washington lobbyist
who asked him to intervene in a drunken driving arrest, The
Washington Post reported.
   The Post, in Wednesday's editions, quoted Officer Ronald A.
deGueldre as saying that he accepted the watch from lobbyist Craig
J. Spence, who has been linked with an alleged homosexual
prostitution ring. The drunken driving arrest was made by the Secret
Service.
   DeGueldre said he ``talked to my superiors the next day and
informed them that this was a guy with a lot of clout. That's the
last I ever heard of it.'' The Post said court records showed that
two weeks later, district prosecutors dropped the charge of driving
under the influence.
   DeGueldre, reached by telephone Tuesday night by The Associated
Press, refused to comment and hung up on a reporter.
   The District of Columbia Office of Corporation Counsel said
Tuesday the case was dropped because it was ``without merit,'' but
would not give details, the Post said.
   The paper said deGueldre denied allegations contained in a sworn
statement by a Secret Service investigator that he admitted stealing
several pieces of the valuable Truman china collection from a pantry
in the White House living quarters, giving one piece to Spence and
several to members of deGueldre's family.
   The Secret Service said the officer admitted stealing two sets of
presidential cufflinks and tie tacks from the basement office of
Rose Zamaria, director of White House operations.
   The Post interviewed deGueldre, who denied committing any thefts
or doing favors for Spence. Spence has not responded to requests for
interviews, the newspaper said.
   Federal authorities are investigating Spence's relationship with
government employees, including the Secret Service officer. The
probe is tied to an investigation of possible credit card fraud by
an alleged homosexual prostitution service broken up by local and
federal agents in February.
   The Washington Times has reported that Spence was a client of the
prostitution service.
   In the Post interview, deGueldre said Spence telephoned him after
being arrested on Jan. 20, 1988, for alleged drunken driving. After
talking with his superiors, deGueldre said the charges against
Spence were dropped on Feb. 5, 1988, the day of his scheduled court
appearance.
   DeGueldre told the Post he took Spence and several friends on an
evening tour of the White House on the weekend of Independence Day
1988, and that same weekend, ``Spence said we should swap watches,
and I gave him my $22 Casio and he gave me the $8,000 Rolex. It was
a friendship thing, not to do anything for him.''
</TEXT>
