<FIRST>r a AM-OperationRescue 1stLd-Writethru a0407 07-12 0334</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Operation Rescue, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0407,0340</SECOND>
<HEAD>Anti-Abortion Leader Arrested At Promotional Appearance</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS grafs 4-5, with 2 grafs to CORRECT bond to $50,000, sted
$20,000, ADD other arrest warrant; picks up 6th graf, `Atlanta lawyer ...'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The founder of the anti-abortion group Operation
Rescue, which staged huge demonstrations at the Democratic National
Convention last summer, was arrested on charges stemming from the
protests.
   Randall Terry was arrested Monday after he finished an appearance
before the Christian Booksellers Association to promote his book
``Operation Rescue,'' an account of the group's history and mission.
   Operation Rescue spokesman Joseph Foreman said Terry was a
``political prisoner.'' The Binghamton, N.Y.-based group has
sponsored numerous demonstrations nationwide.
   Foreman said there were no plans to post the $50,000 bond to
release Terry, who was charged with one count of being party to a
crime and three counts of criminal trespass stemming from last
summer's Operation Rescue demonstrations outside Atlanta abortion
clinics.
   The bond was raised when he failed to appear for a court hearing
on the charges in February. Another arrest warrant containing the
same four charges was issued for Terry after that hearing.
   Atlanta lawyer Robert Fierer said that if Terry had had a court
date and he had been aware of it, he or somebody from his office
would have attended it.
   ``We were totally unaware of that,'' said Fierer, who no longer
represents Operation Rescue but said he has been in touch with Terry
since the arrest.
   Fierer, who represented the group after hundreds of its members
were arrested at the Democrats' convention last summer, said the
cases now involve 1,500 people and had ``become a tremendous
administrative nightmare for us.''
   Attorney, Jay Sekulow, who is handling Terry's case, said he,
too, was unaware of any outstanding warrants.
   Terry's wife, Cindy, said she and her husband knew he might be
arrested.
   ``It's a possibility in a lot of cities,'' she said. ``We don't
know why Atlanta would pick this time, this place.''
</TEXT>
