<FIRST>r a AM-NewOrleans-Abortion     07-12 0327</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-New Orleans-Abortion,0339</SECOND>
<HEAD>Abortion-Rights Advocates Protest Move to Revive Louisiana Law</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHEVEL JOHNSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pickets marched in front of District Attorney
Harry Connick's office Tuesday and the American Civil Liberties
Union promised to fight Connick's efforts to revive Louisiana's ban
on abortions.
   ``Louisiana is a major battleground,'' said Shirley Pedler,
director of the Louisiana ACLU chapter. ``It is the first state to
try to criminalize abortion, even without grounds to do so. Public
officials don't seem to be under the law.''
   Pedler spoke to reporters during a news conference at a New
Orleans abortion clinic.
   Earlier Tuesday, a half-dozen members of a New Orleans chapter of
the National Organization for Women marched in front of Connick's
office to protest his plans.
   Among the pickets was a 10-year-old girl wielding a large placard
reading: ``Harry, you oppressor.''
   Connick on Monday asked a federal district judge to lift a 1976
injunction against enforcement of a law making performing an
abortion a criminal offense.
   Under the law, a woman who undergoes an abortion is not liable
for punishment, only the person who performs the procedure.
   Judge Martin Feldman will hold a hearing on the matter Aug. 9.
   Connick said he had no plans to try to immediately enforce the
law.
   The Supreme Court's July 3 decision upholding Missouri
restrictions on abortion prompted Connick's action. Connick said the
decision leaves open the possibility that further restrictions could
be ruled legal.
   Connick said in a broadcast interview Tuesday he hoped his
actions would hasten a decision by the high court to uphold or
overturn the 1973 Roe vs. Wade case upholding a woman's right to
abortion.
   ``Why not find out where we stand instead of waiting for another
shoe to fall?'' Connick said.
   Pedler said the ACLU will argue at the Aug. 9 hearing that the
injunction barring enforcement of Louisiana's law should not be
lifted as long as Roe vs. Wade is intact.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
