<FIRST>r a AM-WoundedBaby     07-12 0286</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Wounded Baby,0293</SECOND>
<HEAD>Wounded Infant Born With Bullet In Chest</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MEMPHIS, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An infant was born with a bullet in her
chest after her mother was shot, but the child's most serious injury
was a broken rib and she was in stable condition Tuesday. Her mother
also was recovering.
   Despite breaking a rib, the small-caliber bullet lodged just
under the skin and did not damage internal organs, said Dee Denton,
a spokeswoman for Le Bonheur Children's Medical Center, where the
slug was removed.
   The baby's mother, Evelyn Page, 31, also was in stable condition
Tuesday at Regional Medical Center here. She was eight months
pregnant when shot by an unknown assailant Saturday. The baby was
delivered by Caesarean section.
   ``I knew my baby had been shot, the way my baby started moving in
me,'' she said. ``My baby started moving real fast. She kicked the
whole time. I knew that bullet had hit her.''
   ``What should I name her? Miracle Baby or what? That's what I was
thinking about, because she is a miracle baby,'' Ms. Page said.
   Ms. Page told police she was walking along a street early
Saturday when a man in a car stopped and told her to get in.
   ``I said, `You don't look right, I'm not getting in the car with
you,' and he reached down and pulled out a gun,'' she said. ``He
just shot me out of the clear sky.''
   She said the bullet went through her left arm and through her
side before hitting her fetus, but she was able to walk to a nearby
store and ask for help.
   ``I'm living. My baby's living. I thank the Lord it happened like
that,'' she said.
</TEXT>
