<DOCNO> AP890712-0026 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-12-89 0116EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-GayRights     07-12 0369</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Gay Rights,0380</SECOND>
<HEAD>Mass. Senate Approves Gay Rights Bill In Initial Vote</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN DIAMOND</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gay rights legislation was passed Tuesday in the
Massachusetts Senate, and advocates of homosexual rights said they
expect a tough fight when it comes up for final reading this fall.
   The legislation, approved 24-15, would ban discrimination against
gays and lesbians in housing, credit, employment and public
accommodations.
   ``This is the big vote we've been pushing for,'' said David
LaFontaine of the Coalition for Lesbian and Gay Civil Rights. ``This
is an overwhelming mandate from the Senate.''
   The bill still needs final Senate approval, and is expected to
come up for a vote this fall. It was passed by the House in March.
   The vote came with almost no debate. The chamber rejected three
amendments proposed by state Sen. Edward Kirby that would have
weakened the bill or included anti-gay language.
   ``We're only halfway there,'' said state Sen. Michael Barrett,
the bill's Senate sponsor. ``I anticipate a very tough fight in the
fall.''
   This year, as in past sessions, the legislation was stalled by
procedural tactics employed by its opponents. Kirby kept the
legislation off the Senate floor for weeks by proposing amendments,
then invoking a rule that requires at least a day's delay to allow
the amendment to be printed on the Senate calendar.
   But this week, Senate President William Bulger, who has not been
viewed as a supporter of the gay rights bill, pushed through a rules
suspension that prevented opponents from gaining time-consuming
delays.
   ``He deserves some credit for rising above his personal feelings
on this,'' LaFontaine said.
   Tuesday's vote sent the legislation to the Senate Committee on
Bills in Third Reading, a way station for legislation before final
debate. In 1987, committee rules were used to tie up the gay rights
bill in committee until the session expired.
   This year, committee Chairman William Q. MacLean said he would
refrain from using procedural moves to block the bill, even though
he voted against it.
   MacLean said 1989 may be the year the bill becomes law. ``Based
on the head count, you have to say it looks like there is a strong
possibility of it.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890712-0027 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-12-89 0116EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r e BC-Ballet     07-12 0421</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Ballet,0441</SECOND>
<HEAD>Kirov Dances `Sleeping Beauty'</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Will stand for PMs.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARY CAMPBELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A cast change moved the Kirov Ballet's Altynai
Asylmuratova from the Monday to the Tuesday ``The Sleeping Beauty,''
and the scramble was on for Tuesday tickets. Miss Asylmuratova is,
indeed, a glowing Princess Aurora.
   She's a lyrical dancer, whose dancing spins a long, lovely
phrase. She doesn't dance fast. Her balance is good _ Princess
Aurora constantly is being asked to balance _ but it isn't rock
solid.
   She looks like a human being capable of a catchable waver.
   The famous ``Rose Adagio'' ends with each of four suitors taking
the princess' hand and turning her in a circle. On Tuesday, at the
Metropolitan Opera, Miss Asylmuratova realized either that she
didn't have time or didn't have balance. She didn't turn for the
final suitor and he, catching on fast, dipped her into a position
that looked like an appropriate ending.
   She smiled dazzlingly at the prince in the last act wedding
scene. But earlier, while being courted by the four suitors, she
presented a ballerina instead of a girl on her 16th birthday.
   Konstantin Zaklinsky merits high praise for technique and
deportment as the prince.
   Lyubov Kunakova as the Lilac Fairy is a strong dancer, not at all
ethereal but since she's primarily the person in charge, it's
appropriate. The Lilac Fairy not only makes the princess sleep
instead of die from the evil fairy's curse and guides the prince to
her palace, but apparently she performs the wedding.
   The corps de ballet looked wonderful. It's a beautiful
production, with attractive costumes and old-master-style painted
backdrops giving an illusion of deep distance.
   The character dances at the wedding celebration don't include a
troupe of Russians in this Russian version. Albert Mirzoyan as
Puss-in-Boots had some amusing gestures flexing his paws at the tall
White Cat, Elvira Krylova.
   Andrei Garbuz and Yelena Pankova were deft and fast in the
Bluebird pas de deux, yet failed to excite. Maybe it was because
orchestral tempos, as conducted by Dzhemal Dalgat, kept fluctuating.
   Thus far in the engagement, the Kirov Ballet has been slightly
disappointing. This may be the fault of a viewer, from an inflated
memory of what one saw on its last visit 25 years ago, or from an
unreasonable desire to have each evening of ballet top the last one.
   ``The Sleeping Beauty,'' with choreography by Petipa and music by
Tchaikovsky, had its premiere in St. Petersburg in 1890.
</TEXT>
