<FIRST>r i PM-Britain-BAT     07-12 0456</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Britain-BAT,0470</SECOND>
<HEAD>RETRANSMITTING a0426 to change category code.</HEAD>
<HEAD>Analysts: Bidders Will Have to Raise BAT Offer to Succeed</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Similar version on financial wire.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By COTTEN TIMBERLAKE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Financier Sir James Goldsmith and fellow bidders
will have to raise their record-breaking $21 billion securities
offer for BAT Industries PLC and throw in some cash to succeed in
the hostile takeover attempt for the giant conglomerate, analysts
say.
   The highly leveraged offer, announced Tuesday, might be a move by
the bidders to beat the bushes for backers _ and for competing
bidders for the company, whose U.S. holdings include the Saks Fifth
Avenue stores and Brown and Williamson Tobacco Corp., one analyst
said.
   BAT's cigarette brands include Benson and Hedges, Kent and Kool.
   The acquisition would be the largest ever in Europe and the
second-biggest worldwide, eclipsed only by the $25 billion takeover
of RJR Nabisco Inc. by the New York investment firm Kohlberg Kravis
Roberts &amp; Co., which was completed earlier this year.
   The investment group, Hoylake Investments PLC, offered 850 pence,
the equivalent of $13.86, in debt instruments for each share of BAT,
Britain's third-largest company.
   Hoylake, which owns about 1.25 percent of the BAT's stock, said
it intends to break up London-based BAT, which has interests in
tobacco, financial services, retailing and paper.
   Hoylake also includes Australian entrepreneur Kerry Packer and
British investor Jacob Rothschild, a member of the famous banking
family.
   BAT, the world's biggest tobacco company, said it would fight the
bid, which it called ``an ill-conceived attempt at destructive
financial engineering.''
   ``This is just the opening shot,'' said Mike Simmonds, head of
British research at Yamaichi International Ltd.
   Charles Pick, an analyst with Nomura Research Institute, said,
``The offer in its present form hasn't got a hope of winning.''
   Bruce Davidson, an analyst with Smith New Court PLC, said, ``My
guess is that it has been launched to see if anyone else is going to
compete, or possibly to line up a cash alternative by feeling out
fund managers.''
   BAT shares finished well above the offered price Tuesday on
London's Stock Exchange, indicating that the market was expecting a
higher bid to emerge.
   BAT has diversified away from tobacco in recent years to reduce
its exposure to that sluggish business.
   Goldsmith said that by selling BAT's non-tobacco businesses he
intended to unlock ``shareholder value.'' Among the non-tobacco
units he would sell is Farmers Insurance Group Inc. of Los Angeles,
which BAT acquired for $5.2 billion in cash last year after a long
takeover fight.
   BAT's other subsidiaries include British-American Tobacco Co.
Ltd., BATUS Inc., Marshall Field and Co., Argos Distributors,
Appleton Papers Inc., Wiggins Teape Group, J.B. Ivey and Co. and
Eagle Star Holdings PLC.
</TEXT>
