<FIRST>r i PM-Hungary-Opposition     07-12 0564</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Hungary-Opposition,560</SECOND>
<HEAD>Hungarian Opposition Groups Seeking to Capitalize on Bush Visit</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Bush-Hungary Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KEVIN COSTELLOE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BUDAPEST, Hungary (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The anti-government opposition papers
crammed atop a tiny downtown cafe table symbolize a world of change
for a resistance movement trying to oust the communists from power.
   With President Bush in town today, nine opposition groups have
set up shop in the corner of the Spartacus Cafe.
   In contrast to other Soviet bloc nations, Hungary has been
relatively tolerant of dissidents. But such an open and public
display of resistance, such as the one in the cafe, would have been
unthinkable in Hungary just a few years ago.
   ``A year ago, we could have imagined being taken into custody,''
says Tibor Vidos, a labor union spokesman.
   Vidos says the nine opposition groups represent between 80,000
and 100,000 people mapping strategy for free elections planned for
next year.
   ``I hope the Bush visit will strengthen democratic rights,'' the
35-year-old Vidos says. ``It will show those in power the world is
watching what's happening in Hungary.''
   Vidos is the spokesman for the Democratic Trade Union of
Scientific Workers, which bills itself as ``the first free union to
be formed in Hungary.''
   He and representatives of the other political opposition groups
are openly chatting with foreign journalists in the Spartacus Cafe,
named for a Roman gladiator who led a dramatic slaves' revolt in 72
B.C. The cafe is located two blocks from the U.S. Embassy.
   On the sultry eve of Bush's arrival, the late Roy Orbison's
classic song, ``Pretty Woman,'' is blaring from the cafe's souped-up
sound system. Soft drink bottles perch precariously on the cafe
table jammed with opposition literature espousing the heady goals of
breaking the last of the Communist Party grip on the country.
   ``We have no doubt that the vast majority of people have had
enough of this regime,'' says Geza Jeszenszky of the Hungarian
Democratic Forum.
   Jeszenszky, 47, describing his group as a patriotic movement
aimed at reaching out to the poor and those in rural areas, says
such an information center would not have been possible a year ago.
   ``On the surface, they (the Communists) really have changed their
spots,'' the Hungarian Democratic Forum spokesman says, adding he
hopes the changed attitudes also go much deeper.
   Aiding the opposition force is the reform mood within the
Communist Party itself, as well as the occasional divisions that
also are weakening the once iron-solid party grip on Hungary.
   The blunt tone of the material handed out at the Opposition
Information Center pushes freedom of expression to new limits in
Hungary.
   ``HDF (Hungarian Democratic Forum) aims at relieving people from
the remnants of Stalinist tyranny, and letting the rebirth of the
nation happen without disaster,'' says the forum's English-language
pamphlet.
   The Federation of Young Democrats' pamphlet, also in English,
condemns ``dictatorial, totalitarian regimes, which are also hotbeds
of national oppression.''
   Federation spokesman Miklos Sukosd says opposition leaders are
counting on the proximity to the U.S. Embassy for ``symbolic
support.''
   Sukosd, 28, who said he was a graduate student in sociology at
Harvard University, says the opposition groups would like to delay
the elections by a few months to give them more time to campaign.
   ``The Communist Party popularity is falling very fast,'' said
Sukosd, who like the other opposition representatives spoke to The
Associated Press at the Spartacus Cafe.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
