<FIRST>r a PM-Nielsens     07-12 0410</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Nielsens,0427</SECOND>
<HEAD>`Totally Hidden Video' Gets High Rating, But ...</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JERRY BUCK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Television Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Picture this hidden camera shot: ``Totally
Hidden Video'' made an unusually strong debut in the A.C. Nielsen
Co. ratings for a Fox Broadcasting show.
   The twist: Fox had to make last-minute substitutions when it was
learned three segments used actors instead of unsuspecting people
caught by hidden cameras, and Allen Funt said in a lawsuit the show
was using some stunts from his ``Candid Camera.''
   And a producer was fired.
   ``Totally Hidden Video'' tied for 21st place in last week's
Nielsen ratings. Fox's ``Married...With Children,'' usually its
highest-ranked show, increased its showing for a tie for 29th place.
   NBC, led by ``Cheers,'' dominated the top 10 and won the week for
its 55th consecutive victory.
   Fox substituted part of Sunday's premiere show because actors
were used in three segments that were supposed to show the reactions
of people caught unaware by a hidden camera. Funt has sued Quantum
Media Inc., alleging the show uses stunts from his 43 years of
``Candid Camera.''
   The studio denies the allegations, but said it fired a producer
it did not identify.
   ``The producer failed to follow the show's guidelines requiring
that all targeted individuals were to be totally unaware a camera
was present and have no prior knowledge of the setups,'' Quantum
Media said in a statement.
   ``Totally Hidden Video'' got a 10.5 rating and ``Married...With
Children'' got 10.0. ``Married...With Children'' has been in the
mid-40s in the rankings and had ratings of 8.6 or lower.
   NBC won the week with an average prime-time rating of 10.1. ABC
had 8.8 and CBS 8.4.
   For the season to date, NBC leads with 15.1 to ABC's 12.1 and
CBS' 12.0. Each rating point measures the percentage of the
estimated 90.4 million U.S. homes with televisions.
   Here is the top 10: NBC's ``Cheers,'' ``Dear John,'' ``The Cosby
Show,'' ``A Different World,'' CBS' ``Murder, She Wrote,'' ``60
Minutes,'' NBC's ``L.A. Law,'' ABC's ``20-20,'' NBC's ``The Golden
Girls,'' and a tie between ``Unsolved Mysteries'' and ``Night
Court.''
   The NBC summer series, ``Knight and Daye,'' made its debut in
16th place.
   ABC's ``Roseanne,'' tied with ``Cheers'' for first last week,
fell to 13th place because of competition from Fourth of July
fireworks.
   CBS had the top-rated evening news show with a rating of 8.5.
ABC, tied for first with CBS last week, was second with 8.1. NBC had
7.9.
</TEXT>
