<DOCNO> AP890712-0033 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-12-89 0126EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-North     07-12 0331</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-North,330</SECOND>
<HEAD>North Appeals Iran-Contra Conviction</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETE YOST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Oliver North, who is appealing his conviction
in the Iran-Contra scandal, won't have to pay his $150,000 fine
until the appeal is decided.
   However, North said Tuesday he does not want to put off the two
years of probation and 1,200 hours of community service that U.S.
District Court Judge Gerhard A. Gesell imposed instead of a prison
term at North's sentencing last week.
   North said in a one-sentence notice that he is taking his
conviction and sentence to the U.S. Court of Appeals and requested a
stay in his fine. Gesell granted the delay in the fine until the
case is resolved.
   In a separate filing, North's lawyers said he ``does not seek a
stay of the sentence of probation conditioned on community service.
He would like to begin promptly the important community service
program ordered by the court.''
   They said the next six to 12 months are ``a critical `start up'
period during which the program could best use the assistance'' of
North. He was ordered to help administer a new program to help
District of Columbia youths living in public housing avoid getting
involved with drugs.
   ``We submit that a stay of payment of the fines would be
appropriate in light of the significant issues that Lt. Col. North
intends to raise on appeal,'' his lawyers concluded.
   Prosecutors said they won't oppose a delay of the fine during the
appeal.
   Gesell, who could have sentenced North to 10 years in prison and
$750,000 in fines, decided not to order any prison time for the
former National Security Council aide. The judge said time behind
bars would only ``harden your misconceptions'' about public service
and increase North's feelings of martyrdom.
   North was convicted May 4 of aiding and abetting an obstruction
of Congress, altering and destroying classified National Security
Council documents and accepting an illegal gratuity. He was
acquitted on nine other charges.
</TEXT>
