<FIRST>r w PM-NuclearDump     07-12 0593</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Nuclear Dump,580</SECOND>
<HEAD>Regulators Say Nuclear Dump Site Planning is Flawed</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT BURNS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Federal officials may not be paying enough
attention to the risk of geologic faults and volcanic activity near
a proposed Nevada site for a high-level nuclear waste dump, a
Nuclear Regulatory Commission member says.
   The NRC also said Tuesday the Energy Department's formula for
evaluating the desert site is flawed in at least two important ways.
   Kenneth Rogers, a member of the commission, questioned whether
the department was giving enough attention to ``killer issues'' that
could disqualify the site, such as whether geologic faults or
volcanic activity in the area could destabilize the underground
repository.
   ``I wonder whether that's getting as much attention as it
should,'' Rogers said.
   The commission on Tuesday published key parts of its review of
the Energy Department plan for assessing whether Yucca Mountain,
about 100 miles northwest of Las Vegas, could safely store tons of
radioactive nuclear waste for 10,000 years.
   The final NRC assessment is to be published July 28.
   The Nevada state government is strongly opposed to the waste dump
for safety and public health reasons. Gov. Bob Miller recently
signed a bill passed by the legislature prohibiting storage of
high-level radioactive waste in Nevada.
   Technical experts who conducted the NRC review told the
commission the Energy Department has made many improvements in its
plan since last year, but that it has not yet resolved at least two
significant issues.
   The objections are that the department's plan does not include an
adequate means of assuring the quality of the technical data
collected, and that the design of an experimental shaft to be
drilled on the site may be flawed, said Robert Bernero, director of
the NRC's office of nuclear materials safety and safeguards.
   Bernero said the department could go ahead with its site
assessment without NRC approval of the plan, but it could face the
same objections later when it sought licenses from the commission to
operate the dump, he said.
   Initial construction work is scheduled for November, and the
Energy Department is to decide by 1994 whether the site is suitable.
It would then have to apply to the NRC for an operating license.
Under the present timetable, nuclear waste would start moving into
the site in 2003.
   Dade Moeller, chairman of an NRC advisory committee that also has
reviewed the Energy Department plan, said department officials told
him they believed any problems that could disqualify the site would
``just pop out'' during the site evaluation.
   Bernero also said the NRC is concerned that the project timetable
is putting the Energy Department under too much deadline pressure.
   Bernero also disclosed that Samuel Rousso, the head of the
department's waste management program, complained in a June 28
letter that the NRC was nitpicking on the Yucca Mountain project and
causing unnecessary delays.
   ``We are frequently devoting time to repeatedly addressing
matters that could be more productively evaluated'' by beginning the
on-site evaluation work, Rousso's letter said. A copy of the letter
was made available by the NRC.
   In a related development, the Energy Department's field office in
Las Vegas said it ordered Sandia National Laboratories, a major
contractor on the Yucca Mountain project, to stop work Monday until
it corrects a technical flaw in its quality-control program.
   Derek Scammell, a department spokesman in Las Vegas, said Sandia
is expected to fix the problem by Aug. 4 and that the work stoppage
will not affect the overall schedule for completing the assessment
of the mountain site.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890712-0035 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-12-89 0129EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-ThirdWorldWomen     07-12 0414</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Third World Women,410</SECOND>
<HEAD>Special Health Needs Cited for Third World Women</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CARL HARTMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Women in the Third World need special health
care that goes far beyond the childbearing needs that medical
providers pay attention to, according to an international study.
   The women's problems, stemming from the large amount of work they
perform, are made worse by the lack of professional health care,
according to the report, ``Strengthening Women: Health Research
Priorities for Women in Developing Countries.''
   The study said medical attention for women in the Third World is
focused almost entirely on childbearing.
   A.W. Patterson, director of the Caribbean Food and Nutrition
Institute in Jamaica, said that in the Third World one of every four
deaths of young women _ in some countries one out of every two _ is
related to pregnancy and childbirth.
   But ``we don't need the infant-health rationale for attention to
be focused on women's health,'' said Allan Rosenfield, dean of the
School of Public Health at Columbia University.
   The women suffer malnutrition, diabetes, high blood pressure and
other physical problems far more frequently than women in developed
nations, the report released Tuesday said.
   ``Women's ... responsibilities in developing countries include
obtaining water, producing and preparing food and gathering
firewood, all without benefit of modern appliances,'' the report
said.
   ``Women farmers grow at least 50 percent of the world's food ...
Women's low earnings, poverty and often sole responsibility for
maintaining households add to the burdens of their dual home and
market roles because women must work longer hours to earn even a
minimally acceptable level of income.''
   Heavy work can lead to special leg and back problems. The Third
World women are exposed to water-borne diseases because they are
generally responsible for getting water from communal sources.
   Women in the Third World also suffer from malnutrition due to
lack of proteins and from anemia and other diseases caused by a lack
of iron, the report said. Older women have more diabetes and
possibly more high blood pressure than their counterparts in
wealthier nations.
   The study pointed out that many women in Third World countries do
not know how to get medical attention and often lack the time, money
and transportation to get it.
   It called for more research that distinguishes results by gender,
by geographical region and which takes social and cultural facts
into consideration.
   The report was prepared by researchers from the United States,
India, Jamaica, Zaire and Chile.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
