<FIRST>r w PM-Hastings     07-12 0589</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Hastings,580</SECOND>
<HEAD>Shadowy Figure Takes Witness Stand at Impeachment Trial</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIKE ROBINSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Senators gathering evidence against Judge Alcee
L. Hastings are weighing testimony from a shadowy figure with
underworld ties who answered questions behind closed doors and then
vanished out a rear exit.
   ``He is an elusive figure who can only be located through the
FBI,'' Rep. John Bryant, D-Texas, told reporters after informant
William Dredge finished testifying at the Hastings impeachment trial.
   Hastings, the first black federal judge in Florida history, is
accused of conspiracy to obtain a $150,000 bribe, lying about it to
a jury that acquitted him in 1983 and improper disclosure of wiretap
information.
   Impeached by the House a year ago, Hastings is now on trial in
the Senate. If convicted he would be removed from the bench and
deprived of his $89,500 annual judicial salary.
   Testimony from Dredge at a panel hearing evidence on the case
came as Hastings lost a battle Tuesday to get a Supreme Court order
halting the proceedings.
   Justice Byron R. White, without comment, denied the request to
halt the proceedings while the U.S. Court of Appeals makes a
decision on Hastings' claims that the impeachment trial is
unconstitutional.
   Bryant and other House members are serving as prosecutors as the
Senate panel collects evidence, which will be presented to the full
Senate before it votes on Hastings ouster.
   Police guarded hearing room doors and a television cameras were
ordered off as Dredge was brought in to testify. Bryant said he
feared for his life because he had been a witness for the government
in a trial involving top organized crime hoodlums.
   Bryant, who is acting as chief prosecutor in the Hastings case,
acknowledged Dredge was less than an ideal witness.
   ``Everyone involved in this knew that Dredge had a lengthy
criminal record spanning his entire adult life,'' Bryant said
afterward. He said efforts to remove Hastings from the bench do not
hinge on the Dredge's credibility and that the key points are
corroborated by other witnesses.
   Hastings attorney Terence Anderson discounted the testimony,
saying he had zeroed in on Dredge's background.
   ``On cross examination, I think I showed up the slippery little
worm,'' Anderson boasted after Dredge had been escorted out a rear
exit.
   Bryant said Dredge's testimony was intended to show the senators
there was nothing unusual in building the Hastings case.
   Prosecutors say Dredge was sent by Washington attorney William
Borders to solicit a $150,000 bribe in exchange for Hastings'
keeping two brothers, Frank and Thomas Romano, out of prison.
   The Romano brothers, both now dead, had been sentenced by
Hastings to three years each following a racketeering conviction
involving a loan from a Teamsters Union pension fund.
   Dredge, facing trial on charges of plotting to distribute
quaalude tablets, became an informant against Borders, who
eventually went to prison.
   Dredge retold the story in detail in his five hours before the
committee, attorneys and lawmakers said.
   During a lunchtime break, Hastings told reporters outside the
hearing room that Dredge was ``an incredible liar.''
   ``Quite frankly, I don't like him,'' Hastings said. ``Never did,
never will.'' He said Dredge's testimony ``has been carefully
rehearsed and gone over repeatedly.''
   Meanwhile, House members were blocked from asking Miami criminal
lawyer Neal Sonnett about a telephone conversation between the
Romano brothers and an associate, Phillip Moscato, in which they
allegedly discussed whether someone could intervene in the Romanos'
legal troubles.
   The Senate panel's chairman, Sen. Jeff Bingaman, D-N.M., said
Sonnett's testimony would be hearsay.
</TEXT>
