<SECOND>PM-Hecht-Bahamas,500</SECOND>
<HEAD>Hecht Confirmed as Ambassador to Bahamas</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAWRENCE L. KNUTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former Sen. Chic Hecht is headed to the
Bahamas, winning confirmation as U.S. ambassador despite complaints
from some of his former colleagues that he's unfit to serve as point
man in the war on drugs.
   The Senate voted 78-19 on Tuesday to confirm the Nevada
Republican and keep alive the tradition that the Senate rarely
rejects a former member seeking confirmation to an executive branch
post.
   The vote came after Hecht's defenders declared he was fully
qualified by his experience in business, banking and government to
handle an ambassadorship.
   But Hecht's detractors pointed to his remarks that he was looking
forward to his appointment because the Bahamas offered gambling
casinos, good golf and fishing.
   ``An appointment of an ambassador is not a vacation trip,'' said
Sen. John Breaux, D-La.
   Sen. Bob Graham, D-Fla., who led the fight against the
nomination, said that while Hecht might serve with distinction in
other posts, he is not qualified to serve as ``a key operational
officer in the war against drugs.''
   ``He does not deserve, nor does our nation deserve to be
represented by him in the Bahamas,'' Graham said.
   Graham said the Bahamas has risen to a high state of importance
in the drug war because of its history as a shipping point for
cocaine and other narcotics and because its banks have been used to
launder illicit drug profits.
   Sen. Paul Sarbanes, D-Md., said Hecht is representative of the
high percentage of Republican stalwarts and fundraisers being named
by President Bush to diplomatic posts.
   The chief qualification of most of them is loyalty to Bush, said
Sarbanes, who called them ``political throwaways.''
   Graham and other senators said the Bahamas had become too
important in the war against drugs to entrust the post to anyone who
is less than a fully competent and professional ambassador.
   Hecht, 60, whose one term in the Senate was marked by such
malapropisms as his vow not to permit a ``nuclear suppository'' to
be located in his state, had told the Senate Foreign Relations
Committee he would feel at home in the Bahamas because of its
similarities to Las Vegas.
   ``I've been involved in gambling in Nevada, and I've been
involved in banking for 25 years,'' Hecht said. ``Also, I understand
it is a nice lifestyle. I love golf and they have a lot of nice golf
courses and good fishing.''
   Sen. Harry Reid, D-Nev., said Hecht made those comments in jest.
   Another defender, Sen. Jesse Helms, R-N.C., said Hecht was trying
to say that both the Bahamas and Las Vegas have multimillion-dollar
tourist industries of great importance to their economies.
   ``It is not something to be twisted and misrepresented and
hee-hawed by journalistic pygmies in the news media,'' Helms said,
contending that Hecht has been attacked only because of his record
as a conservative.
   ``Chic is a remarkable man,'' Helms said. ``He is probably the
brightest man to serve in the Senate.''
</TEXT>
