<FILEID>AP-NR-07-12-89 0153EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Vacations     07-12 0450</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Vacations,0463</SECOND>
<HEAD>Europeans Have Most Paid Time Off, Americans and Japanese Least</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CLARE NULLIS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GENEVA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Workers in Western Europe have bargained their way
to the longest annual paid vacations, while Americans have the
shortest vacations and the Japanese have to be persuaded to take
time off, an International Labor Organization report says.
   The study published Tuesday says legislation and collective
bargaining have lengthened vacations in Europe, but there is little
movement in this direction in the United States.
   In West Germany, nearly two-thirds of the workforce get six weeks
paid leave each year under deals struck by employers and unions,
even though the legal entitlement is only three weeks. Ten years
ago, nobody in the country had six weeks paid holiday.
   In France, Sweden, Belgium and Luxembourg, collective bargaining
often boosts the statutory five-week leave by another week, the
report says.
   In legal terms, Spain has made the most progress, increasing paid
leave from one to five weeks over the last 25 years.
   Italian workers are frequently given six weeks annual leave,
while most British employees enjoy at least four weeks paid
vacation, even though neither country has laws on holiday rights.
   However, collective bargaining in the United States has not had
the same results. There are no laws on holiday entitlement and time
off depends on the length of service with an employer, the report
notes.
   It cites a U.S. government survey showing that, on average,
employees who had worked for a company for one year got less than
nine days paid holiday. This rose to nearly 23 days after 30 years
with the same company.
   ``But not many people in the United States stay in the same place
for 30 years,'' said Joseph Thurman, an expert on working hours at
the ILO.
   He said cultural differences and lack of pressure to increase
holiday time are among the reasons for the United States lagging
behind Western European countries.
   ``If you told an American that a West German got six weeks
holiday, he would be astounded. Similarly, a West German would be
amazed that anyone could make do with two weeks paid leave a year,''
Thurman said in an interview.
   Although Japan cut working hours last year, he said, the Japanese
are proving reluctant to take advantage of their increased leisure
time.
   Thurman said most Japanese workers take only half their yearly
allowance of 10 days leave. But the 17 to 18 days of public holidays
in Japan compare favorably with eight days in Britain and
Switzerland, he added.
   Thurman noted that Japan's Ministry of Labor had set up a special
Leisure Development Center to persuade people to take their full
holiday entitlement.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890712-0043 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-12-89 0156EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-CleanAir     07-12 0588</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Clean Air,600</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush Clean Air Draft Would Weaken Initiative, Environmentalists Say</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LARRY MARGASAK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Bush administration draft of clean air
legislation substantially backs off from his promise to
``dramatically accelerate'' pollution reduction by the year 2000,
say a House panel chairman and an environmental spokesman.
   ``We've got to hope people in the Environmental Protection Agency
can turn this around,'' Rep. Henry Waxman, chairman of the House
Energy and Commerce environment subcommittee, said Tuesday after
seeing the draft language.
   The Office of Management and Budget draft, also obtained by The
Associated Press, was dated June 30 and warned at the top of each
page, ``all provisions subject to change. Do not distribute, quote
or cite.''
   A spokesman for the Environmental Protection Agency denied
Tuesday night that the president's proposals had been significantly
weakened.
   Bush and congressional leaders have placed a new clean air bill
near the top of their legislative agenda for the remainder of this
year.
   Bush outlined his proposal June 12 but has not yet sent Congress
the legislation to implement his plan. A White House fact sheet
distributed after the announcement promised the plan ``will
dramatically accelerate the pace of pollution reduction and put
America on the path toward markedly cleaner air by the end of the
century.''
   The legislation is expected to be sent to Congress in about two
weeks.
   ``I'm very disappointed to hear the direction the administration
seems to be taking,'' said Waxman, a California Democrat.
   Among the provisions criticized by Waxman and others is a
proposed switch in auto emissions standards from an emissions
ceiling that each car must meet to a fleet-wide average, a change
long advocated by the auto industry.
   The draft would give the EPA administrator authority ``to
demonstrate compliance with ... emissions standards through intra-or
inter-manufacturer averaging of emissions of vehicle or engine
families.''
   Last month Bush said he would propose reducing the exhaust
standard for unburned fuel from 0.41 grams per mile to 0.25 grams
per mile, the limit currently in effect for California.
   But to account for manufacturing variations, automakers already
must build cars that average somewhat below 0.41 grams, so it is not
clear what an average of 0.25 grams would mean. Waxman said the
proposal could mean no reduction in actual emissions.
   Richard Ayres, staff attorney for the Natural Resources Defense
Council and chairman of the National Clean Air Coalition, the major
lobbying organization of environmental groups on clean air
questions, said the auto fleet average provisions would be a major
retreat from current law.
   The president said he wanted to require industrial emitters of
toxic air pollutants to use the ``best available'' technology to
control pollution.
   The bill draft, however, would permit EPA to take into account
not only the risks to public health, but also ``the cost and
technical feasibility'' for industry in ordering reductions of
toxics.
   ``They're talking about the cost-benefit system rather than
setting a health standard. There is the potential to say it's not
worth the cost'' of emission reductions, Waxman said. ``No one
figures the economic cost of cancer and other health care costs.''
   Christian Rice, spokesman for EPA, said, ``There isn't any loss
for Bush's proposals.''
   Top EPA officials ``are saying we've won major victories in the
inter-agency process,'' Rice said. He said consideration of cost in
controlling toxic air pollution was envisioned all along in the
president's plan.
   The switch to an average auto emissions standard would still mean
``you'd get some reduction in emissions,'' he said.
</TEXT>
