<HEAD>Helicopters Crash Over Gulf, Pilots Missing</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: UPDATES throughout with two pilots presumed dead, search called
off, Alabama crash; no pickup.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GALVESTON, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two commercial helicopters collided off
Galveston Island and crashed in shallow waters Tuesday, and each
aircraft's pilot was presumed dead, the Coast Guard said.
   In Alabama, a military helicopter crashed and burned, injuring
two crewmen, the Army said.
   The Coast Guard called off its search late Tuesday after human
remains were found two miles south of Galveston Island, officials
said.
   Searchers also found floating wreckage and debris on the beach
along the island's west side, said Coast Guard Petty Officer Ron
Chadwick.
   The crash occurred around 4:30 p.m. in waters about 25 feet deep,
officials said. There were no witnesses.
   The Galveston airport reported losing radio communications with
the helicopters, which were apparently used to ferry crews to
offshore drilling sites, said Coast Guard Lt. Scott LaRochelle.
   The names of the two pilots, who were alone in their aircraft,
were being withheld pending notification of relatives, said Chadwick.
   A Coast Guard helicopter and patrol boat took part in the search,
said LaRochelle.
   One of the helicopters, a Bell 206-L1, was owned by Air Logistics
Inc. of New Iberia La. The other was identified as an Aerospatiale
AS-350 owned by Petroleum Helicopters Inc. of Lafayette, La.,
company officials said.
   In southeastern Alabama, a UH-1H Huey helicopter from Fort Rucker
crashed Tuesday morning as it attempted to land at staging field
near Louisville after becoming sluggish, said Army Master Sgt. David
Malone.
   The two crewmen were in fair condition with back injuries at
Lyster U.S. Army Community Hospital, said Fort Rucker spokesman Jim
Kelley.
   The aircraft made an unusual sound before crashing, Malone said.
He said it was unclear whether the $250,000 aircraft caught fire
before hitting the ground or after.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
