<FIRST>r a PM-EagletBanding     07-12 0480</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Eaglet Banding,0493</SECOND>
<HEAD>Eaglet is Banded in Program to Restore Endangered Species</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIKE RECHT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ERROL, N.H. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A conservationist climbed 71 feet up a white
pine tree and placed an identification band on an eaglet while the
new father swooped overhead.
   To Peter Nye, who has banded several hundred eagles, Tuesday's
job proved mostly routine. But it was an exciting moment for New
Hampshire environmentalists in their long attempt to bring
endangered bald eagles back to the state.
   On April 14, they celebrated the discovery of an egg. The chick
hatched about five weeks later, but on June 13 it was determined the
eaglet had died.
   That's when the plan was hatched to bring in a foster chick, born
in captivity at a Syracuse, N.Y., zoo, to see if the grieving
parents would accept a substitute.
   Three days later, the 27-day-old chick was put in the nest on the
Magalloway River near Umbagog Lake on the Maine border. By day's
end, the parents had accepted the chick.
   That's when the call went out to Nye, head of New York's
Department of Environmental Conservation's Endangered Species Unit.
   With biologists and others looking on anxiously from a nearby
island, Nye went about his task. He called it unusual for the male
to swoop overhead that close, but he was unperturbed.
   ``I didn't pay much attention to him,'' he said, ``I felt pretty
safe because I had a lot of branches protecting me.''
   After photographing the chick, he took one leg of the eaglet,
which he said tried to hit him with its wings. ``Once I got a hold
of her, she was real quiet,'' he said.
   He placed a band on each leg to enable environmentalists to study
the eagle's movements. Coincidentally, five years ago Nye had banded
the father, who had migrated from New York, the farthest Nye knows
one of his birds has traveled to nest.
   The eagle ``is something we've really done a bad deed to,'' he
said, ``and it's good to be part of something to bring them back.''
   Chemical sprays, such as DDT, crept into the wildlife food chain
after World War II and helped make eagles an endangered species.
   Nye's program has helped restore them in New York. Maine has
about 100 pairs. Alaska has the most eagles. Some also can be found
in Florida, Pacific Northwest, Great Lakes and Chesapeake Bay.
   ``We have no control over where they go,'' said Carol Foss of the
Audubon Society of New Hampshire. ``We do our best to protect them
when they come back. If all goes well, 10 or 15 years from now, we
might have 10 or 15 eagle pairs.''
   But for now, the next step is the first week in August when the
eaglet is expected to take flight for the first time. Then she will
be on her own.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
