<DOCNO> AP890712-0046 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-12-89 0211EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-Lites     07-12 0622</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Lites,0642</SECOND>
<HEAD>On the Light Side</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JUNEAU, Alaska (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Take a lump of beef fat, spike it with a
dash of lithium chloride, top it off with a whiff of Pine Sol and
you've got a sickening recipe.
   So sickening that state biologists hope it will keep scavenging
bears away from Juneau's garbage cans.
   The state Department of Fish and Game is stuffing fat chunks with
lithium chloride or thiabendazole, which when digested cause
vomiting and diarrhea. The chunks are tied to strips of flannel
soaked in Pine Sol, a pine-scented cleaner, and placed along bear
trails in forests and in garbage cans on the edge of town.
   Biologists hope the bears will associate the odor of Pine Sol
with food that makes them retch. If the experiment works, deterring
bears from garbage dining could be as easy as spraying trash cans
with pine cleaner.
   ``The idea is to make these bears hate being around people. The
faster we can do that, the better,'' says state biologist Roger
Seavoy. He says the chemical deterrents are not permanently harmful
to the bears.
   It's too early to determine if the experiment is working, but
Seavoy says there are signs that bears sickened by the tainted
snacks are choosing to dine elsewhere.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>LUCK, Wis. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Beef lovers are in Luck.
   Or at least that's what the advertisements might say. This small
western Wisconsin community was chosen as the setting for a
television commercial to promote red meat, and the locals have no
beef with that.
   ``Nothing ever happens in little Luck,'' said Mary Peterson, an
employee in the clerk's office for the village of about 1,000
residents. ``This is real exciting.''
   Luck was one of four small communities selected by the Beef
Industry Foundation as part of a ``real food for real people''
advertising campaign. The ads will be a switch from the recent
campaign featuring celebrities such as actors James Garner and
Cybill Shepherd and basketball star Larry Bird.
   ``The whole idea of our campaign is that we want to use real
people in real cities that have interesting names,'' said Jeanne
Sowa, advertising vice president for the Beef Industry Council.
   The comercials will feature Manhattan, Mont., where people are
supposed to respect good taste; Utopia, Texas, where they are said
to feel good after eating beef; and Yale, Wash., where they
supposedly are sophisticated enough to appreciate nutrition.
   You might have guessed the script for the Luck ad. ``Where would
we be without beef?'' a narrator asks. ``Out of luck.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Club goers hoping to party 'til dawn can come
a little closer to their goal thanks to a court ruling giving
discotheque patrons an extra half-hour to imbibe after ``last call.''
   In a 6-1 decision Tuesday, the state Court of Appeals ruled that
New York City's Cabaret Law requiring such establishments to close
from 4 a.m. to 8 a.m. conflicted with a state law allowing bar
patrons to continue to consume alcoholic beverages until 4:30 a.m.
   While the court noted the law also prohibits the sale of
alcoholic beverages between 4 a.m. and 8 a.m., it said the law
permits bars to stay open until 4:30 a.m. so patrons can finish
their drinks.
   The court ruled in a case brought by the owner of The Limelight,
a disco located in a former Manhattan church. Owner Peter Gatien got
upset over a $100 fine and pursued his case to the state's highest
court, said a lawyer for the popular nightspot.
   Stuart Byron, the chief lawyer for Gatien, said that by having a
simultaneous closing time and cutoff of drink sales, ``you almost
compel people to chug-a-lug.'' That could lead to more drunken
driving, he said.
</TEXT>
