<FIRST>r i PM-Korea     07-12 0558</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Korea,0574</SECOND>
<HEAD>Agents Raid Newspaper, Confiscate Evidence of Lawmaker's North Korean
Trip</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By M.H. AHN ^Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Intelligence agents charged into a
leading dissident newspaper today and confiscated pictures and
notepaper as evidence of a lawmaker's illegal trip to North Korea.
   About 40 intelligence agents and 100 plainclothes police wearing
helmets forced their way through the locked gates of the dissident
Hankyoreh newspaper as reporters shouting ``We refuse to be
searched!'' tried to block them.
   More than 1,000 riot troopers in combat fatigues circled the
newspaper compound. Police, apparently fearing a suicide attempt in
protest of their raid, laid out safety mattresses around the
building and a firetruck stood by.
   About 30 protesting reporters, many wearing headbands and
shouting slogans, were taken away by police and kept in a police van
until the 20-minute search was completed. They were released
afterwards.
   ``The surprise search at dawn of the newspaper's editorial room
is unprecedented and is never tolerable. We will continue our
struggle to win a free and independent press freedom in solidarity
with journalists at home and abroad,'' said Hankyoreh president and
publisher Song Kon-ho.
   The Agency for National Security Planning obtained a search
warrant on Monday demanding pictures and other material pertaining
to the illegal visit to communist North Korea by National
Assemblyman Suh Kyung-won.
   Reporters staged a two-day sit-in and the newspaper refused to
allow agents in the newsroom, claiming it was an infrigement on the
free press.
   Suh turned himself into authorities June 25 and was arrested
three days later and charged with national security violations for
his August 1988 trip.
   An arrest warrant has been issued for Hankyoreh reporter Yun
Chae-gol but action was delayed because Yun was hospitalized.
   Yun and nine other persons in jail were charged with failing to
report Suh's illegal trip to authorities, a crime in South Korea.
   Reporter Yun allegedly learned of Suh's trip while accompanying
leading opposition leader Kim Dae-jung, head of the Party for Peace
and Democracy, on a tour of Europe in February. Suh was on the trip
as a party lawmaker.
   Authorities said Suh approached the reporter, suggesting a story,
but changed his mind later and the story was never written. Party
leader Kim has said he had no prior knowledge of the trip.
   Reporters at the newspaper said intelligence agents arrived at
the gate to the newspaper compound at 7 a.m. and when protesters
refused to let them in, they forced open the gate with hammers.
   Witnesses said the agents and police raced to the second-floor
editorial room, forced open a glass door and with the help of a
homemade map found reporter Yun's desk and files.
   Hankyoreh reporters said the agents took 23 photographs, some
allegedly taken in North Korea, and some sheets of pink memo paper
with a North Korean letterhead. They looked at, but did not take,
the reporter's notebook on his interview with Suh.
   One agent was quoted as saying, ``We return reporter Yun's
notebook in the spirit of protecting sources.''
   The state-run Korean Broadcasting System said investigators also
took a draft of a report Suh allegedly made to North Korean leader
Kim Il Sung.
   Chairman Chang Yun-hwan of the paper's editorial comittee and
another ranking member of the paper offered to resign to take moral
responsibility for the action against the paper.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
