<HEAD>Dangerous Dolls Seized</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A total of 53,000 imported dolls that could be
dangerous to children were seized in a New York warehouse, according
to the Consumer Product Safety Commission.
   The dolls, sold by mail order retailers as the ``Dress Me Clown''
at $5 or $6 each, were imported by Etna Worldwide Corp. of New York
and were sold as the ``Dress Me Clown'' at $5 or $6 each. The CPSC
said children could choke on buckles, buttons or other pieces.
   The dolls had been returned by a retailer to Etna, which failed
to assure the commission that the dolls would not be resold, the
CPSC said.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>Pickens: Japanese Keep Corporate Affairs Closed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Japanese don't want corporate raider T.
Boone Pickens Jr. to own a company there because they don't want
their closed economy exposed, according to Pickens.
   The millionaire raider recently paid $800 million for a 20.2
percent stake in Koito Manufacturing Co., an automobile lighting
company. But two weeks ago, he was rejected when he sought he sought
three seats on Koito's 20-member board.
   Pickens told a Senate committee Tuesday he isn't a threat to
Koito management because he can easily be outvoted. ``They must want
to exclude me so that an American won't see how their cartel works.
They don't want their system exposed for what it is.''
   Pickens said he supports a bill that would require foreign
investors to register with the Department of Commerce when they
purchase more than a 5 percent stake in a U.S. company or real
estate valued at more than $5 million.
</TEXT>
