<FILEID>AP-NR-07-12-89 0239EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-Dukakis-FiscalMess Bjt   07-12 0735</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Dukakis-Fiscal Mess, Bjt,0755</SECOND>
<HEAD>Massachusetts Faces `Deep and Painful Cuts'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DUNCAN MANSFIELD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   After pitching his role in the ``Massachusetts
Miracle'' during his presidential campaign, Gov. Michael S. Dukakis
is winding down his final term trying to draw from a spending well
that has all but run dry.
   The darkest hour is expected Thursday, when Dukakis will announce
$500 million in ``deep and painful cuts'' from a budget just enacted.
   ``Personally, I regret this,'' he said, ``because Thursday is
going to be a dark day in the history of this commonwealth, and it
is all so unnecessary.''
   He said the spending vetoes will lead to thousands of state
employee layoffs, across-the-board cuts in government and the
possible elimination of some agencies.
   Dukakis said he has ``a constitutional responsibility, a
statutory responsibility and a practical responsibility to make sure
that over the course of the next 12 months, spending does not exceed
revenue, lest we go into the next fiscal year with an even worse
situation than we face this year.''
   Reductions in state aid to municipalities will mean ``fewer
teachers, fewer policemen, fewer firemen or more rubbish.
Essentially those are our choices,'' said Lexington Mayor Paul
Marshall.
   ``We've made serious cuts already,'' said council member Buzz
Stapczynski, the town manager of Wilmington. ``For us to make more
is going to be the proverbial blood in the street.''
   Since Dukakis' defeat in November's presidential election,
Massachusetts' credit rating has fallen through the floor and a
major income tax increase has loomed to pay off multimillion-dollar
deficits.
   ``We can either look at this as an ending or as a beginning,''
Dukakis told his local government advisory council Tuesday. ``I
prefer to look at it as a beginning, painful though it is.''
   Dukakis, who announced shortly after the election that he would
not seek a fourth term as governor in 1990, still believes he can
right the ship of state in the 1{ years left in his term.
   To do so when Massachusetts' economic ``miracle'' is experiencing
a comedown from the double-digit revenue growth of recent years will
take more taxes, he maintains.
   But Republican House Minority Leader Steven Pierce said Dukakis'
campaign for higher taxes has failed. Recent newspaper polls suggest
widespread opposition by voters, he said.
   ``There are times the public can be sold a tax increase,'' Pierce
said. ``But it most definitely has not happened with this one
because the taxpayers do not believe that spending has been
restrained or cut or reduced.''
   In January, the Democratic governor proposed $604 million in new
taxes to support a $12.9 billion fiscal 1990 budget. The House took
a tough no-new-taxes stand and slashed his budget accordingly.
   Now, the Legislature is considering a $793 million, 18-month
income tax increase just to pay off a $375 million deficit from
fiscal 1989 and $488 million in recently disclosed Medicaid bills
dating back a decade.
   Despite the Legislature's cuts in his fiscal 1990 budget, Dukakis
said he will have to slash $500 million to bring the enacted budget
in balance with lower revenue estimates and higher projected
Medicaid requirements.
   ``When the Legislature acted (without a permanent fiscal 1990 tax
increase), we warned them the veto pen ... would be more like a
knife,'' Dukakis said. ``And that's exactly what's going to happen.
   Through elimination of 2,500 state jobs and other cutbacks in
recent months, the governor said, ``we've been able at least until
now to maintain basic levels of services. That's not going to be
possible after Thursday. We are going to have deep and painful
cuts.''
   Of the $500 million in vetoes, $200 million is expected in local
aid to cities and towns, which had already reduced their
expectations to matching the previous year's funding.
   Dukakis may be able to balance fiscal 1990 with the vetoes, but
the troubles won't end there.
   Members of his local government advisory council told him they
are collecting support for a possible 1990 ballot initiative to
guarantee that towns and cities will receive their fair share of
state aid in the future.
   And a coalition of anti-tax advocates and chambers of commerce
also are planning a 1990 ballot proposal to win back the extra money
that will be going to the temporary income tax increase.
   Although Dukakis has remained steadfast through the mounting
problems, he recently admitted, ``this hasn't been the best seven
months of my life.''
</TEXT>
