<DOCNO> AP890712-0052 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-12-89 0243EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Salvador     07-12 0396</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Salvador,0409</SECOND>
<HEAD>Government Says 2,800 Rebels Killed, Wounded or Captured In Past
Year</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DOUGLAS GRANT MINE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN SALVADOR, El Salvador (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Government forces killed,
wounded or captured 2,834 leftists guerrillas over the past 12
months, up slightly from the previous year, the defense minister
says.
   If the figures given Tuesday by Gen. Humberto Larios in his
annual report to the legislature are accurate, the casualties
represent about 40 percent of the guerrilla army _ estimated at
6,000 to 7,000 combatants.
   Furthermore, if the general's figures are correct, the Farabundo
Marti National Liberation Front has been extremely successful in
attracting new recruits because its fighting force is not considered
to have diminished.
   The insurgents maintain a constant and active presence in about a
third of this Massachusetts-sized country.
   Last year, 2,766 guerrillas were killed, wounded or captured,
according to government figures. Larios said 455 government soldiers
were killed in the year prior to June 1. He gave no breakdown of
guerrilla dead and wounded.
   Foreign journalists and other independent observers consider both
army and rebel figures on enemy casualties inflated.
   Reporters have found that official and insurgent figures rarely
coincide with the number of bodies discovered following combat.
   Larios, named to his post last month by President Alfredo
Cristiani, said the six nationwide elections held this decade
demonstrate ``rejection of the communist delinquents' hypothesis
that economic, political and social problems can only be resolved by
violence.''
   Cristiani, of the rightist Republican Nationalist Alliance, took
office from Jose Napoleon Duarte of the Christian Democratic Party
on June 1. Duarte is terminally ill with cancer and was prevented by
law from seeking re-election.
   The Salvadoran military receives $85 million a year in aid from
the United States, more than any armed forces in the Western
Hemisphere.
   Cristiani is trying to form a commission to represent the
government in talks with rebel representatives. Non-rightist sectors
have declined to participate, contending the proposed commission
would not have sufficient authority to negotiate peace.
   The rebels have said they will not participate in talks with any
commission that does not include sectors other than the governing
party and that does not have authority to negotiate. They say
Cristiani is trying to engineer their surrender through the
proposals for a dialogue.
   An estimated 70,000 people, most of them civilians, have been
killed in the nearly 10-year civil war.
</TEXT>
