<DOCNO> AP890712-0053 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-12-89 0248EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-Wyoming-Wal-Mart     07-12 0575</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Wyoming-Wal-Mart,0593</SECOND>
<HEAD>Wyoming Town Takes Exception to Discount Stores</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KURT J. REPANSHEK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHEYENNE, Wyo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Wal-Mart's invasion of Wyoming is being
heartily endorsed by just about everyone _ except many Jackson
residents, who are aghast at the thought of having the discount
store as a neighbor.
   The department store chain has begun building stores in Cheyenne,
Laramie and Rock Springs. And plans include adding to the Wal-Mart
Stores Inc. empire in Gillette, Riverton and Jackson.
   In economically strapped Wyoming, the six stores mean roughly 800
jobs and millions of tax dollars.
   But in Jackson, the proposed store is being portrayed as an
eyesore that doesn't mesh with the resort community's Western motif.
   ``We all know what brings people here,'' said Larry Hendricks,
the assistant director of the Jackson Hole Chamber of Commerce. ``We
advertise it as the last and the best of the old West. ... There are
already a lot of chains here, but none that in one fell swoop would
have such a visible impact.''
   Wal-Mart spokeswoman Brenda Lockhart believes the community can
only benefit from the outlet. ``Obviously, we would just like an
opportunity to be a contributor to the community, a good corporate
citizen,'' she said.
   Jackson residents are beginning to realize they can't keep
Wal-Mart out of town, said Hendricks, but that doesn't make the
company's plans any more palatable.
   A recent chamber meeting on the issue produced ``our best
attended general membership meeting in history,'' he said.
   Concerns include a fear that housing in the Jackson area is
insufficient to accommodate the 150 or so new jobs Wal-Mart would
create, and that Wal-Mart's new employees would be coming from other
businesses, said Hendricks.
   But the biggest concern apparently is that Wal-Mart wants to
build on ranchland south of the western Wyoming town of 4,500
residents. Tourists coming into Jackson from the south now see
haystacks and the Tetons before reaching town.
   One faction of residents say a rancher should be able to sell his
land to whomever he wants, others believe such a sale would destroy
``part of the very scenic values that draws people here,'' said
Hendricks.
   Across the state, Cheyenne leaders went out of their way to help
Wal-Mart plan the 110,580-square-foot store being built at the
capital's north end.
   ``I've heard mostly positive things about it, the sort of feeling
that competition is good for business and that that size of a store
would tend to draw more people from outlying areas into Cheyenne,''
Chamber of Commerce President Phil Noble said.
   When asked about Jackson's resistance, Noble expressed an
understanding, saying, ``The prairie out north Cheyenne is certainly
different than the Jackson Hole ambience.''
   Den Costantino, chairman of the Sweetwater Economic Development
Association, agreed, saying the Jackson residents rely on tourists
and want to maintain the Western flavor that surrounds the community.
   Wal-Mart's drive in Wyoming is simply part of its ambitious
expansion program, which aims to open 150 new stores this year. The
company, which operates roughly 1,300 stores in 25 states, has none
in Wyoming.
   ``Obviously, Wal-Mart would like to be in a lot of markets,''
Lockhart said. ``We've also announced entry into New Jersey, New
York and Pennsylvania recently.''
   Noble, Costantino and Maureen Murphy, executive director of the
Laramie Chamber of Commerce, believe Wal-Mart will bring new
customers to their towns.
   As for increased competition, Costantino, who owns a men's
clothing store, said: ``It makes everybody healthy.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
