<FIRST>u i AM-Japan-Markets     07-12 0349</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Japan-Markets,0360</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Up Against Yen, Tokyo Stocks Fall</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. dollar rose against the Japanese yen
Wednesday, while share prices on the Tokyo Stock Exchange fell.
   The dollar closed at 140.50 yen, up 0.88 yen from Tuesday's
139.62-yen finish. The currency opened at 140.70 yen and moved
between 140.40 yen and 140.95 yen.
   The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues lost 45.25
points, or 0.13 percent, ending the day at 33,701.52. The index, a
70.75-point gainer Tuesday, added 66.66 points in early morining
trading.
   Dealers said the market was directionless as investors were
unable to decide whether they should buy or sell amid political
uncertainties ahead of a July 23 parliamentary election despite the
downward trend in the U.S. interest rates.
   It is widely expected that the ruling Liberal Democratic Party
will lose badly in the upcoming upper house election, hurt by an
influence-pedddling stock scandal, an unpopular 3 percent
consumption tax and Prime Minister Sousuke Uno's reported
involvement with paid mistresses.
   Investors are reluctant to buy due to fears that the LDP's
election loss will result in a market plunge.
   A dealer with New Japan Securities Co. said the index fell
sharply within 30 minutes of morning trading, when foreign investors
sold spot issues and bought futures issues in arbitrage deals, but
the index made up most of the losses later. He spoke on condition of
anonymity.
   In currency dealings, traders said the dollar's strength followed
its uptrend in New York as no other major U.S. banks followed Chase
Manhattan Bank's lead in cutting the prime lending rate.
   The New York bank cut the rate by 0.5 percent Monday to 10.5
percent.
   Lower U.S. interest rates decrease the value of
dollar-denominated investments.
   A Bank of Tokyo trader said many Japanese players took a
wait-and-see position in anticipation of an economic summit of major
industrialized countries in Paris beginning Friday and releases of a
variety of U.S. economic indicators the same day.
   Among the U.S. indicators to be released in Washington on Friday
are the producer price index, industrial production and retail sales.
</TEXT>
