<FILEID>AP-NR-07-12-89 0311EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-FaithfulHusband     07-12 0476</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Faithful Husband,0491</SECOND>
<HEAD>Judge Makes Ban on Illegitimate Children Part of Man's Probation</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SPARTANBURG, S.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Legal observers question a judge's order
that a man with six illegitimate children could have no more
children except with his wife, but doubt the sentence violates the
man's constitutional rights.
   Bill McAninch, a professor at the University of South Carolina
Law School, pointed out on Tuesday that state laws prohibit
fornication and adultery and terms of probation require that all
state laws be obeyed.
   ``I suppose the condition is not to violate a criminal law. I
guess what he's doing is just singling out one part of the law,''
McAninch, a specialist in criminal and constitutional law, said
after the sentence by retired Circuit Judge Frank Eppes.
   Derone Suber was in court Monday to plead guilty to stealing a
truck when Eppes _ on special assignment in General Sessions Court _
turned the sentencing into an impassioned talk about the evils of
illegitimate children.
   Suber, 26, has six children from several different women. He
fathered his first child when he was 13.
   In his lecture, Eppes focused on the need for people to own up to
responsibility, particularly for the care of children if someone
chooses to become a parent.
   ``The state's got to pay for him and his children,'' said Eppes.
``This is one of the most tragic things I've seen in court in a long
time.''
   At first, Eppes wanted to make Suber visit schools or churches
twice a month.
   But Suber's attorney, W. Barry Bland, said his client, who walks
with the aid of a walker because of injuries suffered when he
crashed the truck he stole from the Spartanburg Sanitation
Department in 1986, would have difficulty meeting that sentence.
   So Eppes withdrew that condition and Suber was allowed to go.
   A few moments later, Eppes recalled Suber.
   ``I don't feel sorry for you. I'm not mad at you. I'm mad at what
you've done,'' Eppes said. ``I feel sorry for those six children.''
   Eppes then sentenced Suber to 10 years for stealing the truck,
but suspended it to five years' probation. One condition of the
sentence is that Suber not have children with anyone but his wife
during that time.
   It's unlikely the issue would come to a head unless Suber
violated the terms of his sentence and Eppes found out about it and
decided to enforce the sentence, said Steven Bates, executive
director of the American Civil Liberties Union's South Carolina
affiliate.
   ``I don't know how far judges can go in actually enforcing those
types of conditions,'' he said. ``It's difficult to be too critical,
however, because there is a need for a lot of creativity in
sentencing people. Just putting people in jail is not going to solve
problems in the long run.''
   Bland said he may appeal his client's sentence.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
