<FIRST>u i PM-Cuba-Drugs     07-12 0707</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Cuba-Drugs,0732</SECOND>
<HEAD>Castro Accuses U.S. of Withholding Information on Drug Case</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Note language in 16th graf.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CANDICE HUGHES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Fidel Castro has accused the United
States of withholding information that he says could have helped
Cuba uncover sooner a drug ring operating in the top ranks of its
military and government.
   The official news agency Prensa Latina, monitored in Mexico City,
quoted Castro as telling Cuba's Council of State, ``The North
Americans had at least two names.'' There was no elaboration.
   Cuba announced last month that it had uncovered the
drug-smuggling ring. The disclosure followed years of denials by
Castro of U.S. allegations that Cuba had become a way station in the
cocaine and marijuana trade.
   The Council of State, which Castro chairs, on Sunday unanimously
upheld a court-martial's death sentences for cashiered Maj. Gen.
Arnaldo Ochoa, a war hero convicted of running the ring, and three
alleged close collaborators.
   Castro said Cuba had once warned U.S. officials about a plot to
assassinate former President Reagan and said the courtesy should
have been repaid with information about the narcotics ring.
   Prensa Latina said Cuban intelligence told Washington the
assassination plot involved ``reactionary elements'' in the southern
United States who had planned to kill Reagan the next time he
visited their state.
   It did not provide further details.
   Excerpts of Castro's Sunday speech were broadcast Tuesday night
on Cuban television and reported early today by Prensa Latina.
   Castro said Ochoa and the three others must face a firing squad
to restore faith in the Cuban revolution, ensure discipline in the
armed forces and set an example. No date of execution was given.
   The 29-member council also upheld prison sentences ranging from
10 to 30 years for 10 other defendants. All has been officials in
the military or the Interior Ministry security service.
   The council was the final court of appeal, the news agency said.
   Castro said he did not try to influence the council's decision.
He said he asked each of its members for their points of view but
``I never said a word about what I thought.''
   He said the drug scandal had eroded Cuba's international image
and crippled the tourism industry it has been trying to foster.
   Castro's comments about the United States were harsh.
   He accused Washington of trying to discredit his brother and
heir-apparent, Defense Minister Raul Castro, through a propaganda
campaign. Officials in Washington had suggested that Ochoa's
prosecution may have been politically motivated.
   The president said he had ordered Vice Foreign Minister Ricardo
Alarcon to tell an unnamed U.S. official that ``the people who are
spreading these accusations are sons of bitches.''
   He said that if U.S. intelligence officials had been frank and
discreet, Cuba would have taken the drug trafficking charges more
seriously and been able to expose the drug ring sooner.
   It was only after ``friends of ours in Colombia'' came forward
with information about Cuban involvement in the drug trade that the
allegations were taken seriously, he said.
   Ochoa and the others were convicted of collaborating with the
Medellin cartel in Colombia, the world's largest cocaine ring.
   Castro said it was ``supremely grave'' that ``a member of the
Central Committee, a Hero of the Republic, a general of a division,
a man with the prestige Ochoa had'' could become so corrupt.
   Ochoa fought alongside Castro in the revolution that overthrew
dictator Fulgencio Batista in 1959. He went on to become a trusted
aide who carried out confidential missions for the president.
   He is one of only five officers ever awarded Cuba's highest
medal, the Hero of the Republic. Ochoa, 57, was decorated for his
service as a field commander in Ethiopia and Angola. He also headed
the Cuban military mission in Nicaragua.
   Castro repeatedly sought to distance himself from the
now-discredited Ochoa, who is also accused of doing a lucrative
black market business on the side while in Angola that involved
diamonds, ivory, rare woods and military supplies.
   Castro said commuting Ochoa's sentence could create an impression
of impunity that might destroy discipline in the armed forces.
   Ochoa and the others were convicted on Friday. They had earlier
been stripped of all rank and honors and given dishonorable
discharges.
</TEXT>
