<FIRST>r a PM-Fires-Archaeologists     07-12 0416</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Fires-Archaeologists,0430</SECOND>
<HEAD>Archaeologists Work With Fire Crews to Save Indian Ruins</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Fires Rdp, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MESA VERDE NATIONAL PARK, Colo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Firefighters traditionally
battle wildfires with shovels and bulldozers, but those tools are
too damaging to use on a fire threatening an ancient Indian site.
   ``We're not going to compromise the archaeology of the area to
put a bulldozer line in,'' said Paul Hefner, a U.S. Bureau of Land
Management firefighter assigned to the blaze in southwest Colorado.
   ``We're very sensitive to that. We've got to stop this fire, but
not at that cost,'' he said.
   About 400 firefighters and several archaeologists worked to
contain the blaze Tuesday. The fire was triggered Saturday by a
lightning strike, forcing closure of the popular park that houses
numerous ancient cliff dwellings occupied in the 13th century by the
Anasazi Indians.
   The dwellings are in canyons and have not been damaged by fire,
said Charles Harnish, a fire information officer.
   San Juan National Forest Archaeologist Gary Matlock, one of seven
or eight archaeologists who worked with fire crews, said the blaze
also was not damaging ground archaeological sites on the mesas above
the canyons.
   ``They have been through fires before in the 800 years they've
been there,'' he said. ``It's moving right over them.''
   The archaeologists mark the sites so firefighters avoid damaging
or disrupting them, said Linda Martin, district interpreter for the
Chapin Mesa district at the park. The scientists also are on hand in
case firefighters run across a significant find.
   ``Ordinarily, they would just bring in a 'dozer and clear the
area, but there is too much to be lost here for that,'' she said.
   In addition to the cliff dwellings, the archaeologists are
concerned mainly with surface finds such as campsites and kivas,
large rooms used for religious and other purposes.
   Many surface finds have been burned before in the nearly 800
years since they were abandoned, she said. ``The earlier fires have
damaged some of the surface material of the finds, but under the
surface there is still a great potential for finding more,'' Martin
said.
   ``One of the things the archaeologists are doing is studying the
effects of heat on the pottery. The heat has already damaged the
sandstone of the structures. It discolors them,'' she said.
   Firefighter Curtis Miller said working with the archaeologists
was no trouble.
   ``We would clear the brush, then an archaeologist would come
through and mark it before we cut the actual hand line,'' he said.
</TEXT>
