<FIRST>u i PM-Tasnadi'sReturn     07-12 0592</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Tasnadi's Return,580</SECOND>
<HEAD>Photographer Who Fled Hungary Returns With Bush 38 Years Later</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TERENCE HUNT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP White House Correspondent</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BUDAPEST, Hungary (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Photographer Charles Tasnadi jumped down
the steps from Air Force One to the ground and thrust his fists
upward in triumph. He had returned to his native Hungary after 38
years.
   ``If I won $1 million, I wouldn't feel better,'' Tasnadi said on
the two-hour flight from Warsaw, Poland, to Budapest. Peering out
the window as President Bush's plane landed Tuesday, the Associated
Press photographer muttered to himself, ``Moment of truth.''
   But as soon as he hit the ground, Tasnadi went to work, trotting
across the tarmac in a heavy rain to photograph Bush's arrival.
``Welcome home, Charlie,'' his colleagues told him.
   As he focused his camera on Bush, his hands shook. But the
emotions of the moment were blunted by his preoccupation with
getting good pictures.
   Tasnadi had fled Hungary's communist dictatorship as a
25-year-old man, crawling to freedom through heavy snow and
treacherous minefields. He returned Tuesday as a 64-year-old
naturalized American, an AP photographer covering the first visit by
a U.S. president to Tasnadi's homeland.
   His story was well known to Bush, and the president summoned the
photographer to a forward cabin on Air Force One to offer his
congratulations during the flight from Warsaw.
   Tasnadi said Bush had told him that ``he was very happy that I
was here. He said it was most fitting and proper that I return this
way.''
   The photographer's return was a poignant contrast to the way he
had left.
   Tasnadi, a championship skier, and his sweetheart, Maria, now his
wife, joined a group of six other adults and two children in making
their escape from Hungary during the first heavy snowfall of the
1950-51 winter.
   He concocted a story about heading for the slopes, telling the
truth only to his mother who, by design, would report him missing
two days later.
   In the freezing cold, the group made its way across the border to
Austria. On the final, nightlong trek across the border, Tasnadi
carried one of the young children on his back.
   Once in Austria, the escapees took pains to elude Soviet guards
in the 50-mile Soviet zone of that nation. They arrived in Salzburg
several days later.
   It was a harrowing trip. The other child, carried by another man,
had to be knocked unconscious to keep it from crying and alerting
the guards.
   ``And it was so miserably cold,'' Tasnadi said. ``Twice I fell
through the ice up to my chest. I couldn't even feel it.''
   Unexpectedly, Tasnadi said he was not overwhelmed with emotion
during his coverage of the welcoming ceremony for Bush in a downpour
in Lajos Kossuth Square.
   ``I never covered any presidential act in such a rain outside,''
Tasnadi said. ``I was so overwhelmed with the work and to cover the
president that it didn't hit me so deeply as I expected.''
   ``The weather messed up the whole arrival ceremony so there were
no national anthems,'' he said. Tasnadi had feared he would be
reduced to tears hearing the music.
   ``I just looked at this place and thought, my God, this is the
place where as a small boy, I was standing as honor guard'' with Boy
Scouts during civic ceremonies, he said.
   Tasnadi said he was surprised that so many Hungarians turned out
in bad weather to greet Bush.
   ``It shows how the Hungarian people feel about the United States
and this president,'' he said. ``This impressed me very deeply.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890712-0062 </DOCNO>
