<FILEID>AP-NR-07-12-89 0539EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-Obit-Curtis     07-12 0263</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Obit-Curtis,0274</SECOND>
<HEAD>Former Mass. Congressman Dead at 95</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Laurence Curtis, who served five terms in Congress,
has died at age 95.
   Curtis died Tuesday at at Brigham and Women's Hospital. No cause
of death was given.
   Curtis, a Republican from Brookline, also had served one term as
state treasurer, three terms as state senator, two as state
representative and two as Boston city councilor.
   He served in Congress from 1953 to 1962. In 1962, he lost the
Republican primary for a U.S. senate seat to George Lodge,
35-year-old son of former U.S. Sen. Henry Cabot Lodge.
   The younger Lodge lost the general election to Edward M. Kennedy.
   Curtis was unsuccessful in seeking to regain a seat in Congress
in 1968, 1970 and 1972.
   In 1974, when he was 81, Curtis won in an unopposed Republican
primary election for Congress but dropped out the next day, saying
he thought his chances against the Democrat incumbent, the Rev.
Robert J. Drinan, were slim.
   ``With Watergate behind us, the party can get a better
candidate,'' he said.
   In Congress, Curtis served on the House Judiciary and the Foreign
Affairs committees. He thought of himself as middle-of-the-road, but
many regarded him as conservative.
   He was graduated from Harvard College and Harvard Law School and
served for one year with the foreign service, attached to the U.S.
Embassy in Paris.
   He joined the Naval Reserve Flying Corps when World War I started
and lost a leg in a flight training accident.
   He is survived by his wife. A memorial service is scheduled for
Tuesday.
</TEXT>
