<FIRST>u i PM-Dollar-Gold     07-12 0259</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Dollar-Gold,0275</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Mixed, Gold Little Changed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. dollar was mixed today in directionless
trading in Europe. Gold prices were little changed.
   Foreign currency dealers said the markets were correcting last
week's sharp decline and were waiting for U.S. economic indicators
to be released on Friday.
   ``We're in a consolidation phase right now,'' said a trader at a
large West German bank in Frankfurt. ``There's a lot of
position-squaring before Friday going on.''
   Traders said market activity was subdued because many London
traders were absent due to a rail and subway strike.
   In Tokyo, where trading ends before Europe's business day begins,
the dollar rose 0.88 yen to a closing 140.50 yen. Later, in London,
it was quoted at 140.40 yen.
   Other dollar rates at midmorning compared with late Tuesday:
   _1.8808 West German marks, up from 1.8795
   _1.6215 Swiss francs, up from 1.6160
   _6.3785 French francs, up from 6.3740
   _2.1213 Dutch guilders, up from 2.1180
   _1,363.50 Italian lire, down from 1,364.50
   _1.1902 Canadian dollars, unchanged
   In London, the dollar gained slightly against the British pound.
It cost $1.6235 to buy one pound, compared with $1.6270 late Tuesday.
   Gold opened in London at $380 a troy ounce, compared with late
Tuesday's $380.25. At midmorning, the city's five major bullion
dealers fixed a recommended price of $379.50.
   In Zurich, the bid price was $379.40, little changed from $379.75
late Tuesday.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold fell 91 cents to close at $380.87.
   Silver was quoted in London at $5.26 a troy ounce, down from
Tuesday's $5.27.
</TEXT>
