<FIRST>r a PM-HelmsleyTrial     07-12 0433</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Helmsley Trial,0449</SECOND>
<HEAD>Housekeeper: Mrs. Helmsley Said She Didn't Pay Taxes</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VERA HALLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Leona Helmsley once made her housekeeper pay for
food for her estate and boasted that ``only the little people pay
taxes,'' the servant testified at the hotel magnate's tax evasion
trial.
   Elizabeth Baum also said her salary and those of other staff
members were paid by Helmsley businesses.
   Ms. Baum, who spoke with a heavy European accent, said she was
talking with Mrs. Helmsley at the Dunnellen Hall estate in
Greenwich, Conn., four to six weeks after she was hired in September
1983.
   ``I said, `You must pay a lot of taxes,''' Ms. Baum said. ``She
said, `We don't pay taxes, only the little people pay taxes.'''
   Seated at the defense table, Mrs. Helmsley, 69, shook her head no.
   She is accused of tax evasion for allegedly disguising $4 million
in renovations and operating costs at the estate as business
expenses. Two former aides, Frank Turco and Joseph Licari, are
charged with assisting in the scheme.
   Her 80-year-old husband, Harry, was indicted with Mrs. Helmsley
in April 1988 but was found mentally incompetent to stand trial.
   Mrs. Helmsley and Turco also are charged with extorting payoffs
from companies doing business with the Helmsleys' $5 billion real
estate and hotel empire.
   Ms. Baum testified that she ordered groceries and household
supplies for the mansion from the Park Lane Hotel. The items were
delivered every week in a hotel van.
   Assistant U.S. Attorney Cathy Seibel asked if she ever purchased
food locally. Ms. Baum said only on a few occasions.
   ``I bought something for the house that we ate,'' she said. She
testified that when she asked Mrs. Helmsley to reimburse her, Mrs.
Helmsley said, ``You bought it, you pay for it.''
   Ms. Baum said she was fired by Mrs. Helmsley in March 1984. One
Sunday, Mrs. Helmsley called her from the kitchen, ``screamed and
yelled and cursed at me'' and told her she was fired, Ms. Baum said.
   She said when she went upstairs to pack her belongings, Mrs.
Helmsley summoned her again and said everything was fine and she
could stay.
   The next day, Turco called her and said Mrs. Helmsley wanted her
off the estate.
   ``Were you told by Mr. Turco what you had done to cause this?''
Ms. Seibel asked.
   ``No,'' she replied.
   Under cross-examination by Mrs. Helmsley's attorney, Gerald
Feffer, Ms. Baum said Mrs. Helmsley was universally feared by the
staff.
   ``She screamed at everyone and people were scared of her. She was
very nasty,'' Ms. Baum said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
