<FIRST>r a PM-WeatherpageWeather     07-12 0477</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Weatherpage Weather,0494</SECOND>
<HEAD>Several States Drenched by Rain</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Separate storms poured rain on North Dakota, Kansas, Indiana and
West Virginia, turning some roads into waterways.
   Severe thunderstorms spawned a tornado Tuesday night west of
Drake, N.D., and produced hail the size of golf balls. In
Burlington, high winds downed trees and hail the size of golf balls
broke windows.
   Large hail also pelted the North Dakota communities of Watford
City, Carson and Minot.
   In eastern Kansas, thunderstorms Tuesday night deluged the town
of McFarland with more than 6 inches of rain. Three inches fell in
three hours at Washington and heavy rain in Emporia left streets
under as much as 3 feet of water.
   Slow-moving showers and thunderstorms continued to produced heavy
rain in eastern Kansas and southwestern Missouri early this morning.
   Showers early today brought welcome rain to eastern Colorado.
   Elsewhere, rain drenched parts of Illinois, Indiana, Kentucky and
Virginia.
   In Shelburn, Ind., thunderstorms late Tuesday left nearly all the
streets in the town under water.
   Heavy rain fell in parts of West Virginia, resulting in flash
flooding in southern Harrison County.
   Today's forecast called for showers and thunderstorms scattered
from the middle Mississippi Valley across parts of the Great Lakes
and much of the Ohio Valley to the southern and central
Appalachians, and along much of the Gulf Coast and across the
central Rockies.
   Predicted highs: in the 90s across much of the nation; in the 70s
from much of Minnesota across the Great Lakes into northern New
England; in the 60s or 70s along the Pacific Coast; in the 80s over
the northern and central Rockies, and from eastern portions of the
northern Plains across Iowa, northern Illinois and the central
Appalachians to the southern half of the northern Atlantic Coast
states; and above 100 degrees over the southwestern deserts, the
inland valleys of SouthernCalifornia and along the Big Bend of the
Rio Grande Valley in Texas.
   Temperatures at 3 a.m. EDT ranged from 50 degrees at Marquette,
Mich., to 91 degrees at Yuma, Ariz.
   Other reports:
   _East: Atlanta 74 partly cloudy; Boston 64 fair; Buffalo 60
cloudy; Charleston, S.C., 80 fair; Cincinnati 71 cloudy; Cleveland
70 cloudy; Detroit 67 partly cloudy; Miami 77 fair; New York 71
fair; Philadelphia 75 fair; Pittsburgh 71 cloudy; Portland, Maine,
59 fair; Washington 80 hazy.
   _Central: Bismarck 70 fair; Chicago 67 partly cloudy; Dallas-Fort
Worth 79 fair; Denver 66 cloudy; Des Moines 71 foggy; Indianapolis
70 cloudy; Kansas City 75 cloudy; Minneapolis-St. Paul 69 cloudy;
Nashville 72 fair; New Orleans 77 fair; St. Louis 82 fair.
   _West: Albuquerque 72 partly cloudy; Anchorage 59 cloudy; Las
Vegas 75 partly cloudy; Los Angeles 65 partly cloudy; Phoenix 88
fair; Salt Lake City 79 cloudy; San Diego 67 partly cloudy; San
Francisco 56 cloudy; Seattle 64 fair.
   _Canada: Montreal 59 fair; Toronto 61 partly cloudy.
</TEXT>
