<FIRST>r a PM-Newspage-All-StarGame     07-12 0205</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Newspage-All-Star Game,0211</SECOND>
<HEAD>Jackson Leads American League to All-Star Victory</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ANAHEIM, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Starting with a 448-foot leadoff home run
in baseball's All-Star Game, Bo Jackson was in control.
   The American League beat the National League, 5-3, in Tuesday's
contest, which provided a showcase for Jackson's talents.
   Jackson drove in two runs, stole a base and made a nifty running
catch, earning him honors as the most valuable player of the game.
   ``See Bo hit, see Bo run, see Bo do anything,'' Los Angeles
Dodgers pitcher Orel Hershiser said.
   The only other player to hit a homer and steal a base in an
All-Star game was Willie Mays, in the second game in 1960.
   The home run by Jackson, who plays baseball for the Kansas City
Royals and football for the NFL's Los Angeles Raiders, was followed
by a homer by Boston's Wade Boggs.
   California's Nolan Ryan, at 42 the second-oldest pitcher in
All-Star history, was the winner and Atlanta's John Smoltz, the
youngest pitcher in the game, was the loser.
   The National League now leads the All-Star series, 37-22-1. But
the American League has reason to cheer: It won last year, too,
giving it consecutive victories for the first time since 1957-58.
</TEXT>
