<FILEID>AP-NR-07-12-89 0732EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-AbortionRdp     07-12 0532</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Abortion Rdp,0548</SECOND>
<HEAD>New Orleans D.A. Draws Fire for Campaign to Criminalize Performing
Abortions</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHEVEL JOHNSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The American Civil Liberties Union promised to
fight the district attorney in his campaign to make performing an
abortion a crime.
   ``Louisiana is a major battleground,'' ACLU Director Shirley
Pedler said at a news conference Tuesday at a New Orleans abortion
clinic. ``It is the first state to try to criminalize abortion, even
without grounds to do so.''
   Earlier Tuesday, a half-dozen members of the National
Organization of Women picketed District Attorney Harry Connick's
office. Among the protestors was a 10-year-old girl wielding a large
placard that said: ``Harry, you oppressor.''
   Meanwhile, pro-choice protesters in Florida demonstrated against
Gov. Bob Martinez's call for a special legislative session on the
issue come fall, and a Louisiana judge ignored a prosecutor's
request for fines and sentenced dozens of anti-abortion protesters
to a day of community service instead.
   Connick filed documents Monday asking a federal district judge to
lift a 1976 injunction prohibiting enforcement of a law making it a
crime to perform an abortion.
   Under the law, a woman who undergoes an abortion is not liable
for punishment, only the person who performs the procedure.
   Judge Martin Feldman will hold a hearing on the matter Aug. 9.
   Connick said the U.S. Supreme Court's July 3 decision upholding
Missouri restrictions on abortion prompted his action. Connick said
the decision leaves open the possibility that more restrictions
might be deemed legal.
   In a broadcast interview Tuesday, Connick said he hoped his
actions would lead the high court to reconsider the 1973 Roe vs.
Wade case establishing a woman's right to abortion.
   ``Why not find out where we stand instead of waiting for another
shoe to fall?'' Connick asked.
   Pedler called Connick's action irresponsible. She said the ACLU
will argue at the hearing that the injunction barring enforcement of
Louisiana's law should not be lifted as long as Roe vs. Wade is
intact.
   On the small picket line at Connick's office, Michelle Gross of
NOW said Connick was simply playing politics.
   ``Mr. Connick doesn't care anything about women,'' she said. ``He
doesn't care anything about fetuses. He cares about Harry Connick.
He is using this as grandstanding to get re-elected.''
   In South Miami, Fla., hundreds of sign-waving pro-choice
demonstrators surrounded a shopping mall to confront Martinez, but
he ignored their chants on his way into a charity fund-raiser _ the
local opening of the James Bond movie ``Licence To Kill,'' in which
he has a bit part.
   The demonstrators, including some striking Eastern Airlines union
members angered by what they called the governor's indifference to
their plight, tried hard to make Martinez hear their message anyway.
   ``Bob Martinez, there's no doubt, we'll work hard to vote you
out,'' they chanted.
   In Gretna, La., Jefferson Parish Judge Bruce Naccari ordered 84
religious activists to do a day's community service for blocking the
entrance of a suburban New Orleans abortion clinic last October
because he believed they ``were acting out of conscience.''
   ``They felt they were saving lives,'' he said after Monday's
sentencing. ``I didn't feel comfortable with fining them. Many were
poor people.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
