<FIRST>r a PM-Deaths 1stLd-Writethru a0508 07-12 0600</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Deaths, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0508,0614</SECOND>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 1st graf of Caldwell item to UPDATE that she died July
5. Separates moved for PMs as a0440 on Olivier and as a0504 on Curtis.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Laurence Olivier</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Laurence Olivier, the foremost actor of a
distinguished generation and the man whose Hamlet and Henry V
defined Shakespeare for modern mass audiences, died Tuesday of
natural causes. He was 82.
   Knighted and ennobled, he was Lord Olivier when he died but still
plain Laurence Olivier on his stage and screen credits. Olivier was
at home in the plays of Shakespeare, Shaw and Chekhov, as well as
the movie thriller ``Marathon Man'' or the TV mini-series
``Brideshead Revisited.''
   His career took off with roles in Noel Coward's ``Private Lives''
and ``Romeo and Juliet,'' where he alternated the roles of Romeo and
Mercutio with John Gielgud.
   Olivier was the founding father of Britain's National Theatre and
a two-time Academy Award winner. His career was highlighted by a
triumphant procession of Shakespearean roles, from ``Romeo and
Juliet'' in 1935 and ``Hamlet'' in 1937 on stage to a TV production
of ``King Lear'' in 1983.
   He reached mass audiences with title roles and directors' credits
in ``Henry V'' in 1944, ``Hamlet'' in 1948, for which he won the
Academy Award as best actor, and ``Richard III'' in 1955. He brought
``Othello'' to the screen in 1965, a year after playing the jealous
Moor on the London stage.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>Laurence Curtis</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Laurence Curtis, a longtime Republican politician
who held several state posts and was elected to Congress for five
terms, died Tuesday. He was 95.
   The graduate of Harvard College and Harvard Law School joined the
Naval Reserve Flying Corps when World War I started and lost a leg
in a flight training accident.
   He served one term as state treasurer, three terms as state
senator, two as state representative and two as Boston city
councilor.
   From 1953 to 1962, he served in Congress. Curtis was on the House
Judiciary and the Foreign Affairs committees. He thought of himself
as middle-of-the-road, but many regarded him as conservative.
   In 1962, he lost the Republican primary for a U.S. Senate seat to
George Lodge, who went on to lose the general election to Edward M.
Kennedy.
   Curtis was unsuccessful in seeking to regain a seat in Congress
in 1968, 1970 and 1972.
   In 1974, when he was 81, Curtis won in an unopposed Republican
primary election for Congress but dropped out of the race the next
day, saying he thought his chances against the Democrat incumbent,
the Rev. Robert J. Drinan, were slim.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>Sarah Caldwell</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BARNSTEAD, N.H. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sarah Caldwell, the force behind New
Hampshire's living will law that allows a doctor to abandon
extraordinary measures to keep a terminally ill person alive, died
July 5. She was 42.
   Caldwell suffered from multiple sclerosis. Officials are awaiting
autopsy results to determine the cause of death.
   She learned she had multiple sclerosis in 1982. Her son, Mark
Caldwell, said the news devastated her for a while, but she bounced
back and particularly was inspired to work on winning passage of the
living will legislation.
   In 1983 and 1985, the state House and Senate passed legislation
to let people die if their disease progressed to a stage requiring
machines to keep them alive. But then Gov. John Sununu vetoed it
both times.
   Caldwell counted votes from her wheelchair as the state Senate in
1985 overrode Sununu's second veto.
   She wept when the tally was read, and senators hugged her.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
