<DOCNO> AP890712-0073 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-12-89 0754EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-Income-Jackson 1stLd-Writethru a0454 07-12 0651</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Income-Jackson, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0454,620</SECOND>
<HEAD>Limit on Outside Income Aimed at Jackson, Opponents Say</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Inserts 2 grafs after 3rd graf, `'Some of,'' with Jackson planning
early move to D.C.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD KEIL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   District of Columbia council members cite
ethics concerns in voting to cap outside income for top city
officials, but others call it a power play aimed at discouraging
Jesse Jackson from running for mayor.
   The council on Tuesday approved a bill sponsored by mayoral
hopeful John Ray that limits speaking fees and other honoraria to
$10,000 a year for the mayor and the 13 council members.
   ``Some of us who have been involved in the civil rights movement
have heard this before,'' said council member Frank Smith, who
opposed the bill. ``It looks like a cheap shot, and we always look
foolish when it looks like we're trying to keep someone from
running.''
   Jackson's advisers reported Tuesday that Jackson and his wife,
Jackie, will move from Chicago and establish legal residence in the
district this month to qualify for any potential mayoral campaign.
   The Washington Post quoted Jackson aides as saying the couple
will temporarily move into an apartment because renovations to the
house they own here are behind schedule. Candidates for mayor must
be legal residents of the district for at least a year before
election.
   Jackson, whose advisers have said he is ``strongly considering''
running for mayor in the 1990 election, was traveling in Egypt and
could not be reached for comment. The two-time Democratic
presidential candidate earns most of his estimated $200,000 annual
income from giving speeches and making appearances.
   The measure also would limit annual book royalty income to
$10,000 for the mayor and council chairman. No limits would be
imposed on income from other types of employment, but the mayor and
council members would for the first time have to report all sources
of outside income.
   The mayor's job pays $82,500 per year.
   The measure, which was passed by a voice vote, would take effect
in September if it is not vetoed by either Congress or Mayor Marion
Barry. Neither has indicated plans to veto the measure thus far.
   Smith indicated he thought it ironic that the council, which
includes three members who got their political starts in the civil
rights movement, would enact a bill that might discourage a
candidate from running for office.
   ``Those are the things we fought against,'' said Smith. ``They
used to say, `If blacks want to be kings and queens, they can go
back to Africa.' That's what we're doing here.''
   Ray has said he started considering the bill last year after city
residents criticized the council for voting itself a pay raise.
However, he did not explain why he waited to introduce it until
rumors of a possible Jackson mayoral candidacy surfaced.
   Ray did not return several phone calls placed by a reporter after
the council session ended.
   ``I was aware of the Jesse Jackson ramifications, sure I was,''
said council chairman David Clarke. ``It became a question of
timing. I was damned if I did and damned if I (had ignored it.)''
   Clarke, also a declared mayoral candidate, attached to the bill
the provision limiting income from book royalties.
   Council member H.R. Crawford scoffed at the need for an income
limit.
   ``Most people I talk to in the community would pay us $10,000
only to be quiet,'' Crawford said. ``Who on this council could earn
that much giving speeches?''
   Clarke said it's impossible to tell.
   ``I don't know how much anyone here makes,'' Clarke said.
``That's the point _ this bill will tell us.''
   Smith said the bill won't prevent Jackson from running, but could
cause political embarrassment for Ray, Clarke and the other council
members if he is elected.
   ``Things like this usually turn out to be shortsighted
mistakes,'' Smith said. ``The effect here is fairly obvious.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
