<FILEID>AP-NR-07-12-89 0754EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Bush-BarbedWire     07-12 0229</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Bush-Barbed Wire,220</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush Gets Gift of Barbed Wire from Dismantled Barrier</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BUDAPEST, Hungary (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush today got an unusual
souvenir to to take home from his historic visit to this communist
nation: an actual piece of the Iron Curtain.
   Premier Miklos Nemeth gave Bush a piece of the barbed wire,
enclosed in a brass case, from the barriers that used to separate
Hungary from the West.
   The Hungarians began dismantling the grim fences along its border
with Austria earlier this year.
   ``That is just beautiful. That's a marvelous symbol of this whole
visit,'' Bush told Nemeth.
   Secretary of State James A. Baker III got an identical momento
after he and Bush concluded their morning of talks with the
Hungarian leaders at the Parliament building.
   Bush, clearly moved, read the inscription aloud to reporters. It
said:
   ``This piece of barbed wire is part of the Iron Curtain alongside
the Hungarian-Austro border. It palpably represented the division of
the European continent into two halves. It's dismantling was made
possible by the will of the Hungarian people in recognition of
peaceful coexistence and mutual interdependence.
   ``It's believed that the artificial physical and spiritual walls
still existing in the world shall collapse someday everywhere.''
   Later, in a speech at Karl Marx University, Bush said the barbed
wire fences had been ``the ugly symbol of Europe's division and
Hungry's isolation.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
