<FIRST>r w PM-Morgan-Confinement     07-12 0200</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Morgan-Confinement,190</SECOND>
<HEAD>Jailed Doctor Disciplined for Possessing Perfume, Jewelry</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A physician who has been jailed for nearly two
years for contempt of court has been placed in punitive confinement
after guards found her with contraband perfume and jewelry,
officials said.
   Dr. Elizabeth Morgan, serving an open-ended sentence for refusing
to divulge the whereabouts of her 7-year-old daughter in a child
custody battle with her former husband, was disciplined Monday, said
Pat Wheeler, spokeswoman for the District of Columbia Corrections
Department.
   ``She had some contraband,'' Ms. Wheeler told The Washington
Times. ``It was a bottle of perfume, earrings and a gold chain.''
   Under jail rules, prisoners cannot possess items that are not
purchased by corrections officials or are not available in the
prison canteen.
   Ms. Wheeler said after the items were found, Ms. Morgan was
placed in what was described as a section of the jail where
prisoners' movement outside their cells is limited to one hour per
day.
   The action was taken after a disciplinary review board composed
of ranking corrections officials upheld administrative charges
brought against Ms. Morgan.
   ``We do this for everyone's safety and for the orderly operation
of the facility,'' Ms. Wheeler said.
</TEXT>
