<FIRST>r i PM-Pope     07-12 0186</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Pope,0191</SECOND>
<HEAD>Newspaper Says Pope Likely To Visit South Africa Next Year</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A leading newspaper said today
Pope John Paul II is expected to visit several cities in South
Africa early next year.
   Cardinal Owen McCann, Archbishop Emeritus of Cape Town, told The
Star of Johannesburg that the most likely date for a papal visit is
May 1990.
   McCann said he discussed the visit when he met with Vatican
officials and the pontiff in Rome last week.
   The Vatican has indicated that the pope is expected to travel to
Africa next year but says it is premature to discuss which countries
he will visit.
   The Vatican has strongly condemned the South African racial
segragation policies of apartheid, but the pope has indicated he
would be willing to visit.
   John Paul spent several hours in South Africa in September when
his plane was diverted because of bad weather on a flight from
Botswana to Lesotho.
   He visited five countries that border South Africa on that trip
and repeatedly called for an end to racial discrimination without
mentioning South Africa by name.
</TEXT>
