<FILEID>AP-NR-07-12-89 0848EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Israel     07-12 0441</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Israel,0455</SECOND>
<HEAD>Army's Uprising Costs Reported at 500,000 Dollars Daily</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALLYN FISHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Palestinian uprising will have cost the
Israeli army at least $500 million by March 1990, a rate of more
than $500,000 a day, a military magazine reported today.
   In the occupied territories, masked assailants shot and wounded a
42-year-old woman suspected of helping the Israeli authorities, Arab
reports said. The attackers reportedly beat her husband, a distant
relative of Palestinian radical Abu Nidal.
   Soldiers shot and wounded three Palestinians, including a
3-year-old girl, while quelling stone-throwing protests in the Gaza
Strip, Arab reports said.
   The army said it was checking the reports.
   In Israel's Galilee, five Arab Israelis and a Palestinian from
the West Bank were charged with attempted murder for a March 25
grenade attack on a police car.
   In its latest issue, the military weekly Bamahane quoted figures
on the cost of the uprising from Brig. Gen. Michael Navon, director
of the Defense Ministry's budget department.
   Navon was quoted as saying the army by March will have spent $500
million _ or about $575,000 a day _ in attempts to put down the
uprising. The uprising began in December 1987. He said these figures
did not include the losses to the economy caused by the rebellion.
   The Defense Ministry gave lower cost estimates when it prepared
its budget in February. Officials then estimated the uprising was
costing $12.5 million a month, which would amount to $350 million by
March 1990.
   In the uprising, 558 Palestinians have died. Thirty-five Israelis
have also been killed in the violence.
   The army today released figures showing that as of Sunday, 8,592
Palestinians were jailed for uprising-related acts. Of these, 1,857
are being held up to six months without trial.
   The alleged collaborator shot and wounded today was identified as
Rasmiyeh Mohammed Othman, 42, who was wounded near her home in
Nablus, Arab reports said. The assailants injured her husband with
sticks, the reports said.
   Her husband, Tark Banna, 52, is related to Abu Nidal, who leads
the Fatah-Revolutionary Council, a violent Palestinian group based
in Syria and Lebanon. Nidal's real name is Sabri Banna.
   The Israeli Arabs charged today in the attack on a police car are
youths from Sakhnin in the northern Galilee, and the Palestinian is
from Jenin in the West Bank.
   Police Superintendent Gideon Arbel said the group had no known
ties any guerrilla group but added that their attack showed ``an
escalation in nationalist activity in the Galilee.''
   ``Throwing a hand grenade is the sort of activity we didn't face
before. It is a severe act,'' Arbel added.
</TEXT>
