<FIRST>r a PM-ElvisTickets     07-12 0294</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Elvis Tickets,0301</SECOND>
<HEAD>Court Finds Elvis Estate Entitled To Windfall</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAT MILTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MINEOLA, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Nearly 12 years after Elvis Presley died,
lawyers for his estate are wrangling with county officials over
$85,900 in unrefunded ticket sales for a concert that had been
scheduled six days after his death.
   ``Elvis is only entitled to a day's pay for a day's work and
since he didn't show up because he was dead, the ticket holders have
first claims,'' Edward O'Brien, attorney for Nassau County, said
Tuesday.
   ``We take the position that the public treasury is entitled to
the money after the ticket holders.''
   O'Brien spoke after a judge issued a preliminary ruling in favor
of the estate and Presley's promoter, who sued to recover $85,900 in
unrefunded ticket proceeds and $65,000 in interest.
   ``If ultimately, there is a windfall to someone, it should not be
to the county, which played no part in generating the proceeds,''
Nassau County State Supreme Court Justice Eli Wager wrote Tuesday.
   Wager reserved his final ruling until Sept. 19, so the state
comptroller can review the county's claims that it is entitled to
the money under the state Abandoned Property Law.
   A third of the 16,000 people who paid to go to the Aug. 22, 1977,
concert at county-owned Nassau Coliseum in Uniondale never claimed
refunds.
   ``The estate spent money to promote the tour, committed money for
travel and hotels ... If anybody deserve the proceeds it is not the
county,'' said John Brickman, attorney for estate executors
Priscilla Presley, Joseph Hanks, the National Bank of Commerce and
promoter Jerry Weintraub of Los Angeles.
   Presley's estate has filed similar lawsuits in other concert
locations and settled most of them out of court, Brickman said.
</TEXT>
