<FIRST>r i PM-Afghanistan 1stLd-Writethru a0519 07-12 0470</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Afghanistan, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0519,0480</SECOND>
<HEAD>Troops Fire on Rebel Bases as Cease-fire Begins, 44 Reported Dead</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with 2 grafs to UPDATE with guerrillas rejecting cease-fire.
Pickup 2nd pvs, ``The official ...''</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DILIP GANGULY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KABUL, Afghanistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Government forces fired 100 rockets at
Moslem guerrilla bases in hills around the capital hours before the
government declared a cease-fire, authorities said today.
   In Islamabad, Pakistan, the guerrillas rejected the cease-fire,
which was called to observe a religious holiday. ``The cease-fire
doesn't have any meaning for the guerrillas because we began our
fight to get rid of the communists and the problem is not solved,''
a rebel spokesman said.
   The official Soviet news agency Tass said in a dispatch from
Kabul that 44 guerrillas were killed and 62 wounded in artillery
battles in the Kabul area and elsewhere around the country.
   Tass said insurgents fired missiles Tuesday at the central mosque
in Kandahar while a religious service was in progress. It said eight
people were killed and 20 wounded. Battles also were reported
Tuesday in Kabul and the provinces of Ghor, Balkh, Fariab and
Badakhshan.
   Foreign Ministry spokesman Mohammad Nabi Amani said 100 rockets
were fired late Tuesday into the Paghman Mountains, 12 miles
northwest of Kabul.
   ``We understand our brave armed forces have successfully carried
out the task given to them to destroy the (guerrilla) positions,''
Amani said. He did not have casualty figures.
   The rocket barrage preceded by a few hours the Tuesday midnight
start of a four-day cease-fire declared by the government to observe
the Islamic holiday of Eid al-Adha, or Feast of Sacrifice.
   ``We will not fire a single bullet (during the cease-fire), but
if we are fired upon, we will take up arms and destroy the
enemies,'' Amani said.
   President Najib's spokesman, Sarwar Yourish, said Tuesday the
troops would cease hostilities until midnight Saturday for the
holiday, which is held two months and 10 days after the end of
Ramadan, the Moslem month of fasting.
   Amani said, ``We had information that the opponents had massed a
large number of rockets to hit Kabul during the Eid, so we carried
out a pre-emptive operation.''
   The guerrillas, supported by the United States and mostly based
in Pakistan, are trying to overthrow the Soviet-backed government
that seized power in a 1978 coup.
   Afghanistan and the Soviet Union have alleged that the
guerrillas, along with Pakistani military advisers, are planning an
offensive on Kabul and Najib's government has warned that it may
shell Pakistan.
   Pakistan has denied Najib's charges that it is directly involved
in the attacks.
   The Soviet Union ended nine years of military involvement in
Afghanistan when it withdrew the last of its troops on Feb. 15 under
a U.N.-mediated accord. Moscow, however, has continued to supply
arms to the Kabul government.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890712-0084 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-12-89 0905EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-All-Stars-Reagan 1stLd-Writethru a0495 07-12 0692</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-All-Stars-Reagan, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0495,0709</SECOND>
<HEAD>Reagan a Hit at All-Star Game</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 12th graf, `At times ...' to include Reagan's age; A version
moved on sports wires.</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto LA7</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RONALD BLUM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Sports Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ANAHEIM, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ronald Reagan drove in with his entourage,
put on the headsets, checked out the microphone and went back to
what he does best _ talking to America.
   From San Diego street gangs to old movies to the Dominican
Republic, he had something to say, just like every other baseball
announcer. The former president was Vin Scully's color commentator
for the first inning of Tuesday night's All-Star Game won by the
American League, 5-3.
   And he seemed to like it.
   ``I've been out of work for six months,'' Reagan said. ``Maybe
there's a future here.''
   After retiring from the world of Tip O'Neill and Jim Wright,
Reagan returned for a night to the realm of Harry Caray and Phil
Rizzuto. Reagan was his old self _ a bit of humor, and some
memorized facts.
   ``Now, I get a little self-conscious when people can see what's
going on,'' the former radio announcer said while wrapping up his
25-minute stint.
   Like any good announcer, Reagan went down to the clubhouse before
the game to talk to the players. Unlike any other announcer, he
brought along dozens of Secret Service people who sealed and
unsealed corridors, trapping even baseball officials while he passed
through.
   AL president Bobby Brown took him through his league's clubhouse.
Bill White was to lead the National League tour but NL manager Tommy
Lasorda intervened and did it himself.
   Reagan had done most of his homework on Monday, meeting for an
hour with Scully and NBC Sports president Dick Ebersol. He took a
lot of notes, Ebersol said, and was worried about saying the obvious.
   It worked. He bandied about the statistics of National Leaguers
Tony Gwynn and Kevin Mitchell in a way his critics said he was never
able to do when he talked about the federal budget.
   ``He was tied up with the gangs when he was young in school,''
Reagan said of Mitchell. ``And his brother was killed in a gang
fight and he started out in them. But a remarkable person in his
family, his grandmother, took charge, and I understand she saw that
he got a good education. Now here he is away from the gangs, in
baseball.''
   At times, the 78-year-old Reagan just talked with Scully about
what it was like to have outlived many of the ballplayers he grew up
with.
   Scully: ``We were talking before about how baseball makes you
feel young, and when you come down here, I guess all of sudden you
have to figure a few years have fallen off.''
   Reagan: ``Well, yes. Particularly, when our host here tonight is
(Angels owner) Gene Autry and he's 81, and then (California coach)
Jimmy Reese down there, who threw out the first pitch, is 83, I feel
kind of like a kid.''
   Sports broadcasting is nothing new for Reagan. In the 1930s,
``Dutch'' Reagan recreated Chicago Cubs games from Western Union
teletype reports on WHO in Des Moines, Iowa.
   Reagan, who played George Gipp in ``Knute Rockne: All American,''
also was in a baseball movie once. Scully got that in while the
first batter _ St. Louis' Ozzie Smith _ was up.
   ``You wore a Cardinal uniform, as we look at Ozzie,'' Scully said.
   ``Not here in a stadium,'' Reagan said. ``I wore a Cardinal
uniform when I was playing Grover Cleveland Alexander in the
picture, `The Winning Team.' ''
   He even got into a little foreign territory when Scully mentioned
that Pedro Guerrero was from the Dominican Republic.
   ``They have quite a baseball training ground down there for our
major leagues,'' Reagan said.
   It's been a long time since Reagan followed baseball.
   ``Did you get a chance to watch any baseball, with all the
worldly pressures on your shoulders among other things?'' Scully
asked.
   ``Not as much as I would have liked,'' Reagan said. ``Here and
there. But you couldn't quite keep up with what all was going on.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
