<FILEID>AP-NR-07-12-89 0914EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Olivier 1stLd-Writethru a0440 07-12 0888</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Olivier, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0440,0916</SECOND>
<HEAD>An Acting Giant Honored</HEAD>
<BYLINE>Eds: Subs 2 grafs for last pvs, ``A private...'' to UPDATE that
private funeral will be held Friday. No pickup. ^By MATT WOLF</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Theater lights were dimmed and flags lowered as
Britain and the world paid tribute to the incomparable talent of
Laurence Olivier.
   Olivier died in his sleep Tuesday at age 82.
   Queen Elizabeth II and Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher joined
former President Reagan in paying their respects to the actor many
regarded as the greatest of his time.
   But as Olivier would have wished, the shows went on and there was
virtually unanimous agreement that his legacy would continue in
playhouses worldwide.
   The founding father of Britain's National Theater and two-time
Academy Award winner left colleagues reaching for superlatives.
   His public pondered the significance of a career embracing
Shakespearean tragedy and Chekhovian comedy, the romantic and the
elegiac.
   ``He had more magic on the stage than any actor I have ever seen.
He was extraordinary _ he was irreplaceable,'' said Sir John Mills,
one of a generation of distinguished actor-knights. Of those,
Olivier, Sir John Gielgud and the late Sir Ralph Richardson were
considered the three finest.
   ``We became in some ways kind of rivals rather than colleagues,
which I was sorry about,'' Gielgud told the British Broadcasting
Corp. on Tuesday.
   ``But I wouldn't dream of putting myself up as a rival to him in
talent or equipment because he had this extraordinary range of
classical ability and comedy. He was a great comedian and a very
fine tragic actor.''
   Across London's West End, theater marquees dimmed their lights
for an hour. In New York City, Broadway theaters followed suit,
dimming their lights for one minute at curtain time.
   Flags were lowered to half-staff outside the National Theater and
the Royal Shakespeare Company in Stratford-upon-Avon, the birthplace
of Shakespeare. The National's marquee said merely: ``Lord Olivier:
1907-1989.''
   Praise for Olivier began where his gifts first flowered _ on
stage.
   At the National Theater, which Olivier founded in 1963, veteran
actor Michael Bryant told the audience following a performance of
``The Voysey Inheritance'': ``I personally will not be lachrymose.''
   ``I'll be thinking of things like the Crispin's Day speech; `Now
is the winter of our discontent'; his young, magnetic, handsome
Heathcliff,'' said Bryant.
   He referred to Olivier's famed performances in Shakespeare's
``Henry V'' and ``Richard III,'' and as the tragic film hero in the
classic, ``Wuthering Heights.'' They were the three high points of
the late actor's long and distinguished career on stage, screen, and
television.
   At the National's Lyttelton theater, actor Edward Petherbridge
stopped a curtain call for ``The Misanthrope'' to ask the audience
to stand for a moment of silence before one final round of applause.
   ``I'd like us just to applaud especially in case he (Olivier) is
listening,'' Petherbridge said, his voice choked with emotion.
   A rare fusion of superb classical and extraordinary contemporary
actor, Olivier ``summed up the English theater,'' according to
theatergoer Pat Fairbairn, a civil servant.
   But another, Adeline Hartcup, said: ``His ego got in the way.''
   To most observers, Olivier was the consummate British artist: he
distinguished himself in theater and found fame and fortune on
screen.
   Olivier's adventuresome style freed the stage from the ``talking
heads'' elegance of some of his forbears.
   Actor Jeremy Brett said of Olivier: ``The thing one will always
remember is that however many times you'd seen him, it was probably
the most dangerously thrilling moment you'd seen on any stage.''
   Anthony Hopkins said he was constantly struck by the actor's
``tremendous athletic daring.''
   ``In order to test himself, he would hurl himself into the role,
and that can be quite dangerous to limb and body,'' said Hopkins,
who understudied Olivier in August Strindberg's ``Dance of Death''
in 1967. Hopkins went on to co-star alongside Olivier in the films
``A Bridge Too Far'' and ``The Bounty.''
   Denis Quilley, who starred with Olivier in a 1971 stage revival
of ``Long Day's Journey Into Night,'' said Olivier ``never gave up.''
   ``He worked like a dog and was never satisfied until he got what
he thought was right,'' said Quilley.
   ``As far as I'm concerned, the man was cloaked in an aura of
greatness,'' Jack Lemmon said through his publicist. ``No actor that
I know of, that has lived in my lifetime, made me more proud to be
in the same profession.''
   Said Reagan: ``Sir Laurence Olivier delighted millions with his
unmatched excellence on the stage and screen. ... Some of the
greatest moments in the history of the performing arts came as a
result of Sir Laurence's brilliance.''
   Charlton Heston, a close friend who worked with Olivier in the
1966 film ``Khartoum,'' called him ``an amazingly daring actor, the
best of our time.
   ``I had the privilege of working with him on both stage and
screen and his advice to me has proven an inestimable value.''
   Olivier's vicar said today he will conduct a private funeral
service for the actor Friday at an undisclosed Protestant church.
   The Rev. Peter Burch, vicar of St. Andrew's Parish Church near
Olivier's home in Ashurst, 50 miles south of London, said the
service will be followed by cremation.
   A public memorial service will be held later in London, he said.
Details have not been announced.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
