<FIRST>r a PM-AT&amp;TThefts     07-12 0307</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-AT&amp;T Thefts,0315</SECOND>
<HEAD>15 AT&amp;T Employees Fired After Investigation Reveals Theft</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOWN AND COUNTRY, Mo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Fifteen employees of AT&amp;T's national
clearinghouse were fired following thefts up to $500,000, a
newspaper reported today.
   The thefts of telephones, typewriters and other equipment were
set up through a sophisticated computer scheme, the St. Louis
Post-Dispatch reported in a copyright story. Sales employees would
set up fake local buyers for shipments from the clearinghouse in
suburban St. Louis, but the items actually went to friends and
relatives, or were sold on the street at cut-rate prices.
   Jim Tucker, president of Local 6320 of the Communications Workers
of America, said the union was told that AT&amp;T would seek criminal
theft charges against the former employees, who worked at AT&amp;T's
National Service and Sales Center here.
   Salespeople at the center handle purchases and service calls by
telephone for consumers and small businesses throughout the United
States.
   AT&amp;T officials acknowledged in a statement Tuesday that the
company was conducting an internal investigation involving ``loss of
revenue to the company'' and that some sales employees had been
fired. The company declined to give specifics ``because of the
continuing nature of the investigation.''
   The internal investigation began in April after apparent
irregularities were noted in AT&amp;T's ``Like for Like'' program, in
which equipment with service problems is replaced, union officials
said.
   Persons with problems with their AT&amp;T-purchased telephone or
other equipment can call the center and salespeople will dispatch
replacement equipment.
   In the theft scheme, replacement equipment was sent to people who
had never made the initial purchases.
   ``One young lady sent $40,000 worth of equipment _ typewriters,
telephones _ to a car wash,'' Tucker said. An accomplice signed for
the items when they were delivered; the AT&amp;T worker then tried to
sell them on the street for about $25 apiece, Tucker said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
