<FIRST>r i PM-KhomeiniInsurance     07-12 0312</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Khomeini Insurance,0320</SECOND>
<HEAD>Crowd Insured for Expected Crush Marking 40th Day Since Death</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Iran's government-run insurance companies
have established a special death or injury policy for the throng
expected around Ayatollah Ruhalloh Khomeini's tomb to mark the 40th
day since his death.
   Millions are expected at Tehran's Beheshte Zahra cemetery
Thursday to mark the day, the end of the period of mourning in the
Shiite Moslem faith.
   Khomeini, the architect of Iran's 1979 Islamic revolution, died
June 3 of a heart attack at age 86. At least eight people were
killed and thousands collapsed from exhaustion in the mayhem of his
funeral when millions packed Tehran's streets.
   Frenzied mourners grabbed Khomeini's coffin as it was being
readied for the burial and tore apart his white shroud. The coffin
was recovered by Revolutionary Guards and eventually lowered by
helicopter to the graveside at the Beheshte Zahra cemetery.
   The Islamic Association of Insurance Companies, the umbrella
organization for Iran's nationalized insurance companies, announced
that the special policy will pay $13,500 in case of death or serious
injury and medical expenses up to $2,000, the official Islamic
Republic News Agency said today.
   IRNA quoted the minister of the construction crusade, Gholamreza
Foruzesh, as saying about 7,000 workers had been preparing the site
for the past month for Thursday's ceremony.
   Seifollah Vahis Dastjerdi, secretary-general of the Iranian Red
Crescent Society, said medical facilities for Thursday included
1,500 physicians, nurses and relief workers, two helicopters, 250
ambulances and 29 mobile medical centers.
   IRNA said 45 tons of foodstuffs were being shipped in for the
day. The government has distributed free food at the site since
Khomeini was buried.
   IRNA, monitored in Nicosia, also said that the Islamic complex to
be built around the tomb will be able to house up to 150,000
visitors when it is finished within the next five years.
</TEXT>
