<FIRST>u i PM-SununuApology     07-12 0220</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Sununu Apology,210</SECOND>
<HEAD>Sununu Apologizes for Candy Store Remark</HEAD>
<UNK>With PM-Bush-Hungary Bjt</UNK>
<DATELINE>BUDAPEST, Hungary (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   White House Chief of Staff John Sununu
apologized today for comparing Poles to children in a candy store
who can't say no.
   ``I apologize for the metaphor but I think the point was
correct,'' he told a press briefing here, the second stop on
President Bush's 10-day European tour.
   Sununu made his original comment Monday in an NBC-TV interview
when he said Bush would not ``thrust a huge amount of money on the
table'' to help Poland with its staggering economic problems.
   Explaining why substantial funds would be inappropriate, Sununu
replied, ``Well, the analogue ... that's almost appropriate is, you
can't create the problem of a young person in the candy store, where
there is some much there that they don't know which direction to
take and don't have the self-discipline to take the right steps.''
   Asked today about the remark, the chief of staff said he was
trying to make the point that money given to Poland in the 1970s was
misspent and didn't really help that country.
   ``They acknowledge that the utilization of those funds did not
always focus on the most critical needs that Poland had.
   ``The metaphor may have been bad and I apologize for the
metaphor,'' Sununu said.
</TEXT>
