<FILEID>AP-NR-07-12-89 1014EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-LibelJudgment     07-12 0513</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Libel Judgment,0524</SECOND>
<HEAD>Newspaper Pays $2.77 Million Libel Judgment</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Pittsburgh Post-Gazette has paid a $2.77
million libel judgment awarded to a lawyer who was the subject of a
1979 story over a will he prepared.
   It was the largest libel judgment ever paid by a newspaper and
the second-largest judgment upheld by U.S. courts, according to the
Post-Gazette. The largest was a $3 million libel award last year
against CBS News.
   But the newspaper's editor, John G. Craig Jr., said today that he
believes the libel decision is ``a particular Pennsylvania problem''
and won't have nationwide repercussions.
   A Westmoreland County jury ruled in 1985 that the newspaper
libeled Richard DiSalle, a former state and appellate judge, of
Washington County. The payment was for $2 million in punitive
damages, $210,000 in actual damages and interest accumulated since
the verdict.
   The payment check was signed Tuesday by officers of PG Publishing
Co., the newspaper's parent firm. It was paid to DiSalle; his wife,
Joan; and Daniel Berger, the attorney who represented them in the
case.
   At issue was a Sept. 10, 1979, article about the disputed will of
millionaire Paul Ciaffoni. The article contained allegations made in
court documents by some relatives that the will was fraudulently
altered and that DiSalle had a close relationship with the
co-executor, Ciaffoni's youngest daughter.
   The judge instructed the jury that under state libel law
publications about judicial proceedings are immune from legal
responsibility even if they contain information that defames an
individual. The judge said, however, that newspapers give up that
immunity if an article is not a fair summary of those court
proceedings.
   Last month, the U.S. Supreme Court refused to review the case.
   ``I just don't see the decision on neutral reporting privilege
becoming nationwide because it's a very peculiar decision,'' Craig
said. ``But I think in Pennsylvania, until it's overturned, which
I'm sure it will be, it will cause newspapers a lot of trouble.''
   ``You just cannot be involved in a situation like this and not
have a profound effect on you,'' Craig said. ``What it does is bring
home for you the risk involved in the kind of business we're in, and
so you have really a dual responsibility. One is to be conscious of
the risks and execute your business with a great deal of precision
and care. Concurrently, however, you cannot spend your life looking
over your shoulder because people pay you to tell them what's going
on. Part of that is reporting on public life. That's what happened
in this instance.''
   The Post-Gazette is suing one of its insurance carriers, National
Surety Corp., which has refused to pay the $2 million punitive
damages in the case.
   In a lawsuit filed in May, the newspaper argued that its primary
insurance carrier had agreed to pay $1 million to cover the award
and attorneys fees. The lawsuit charged that National, which
provides excess insurance coverage, is refusing to pay.
   The insurance company argued that Pennsylvania law did not permit
insurance carriers to pay punitive damages in the lawsuit.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
