<FIRST>r a PM-CocaineBeach     07-12 0252</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Cocaine Beach,0258</SECOND>
<HEAD>Coast Guard Patrolling As Cocaine Keeps Arriving</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GALVESTON, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Bundles of cocaine continue to wash
ashore on Texas beaches, including a $2.5 million package found near
here, and the Coast Guard warned beachcombers to watch what they
inhale when they take in the air.
   ``If anybody finds any of it, I hope nobody opens the package,''
said Petty Officer James Gutknecht at the Coast Guard's Port
O'Connor station. ``This cocaine is pretty potent stuff.''
   At least nine packages have been found on a 225-mile stretch of
beach between Galveston and Port Aransas since a fisherman found an
11-pound bundle on Matagorda Island on June 30, officials said.
   Officials have said a smuggling ship may have gone down in the
Gulf of Mexico during Tropical Storm Allison three weeks ago,
dumping the contraband into the sea.
   ``We've had seven in the Port O'Connor area,'' Gutknecht said.
``They all weighed about one kilo each.''
   A Coast Guard boat found a 2.2-pound package valued at $100,000
on Tuesday near Matagorda Peninsula. Guard boats are patrolling the
area around Port O'Connor in hopes of intercepting any more bundles,
Gutknecht said.
   The largest find to date was a 55-pound package worth $2.5
million that was discovered Monday evening by a man walking along
Crystal Beach near Galveston, U.S. Customs spokesman Cliff Wolfe
said.
   Galveston County Sheriff Joe Max Taylor said they are the first
instances of cocaine washing up on beaches although bales of
marijuana have washed ashore in the past.
</TEXT>
