<FIRST>r w PM-SecretService-Spence 2ndLd-Writethru a0528 07-12 0506</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Secret Service-Spence, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0528,460</SECOND>
<HEAD>Secret Service Officer Accepted Watch From Spence, Reports Say</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: New throughout to show that Washington Times first reported
officer receiving gift watch last week</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Secret Service officer at the White House has
told investigators he accepted an $8,000 wristwatch from a
Washington lobbyist who had asked him to intervene when the lobbyist
was arrested for driving while intoxicated, according to published
reports.
   The lobbyist, Craig J. Spence, is the target of a federal
investigation of his relationship with federal employees, including
the uniformed Secret Service officer.
   The probe is tied to an investigation of possible credit card
fraud by an alleged homosexual prostitution service broken up by
local and federal agents in February.
   Last week, The Washington Times reported that Spence, who the
newspaper said was a client of the prostitution service, gave Secret
Service officer Ronald A. deGueldre an $8,000 gold Rolex wristwatch
in exchange for ``unspecified favors.''
   DeGueldre has acknowledged admitting Spence and several friends
to the White House for a special 11 p.m. tour on the weekend of
Independence Day in July 1988. ``I gave him the tour like I did my
family,'' deGueldre told The Associated Press on Monday.
   DeGueldre told the Times that he first met Spence when he was a
patrolman near foreign embassies where Spence lived. About five
years later, the officer said Spence called him to invite him to a
number of parties.
   The Washington Post reported in today's editions that deGueldre
also said Spence asked him to intervene with officials following
Spence's arrest on a charge of drunken driving.
   Spence was arrested Jan. 20, 1988 by the Secret Service for
drunken driving, according to court records.
   DeGueldre told the Post that after Spence called him in late
January 1988, deGueldre ``talked to my superiors and informed them
that this was a guy with a lot of clout. That's the last I ever
heard of it.''
   The District of Columbia Office of Corporation Counsel said
Tuesday the case was dropped on Feb. 5, 1988 because it was
``without merit,'' but would not give details, the Post reported.
   DeGueldre, reached Tuesday by The AP, refused to comment on
details of the driving case.
   DeGueldre also said he received the gold watch from Spence last
July. ``Spence said we should swap watches, and I gave him my $22
Casio and he gave me the $8,000 Rolex. It was a friendship thing,
not to do anything for him.''
   According to the Post, DeGueldre has denied allegations by a
Secret Service investigator that he admitted stealing several pieces
of the valuable Truman china collection from a pantry in the White
House living quarters and gave one piece to Spence and several to
members of deGueldre's family.
   The Secret Service said the officer admitted stealing two sets of
presidential cufflinks and tie tacks from the basement office of
Rose Zamaria, director of White House operations, the Post reported.
   DeGueldre denied committing any thefts or doing favors for
Spence, the Post said.
</TEXT>
