<FIRST>r a PM-People-Edwards     07-12 0209</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-People-Edwards,0216</SECOND>
<HEAD>Former Louisiana Gov. Edwards Divorcing</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BATON ROUGE, La. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former Gov. Edwin Edwards has filed for
divorce from his wife of 40 years, saying they have reached an
amicable agreement to part after living apart for more than a year.
   Edwards, 61, filed the divorce petition and a concurring answer
from his 60-year-old wife, Elaine, in state District Court here
Tuesday.
   ``Elaine will remain in New York to pursue a career in television
and advertising,'' said a statement issued through Edwards'
secretary on behalf of the couple.
   ``I will remain in Louisiana to practice law and continue my
pursuit of political interest. We have always been good friends, we
are now and ever will be.''
   The petition says the couple separated in March 1988. It also
says they have reached agreement concerning community property and
that no legal proceedings are necessary to divide it.
   The two married on April 5, 1949. They have four children ranging
in age from 29 to 39.
   Edwards won two terms as governor in 1972 and 1976. He regained
the seat in 1984 and moved into the mansion alone while his wife
remained in their Baton Rouge house. He was defeated in the 1988
Democratic primary by now-Gov. Buddy Roemer.
</TEXT>
