<FIRST>u i PM-Bush-Peaches     07-12 0256</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Bush-Peaches,240</SECOND>
<HEAD>For President, Peaches at 18 Forints a Kilo a Good Buy</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BUDAPEST, Hungary (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush pulled out a wad of
Hungarian money and did his bit for free enterprise today in a
bustling produce market.
   Bush, after his speech at Karl Marx University, went shopping at
the market on nearby Dimitrov Square, the same one where British
Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher purchased garlic and peppers on a
1983 visit.
   Bush had sweeter fare in mind: a dozen ripe peaches that cost 18
Hungarian forints a kilo, or about 14 cents a pound.
   That was cheap for the president of the United States, but close
to an hour's wage for the average Hungarian.
   ``I recommend these to you,'' he told reporters who trailed him
through the crowd of shoppers and vendors.
   An ebullient Bush shook hands and signed autographs for the
crowd, and blew kisses with his hand.
   He was greeted with applause wherever he went in the ornate,
wrought iron market, built late in the 19th century, where vendors
sell succulent heaps of fruit, vegetables, meat and other produce
from Hungary's rich farming land.
   Most of the produce comes from small private plots.
   Earlier, before going to the university, Bush met for half an
hour with 13 students from all over Hungary. Five were members of
FIDESZ, an outspoken youth group formed last year as a rival to the
official communist youth league, which has since disintegrated.
   Bush gave two of the students a ride in his limousine to the
university.
</TEXT>
