<HEAD>Police: Woman Wandered in Airport Five Days</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 3rd graf to insert that woman finally asked officials for
help; SUBS 7th graf, `Ms. Rodriguez ...' to update condition today; SUBS
9th graf with woman sleeping in airport waiting areas.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 70-year-old woman spent five days in an
airport after she was separated from her family as a result of a
series of misunderstandings, police said.
   Initially, it was feared the woman might have been left behind by
relatives, but that turned out not to be the case, police said
Tuesday.
   Irene Rodriguez wandered around Los Angeles International Airport
after she went there July 5 to board a flight to Lincoln, Neb., and
found there was no ticket waiting for her. Finally, she asked
airport officials for help.
   Police began a criminal investigation, believing that pages in
the woman's address book were torn out, that her bank account had
been cleaned out and because officers were unable to locate her
children.
   But her son, Robin Breadwell, 39, and his 47-year-old wife,
Emily, 47, reported his mother missing when they arrived in Lincoln
after driving there. Their trip was delayed by vehicle troubles,
said police Detective Mel Arnold.
   ``It was just a tragic incident, probably a communications gap,''
Arnold said. ``It all worked out OK, I guess.''
   Ms. Rodriguez was undernourished and dehydrated after her ordeal.
She was hospitalized Sunday after finally seeking help and was
listed in good condition today at the Medical Center in Tarzana.
   Breadwell told authorities he reserved a ticket for his mother
July 3, but apparently his credit card purchase had not cleared in
time for the ticket to be issued, Arnold said.
   Ms. Rodriguez said she ate in airport cafeterias until her pocket
money ran out and slept in seats in the airport waiting areas. A
carry-on bag was reportedly stolen during her ordeal.
   Arnold did not explain why authorities initially believed the
woman's address book had been tampered with or whether Breadwell was
authorized to close his mother's bank account.
   The Breadwells reportedly were moving her furniture to Nebraska
overland after buying her a home in Lincoln so that she could be
closer to them.
</TEXT>
