<FILEID>AP-NR-07-12-89 1040EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Israel-Bomb     07-12 0234</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Israel-Bomb,0242</SECOND>
<HEAD>Police Dismantle Explosive Beneath Car of Tel Aviv Mayor</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police today dismantled a small explosive found
under the car of Tel Aviv's mayor while it was parked outside his
home.
   Mayor Shlomo Lahat said people who oppose plans to demolish an
illegally built home and close an unlicensed business may have been
responsible.
   But police spokeswoman Etti Greenberg said the motive was not
known. She described the explosive as ``small'' and refused to
elaborate.
   Israeli radio stations quoted witnesses as saying it looked like
a small gas tank rigged with a few wires.
   Ms. Greenberg said the bomb was spotted by a neighbor early today
beneath the mayor's car in north Tel Aviv. Police are investigating
in all directions to determine who is responsible,'' Ms. Greenberg
said by telephone.
   Lahat, 62, told army radio he believed the assailants were trying
to warn him not to close an unlicensed business or raze an illegally
built house. He did not specify which business or home he was
referring to.
   ``It is what you may call a warning. Not for something done but a
decision that is supposed to be taken. That is my feeling,'' Lahat
said. ``Whoever thinks they will deter me from my job is mistaken.''
   Tel Aviv, on the Mediterranean coast, is the country's economic
and social center. It is home to 350,000 Israelis, including 7,500
Arab citizens.

</TEXT>
</DOC>
