<FIRST>r i PM-Mandela     07-12 0308</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Mandela,0322</SECOND>
<HEAD>Current Likeness of Mandela Distributed by Trade Unions</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Trade unions today distributed
hundreds of posters bearing a likeness of African National Congress
leader Nelson Mandela, defying a law banning reproduction of
prisoners' pictures.
   Mandela, who has been in prison since 1962, is serving a life
term for sabotage and plotting the overthrow of the government.
   After his imprisonment, no pictures of him were published in
South Africa until a small photograph appeared in a government
handbook three years ago. Several newspapers later published that
picture.
   However, the photograph showed Mandela at age 45. He will be 71
next week.
   Last year, according to sources, an artist was commissioned to
produce a current likeness of Mandela and did so from descriptions
of the few people who have been allowed to visit him in prison.
   A color drawing was printed on a poster and distributed today at
the opening of the annual meeting of the Congress of South African
Trade Unions.
   It was described by those who have seen Mandela as ``a very good
likeness,'' and ``fairly accurate.''
   The posters, bearing the words ``Release Mandela and All
Political Prisoners,'' were also taped to the walls and windows of
the convention center south of Johannesburg, where the conference is
being held.
   No police were visible at the conference, and no attempt was made
to remove the posters.
   The poster and the drawing of Mandela bear no artist or printing
company credit. Neither officials of the labor congress nor their
attorneys would discuss the origin of the picture.
   Although no legal photograph has been taken of Mandela since
1962, a picture of him was taken surreptitiously in 1966 at Robben
Island prison.
   Mandela met July 5 with President P.W. Botha. The talks at
Botha's official residence fueled speculation that Mandela may soon
be released.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
