<HEAD>Syrian, Christian Artillery Duels Outside Beirut</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MOHAMMED SALAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Syrian and Christian gunners battled with
howitzers in mountains southeast of Beirut today, and 10 people were
reported wounded.
   The latest casualties brought the overall toll to 405 people
killed and 1,593 wounded since the confrontation began March 8.
   The leftist daily paper As-Safir, which has close ties to Syria,
said the Christian army commander, Gen. Michel Aoun, was planning
``a major escalation of the confrontation in the next few days with
the aim of achieving a meeting of the U.N. Security Council on
Lebanon.''
   The conservative daily paper Ad-Diyar quoted an unidentified
``senior source'' in Christian east Beirut as predicting a ``major
escalation of hostilities'' by the weekend if a three-member Arab
League committee failed to persuade Syria to lift its naval blockade
of Christian ports.
   As-Safir, quoting unidentified Western sources, said France and
Iraq support Aoun's plan to seek a settlement to the
Syrian-Christian confrontation at the United Nations.
   Iraq, Syria's main Arab rival, has declared support for Aoun's
``war of liberation'' against Syria's 40,000 troops deployed in
Lebanon.
   Aoun and other Christian leaders have accused the Syrians of
failing to achieve a 1976 peacekeeping mandate from the 22-nation
Arab League by siding with Moslems against the Christians in the
14-year civil war.
   Syria and its local Moslem and leftist militia allies have
accused Aoun of blocking Arab League peace efforts. An aide to Aoun,
speaking on condition of anonymity, denied that.
   Syrian gunboats have blockaded the 28-mile Christian-controlled
stretch of Lebanon's 130-mile Mediterranean coast.
</TEXT>
