<FIRST>r w PM-PeaceCorps-Hungary     07-12 0429</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Peace Corps-Hungary,420</SECOND>
<HEAD>With PM-Bush-Hungary</HEAD>
<HEAD>American Peace Corps Volunteers Will Train Hungarians in Teaching
English</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARTON REPPERT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Peace Corps' new program in Hungary will
involve about 60 American volunteers going there to train Hungarians
in the teaching of English, agency officials said today.
   President Bush announced the program _ marking the first Peace
Corps effort in a communist country _ during his visit to Hungary.
   In offering the corps volunteers, Bush said in Budapest: ``The
teaching of English is one of the most popular American exports.''
He said the program will help ``open the global market to more
Hungarians.''
   At a news conference here following Bush's announcement, Peace
Corps Director Paul D. Coverdell declared that ``this is a historic
day and the threshold of a new era for the United States Peace
Corps.''
   ``When volunteers enter Hungary, it will be the 100th nation in
which we have served,'' he said. ``It will also be the first
European and first Eastern bloc nation in which the Peace Corps has
served.''
   Coverdell said that while more than 121,000 U.S. volunteers have
served in 99 developing countries over the last 28 years, ``the
program in Hungary shows that the underlying mission of peace has no
political or national boundaries.''
   ``President Bush today told the Hungarians that to succeed in
reforms you need partners _ not just governments, but people. The
United States Peace Corps is proud to provide some of those
partners,'' he said.
   Coverdell said details of the program still need to be worked out
through talks with Hungarian officials.
   Asked about the number of American volunteers that will be
involved, he said that ``ultimately we believe the number will
approach 60 volunteers in 1990, which is a very substantial
program.''
   Coverdell said that eventually the hope is to place volunteers in
all 19 counties of Hungary and the federal district of Budapest.
   The emphasis will be on training Hungarian classroom teachers to
teach English as a second language to their own people.
Russian-language training is no longer required in Hungarian
schools, and Hungarian officials have expressed interest in
expanding the use of English.
   The United States announced plans this spring to send Peace Corps
volunteers to China, but in the wake of the unrest there Chinese
officials have delayed accepting the Americans.
   Coverdell told reporters that Beijing officials had said they
wanted a ``postponement'' and further talks about implementing the
program in China.
   ``We are prepared to enter into those discussions on whatever
timetable they choose,'' the Peace Corps chief said.
</TEXT>
