<FIRST>r i PM-SriLanka     07-12 0262</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Sri Lanka,0269</SECOND>
<HEAD>Sri Lankan Universities Closed, Security Forces Move In</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PATRICK CRUEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COLOMBO, Sri Lanka (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government today closed the
nation's six universities and sent in security forces to search the
campuses in a crackdown on Sinhalese militants.
   The universities are believed to be bases for left-wing
extremists of the anti-government People's Liberation Front.
   Colleges reopened May 10 after being closed for two years in an
effort to curb student unrest and violent anti-government
demonstrations.
   A Defense Ministry statement said, ``The security forces were
compelled to order the closure of universities as a temporary
measure.''
   ``The security forces in a preliminary search have already found
large quantities of explosives, weaponry, subversive literature and
posters intimidating the public,'' the statement said.
   It said the universities will be closed until security forces
complete their search and ``isolate the disruptive elements.''
   Four of the universities are in the island's central and southern
districts, the stronghold of the People's Liberation Front. The
other two are in the northeast.
   The radicals launched a violent, anti-government campaign two
years ago to protest peace overtures to Tamil rebels fighting for an
independent nation.
   The government blames the radicals for more than 3,500 political
killings since then. The extremists allege too many concessions were
given to the minority Tamils, who make up 18 percent of the
population.
   Tamils have been fighting for an independent nation since 1983,
alleging discrimination in jobs and education by the Sinhalese, who
comprise 75 percent of Sri Lanka's 16 million people and control the
government and military.
</TEXT>
