<SECOND>PM-Mexico-Elections, 2nd Ld-Writethru,a0548,0488</SECOND>
<HEAD>Governing Party Wins 12 of 18 Seats in Michoacan State</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with 12 grafs to CORRECT party initials to PRD sted PAN,
and adds name of opposition party in Baja. Pickup 13th graf, `The PAN...'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The governing Institutional Revolutionary
Party made a strong showing in Michoacan state elections, according
to results announced today. News reports said the opposition may ask
for a new election because of alleged fraud.
   The governing party, PRI, conceded defeat in the Baja California
gubernatorial race, its first such loss since the party was founded
60 years ago.
   It won 12 seats in the Michoacan state assembly, compared to six
for the main opposition Democratic Revolutionary Party, or PRD, said
the official Notimex news agency.
   Although PRI fell one short of a majority, the outcome was seen
as a victory for a party that last year lost all but one of the
Michoacan congressional seats in the national elections.
   There are 24 seats in the assembly, six of which are assigned to
minority parties who failed to win any of the 18 races.
   Notimex said PRD leaders may ask for new elections because of
alleged irregularities in the July 2 balloting and the count.
   PRD repeatedly said the PRI was cheating in Michoacan, and PRD
supporters picketed or staged sit-ins in many districts to monitor
the vote count.
   In the northwestern border state of Baja California, official
results had yet to be announced in two of 15 contested legislative
districts and the governorship.
   PRI officials were treating the party's defeats almost as
victories, saying they demonstrated the sincerity of President
Carlos Salinas de Gortari's promise to clean up Mexico's elections
and modernize its politics.
   ``The winds of change and democratic transformation that are
sweeping the world have arrived, without doubt, in Mexico,'' said
the PRI's national chairman, Donald Colosio.
   The defeats are ``a reality that all the sectors of the PRI
accept because, above everything, the commitment is to democracy,''
PRI Sen. Maximiliano Silerio Esparza said.
   PRI conceded the governorship to the National Action Party, or
PAN. Of legislative seats that have been decided, PAN holds seven
and PRI holds six.
   The PAN candidate, Ernesto Ruffo, is the first non-PRI candidate
to win a governorship since PRI was founded. PRI has never lost a
presidential election and suffered its first Senate defeats in last
year's general election.
   Four more seats will be awarded to minority parties by proportion
of the statewide votes.
   The state electoral commission has declared PAN candidates the
victors in mayoral races in Tijuana and Ensenada, while a PRI
candidate was the winner in Tecate.
   In Mexicali, Baja California's capital, PRI claimed victory and
PAN conceded defeat.
   PAN, which ran its first gubernatorial candidate in Baja
California in 1959, is Mexico's oldest and best organized opposition
party.
</TEXT>
