<FIRST>u w PM-B-2Bomber 1stLd-Writethru a0449 07-12 0749</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-B-2 Bomber, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0449,700</SECOND>
<HEAD>Air Force Argues Stealth Needed to Penetrate Soviet Defenses</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDs: TOP 6 grafs new to UPDATE with hearing; picks up 4th graf pvs,
The Air.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DONNA CASSATA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Lawmakers today warned Air Force officials that
the half-billion-dollar B-2 stealth bomber faces a tough uphill
fight in Congress despite the warplane's strategic importance.
   ``Put it in perspective or there's a real possibility that the
B-2 will become a museum piece,'' Rep. Les Aspin, D-Wis., chairman
of the House Armed Services Committee, told Air Force officials at
the start of a hearing on the radar-evading plane.
   Air Force Secretary Donald Rice and Chief of Staff Gen. Larry
Welch, using a color-slide presentation, argued that the plane
outpaces improvements in Soviet air defenses and that failure to
build the bomber would undermine the nation's nuclear deterrent
force.
   The Air Force argument marked the second day in a row that
officials took their case to Congress. Rice and Welch made a similar
presentation to the Senate Armed Services Committee on Tuesday.
   At the start of today's hearing, Republicans as well as Democrats
served notice that the B-2 faces serious opposition in a
budget-minded Congress.
   ``The B-2 program is in a lot of trouble, a lot of difficulty.
It's not technical problems but the price tag,'' said Rep. William
Dickinson of Alabama, ranking Republican on the House Armed Services
panel.
   The Air Force campaign comes amid growing opposition to the
bomber, which recent estimates indicate would be the most expensive
aircraft in history at $500 million to $750 million a copy.
   Last month, Sen. John Glenn, D-Ohio, a member of the Senate Armed
Services panel, urged Defense Secretary Dick Cheney to suspend
production of the B-2 because the aircraft has not been tested in
flight.
   Glenn, a former astronaut and test pilot, said pursuing
production of the plane violates the rule of ``fly before buy.''
   Two weeks ago, a House amendment to the fiscal 1990 defense bill
proposing cancellation of the program failed, but the Armed Services
panel did approve cutting $500 million from the program's
procurement budget.
   Since then, the Pentagon announced late Friday the first flight
tests of the bomber _ 18 months behind schedule _ would be held
during the next two weeks. And on Monday the bomber moved under its
own power when it taxied along a Mojave Desert runway.
   This week, while the Senate committee votes on the military
budget and the House prepares to take up defense spending later this
month, Rice and Welch are presenting their case to lawmakers. Cheney
is scheduled to appear before the House panel on Thursday.
   The Pentagon is proposing a $4.7 billion budget in fiscal 1990
for the B-2. Manufactured by Northrop Corp., in Palmdale, Calif.,
the plane will cost about $24 billion over a three-year peak period
beginning in fiscal 1992, according to Defense Department figures.
   The department has invested about $22.4 billion in the plane so
far.
   One Republican member of the Senate Armed Services pane, said he
was not swayed by Tuesday's lobbying campaign.
   ``I have serious concerns about the aircraft,'' said Sen. John
McCain of Arizona. ``I may not go as far as Senator Glenn, but the
Air Force must prove this aircraft before full-scale production.''
   McCain said the service, with the runway test Monday and a maiden
flight in a few weeks, is ``conveying the appearance of only meeting
milestones in the face of congressional pressures.''
   Rice and Welch told senators the Pentagon estimates the Soviet
Union has spent more than $350 billion on air defense over a 20-year
period and plans to invest more money.
   ``That very expensive array of defenses is largely ineffective
against an aircraft with B-2 capabilities,'' the Air Force said in
an 18-page report.
   Although Rice and Welch met in closed session with the Senate
panel, the ranking members _ Democratic chairman Sam Nunn of Georgia
and Republican John Warner of Virginia _ released the Air Force
report.
   The Air Force also said the B-2 ``can make a powerful
contribution with its conventional capability.'' The plane can cover
all the world's land areas from any of three locations _ the
Whiteman base in Missouri, Diego Garcia in the Indian Ocean and Guam
_ with a single air refueling.
   The Air Force said, a small force of B-2s could have had the same
success that two carrier battle groups and about 120 aircraft had in
the 1986 raid on Libya.
</TEXT>
