<FIRST>r a PM-TroopersShot     07-12 0263</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Troopers Shot,0271</SECOND>
<HEAD>Man Shoots Two State Troopers in Ambush</HEAD>
<DATELINE>VALLEY COTTAGE, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man claiming to be an FBI agent
called state police this morning to ask for backup, then shot the
two troopers who were sent to help him, police said.
   Trooper Noel Sanchez, 30, was hit in the neck but was expected to
recover, said state police Maj. Carl Colberg. Trooper Christopher
Elg was grazed on the forehead, treated and released.
   The gunman got away and police in cruisers and helicopters were
searching in New York and New Jersey. The shooting occurred on the
grounds of the Ford Products Co. in Valley Cottage, about seven
miles from the New Jersey border.
   Colberg said a man called the West Nyack station of the state
police early this morning, saying he was an FBI agent doing
surveillance at Ford Products.
   The man requested ``a state police patrol to assist him in case
he needed a uniformed presence,'' Colberg said.
   The troopers met a man at Ford Products who ``was dressed in a
manner that indicated he was a police person. He apparently was
wearing a bulletproof vest and spoke in police jargon,'' Colberg
said. The man spoke with the troopers, then pulled a gun believed to
be a semi-automatic and fired at them.
   Elg was treated at Nyack Hospital and released, according to
hospital spokeswoman Nancy Kriz.
   Sanchez was transferred from Nyack Hospital to the Westchester
County Medical Center in Valhalla. His wound is not considered
life-threatening, Colberg said.
   Elg has been a trooper since 1985; Sanchez since 1983.
</TEXT>
