<FIRST>u i PM-ArmsControl     07-12 0312</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Arms Control,310</SECOND>
<HEAD>NATO Rushes Package of Weapons Reductions To Table In Vienna</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARRY SCHWEID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Diplomatic Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BUDAPEST, Hungary (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In a drive to reach an early agreement,
the NATO allies will present to the Warsaw Pact on Thursday their
proposal for reducing non-nuclear forces in Europe, Secretary of
State James A. Baker III announced today.
   This is nearly two months ahead of schedule and improves
prospects for completing an accord within a year, Baker told
reporters traveling with President Bush here.
   ``By tabling this proposal, we are taking a step toward ending
the military division of Europe,'' Baker said at a news conference.
   Baker praised the Soviets for accepting a U.S. proposal to
conduct trial monitoring of nuclear missile systems before signing a
strategic weapons treaty.
   ``We think it is very good that the Soviets have responded
positively,'' Baker said.
   Despite complaints by American anlysts outside the government
that it was a stalling tactic, Baker said trial monitoring ``might
move arms control forward instead of retarding it.''
   The negotiations to cut long-range bombers, missiles and
submarines are being held in Geneva. The talks to reduce troops and
other non-nuclear forces are scheduled to recess on Thursday in
Vienna.
   The next round is scheduled for Sept. 5.
   Putting NATO's proposal on the table before the recess gives the
Soviets and their allies nearly two months to frame a response.
   Baker announced, meanwhile, that NATO would propose a ceiling of
5,700 combat aircraft for each alliance and 1,900 combat helicopters.
   The decision to make the proposal on Thursday was reached by a a
panel of senior NATO officials in Brussels last Friday, a U.S.
official said.
   Bush first unveiled at the NATO summit in May his blueprint for
deep reductions in conventional arms and troops in Europe by the
superpowers. It was subsequently endorsed by the full NATO alliance.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
