<FIRST>r i AM-Naidoo     07-12 0182</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Naidoo,0186</SECOND>
<HEAD>Catholic Archbishop Buried After Funeral</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CAPE TOWN, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Roman Catholic Archbishop Stephen
Naidoo was buried Wednesday following a funeral Mass that drew more
than 7,000 mourners.
   The 51-year-old leader of the Cape Town Archdiocese died of a
heart attack July 1 at his brother's home in London.
   Naidoo was interred in St. Mary's Cathedral at a private ceremony
after the Mass, attended by Desmond Tutu, the Anglican Archbishop of
Cape Town, and other South African church leaders, as well as Roman
Catholic bishops from Lesotho and Zimbabwe.
   Durban Archbishop Denis Hurley recalled Naidoo as a ``gentle,
kindly, articulate and considerate person'' who stood for justice
and peace. He said Naidoo would be remembered for his participation
in a clergyman's march on Parliament in February 1988, when he was
arrested for the first time in his life, along with Tutu and others.
   Naidoo also played a prominent role in negotiating the release of
hunger-stiking detainees earlier this year, and was a major force in
organizing the visit of Pope John Paul II to southern Africa in
September.
