<FIRST>u i AM-China-Tourism Bjt   07-12 0594</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-China-Tourism, Bjt,0610</SECOND>
<HEAD>China Hosts Tour Agents in Effort to Revive Tourism</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHY WILHELM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   China wooed 400 foreign travel agents Wednesday
with wine and words of friendship as it tried to persuade them to
bring back lucrative tours that were canceled when martial law was
imposed in Beijing.
   ``The Chinese people will not forget those friends who help us in
difficulty,'' Bo Xicheng, director of the Beijing Tourism
Administration, declared at the start of a two-day seminar.
   The travel agents were reassured by the calm on the streets, but
said the immediate outlook is poor.
   ``These soldiers have their fingers on the triggers,'' Gloria
Copeland of Trinity Travel in Toronto said of troops standing guard
on city streets. ``They're going to have to sling (the guns) behind
their backs before tourists come back.''
   ``People in America take one good vacation a year ... and this
year they're going to Europe,'' said Joe Openshaw of Sunco Travel in
Walnut Creek, Calif. He said lifting martial law ``would help''
China's prospects.
   Bo said, however, that ``we're not going to lift martial law just
because a few tourists won't come to China.''
   Authorities have refused to say how long martial law will last,
keeping an estimated 150,000 soldiers on the streets and in barracks
on the capital's outskirts.
   Tourists and foreign residents fled by the thousands when China's
army fought its way into Beijing on June 3-4, firing on student
pro-democracy protesters and bystanders.
   Luxury hotels emptied except for staff, and gift shop clerks
napped behind their counters as China's tourism industry, which made
$2.2 billion last year, faced major losses.
   Two weeks ago, Bo's office sent invitations to foreign tour
agents it knew, invited them to bring others, then flew them for
free and put them up in luxury hotels in a last-ditch effort to save
the season.
   Zhou Dayan, a spokeswoman for the tourism administration, said
the conference's mission was urgent. ``Maybe in the second half of
the year we can draw some tourists,'' she said.
   Bo recounted the government's explanation that the army crackdown
was necessary, but his main theme was the money being lost on both
sides.
   ``Perhaps we have different views and understandings of some
problems, but this does not prevent us from doing business on an
equal and mutually beneficial basis,'' he told the agents before
they were taken to Tiananmen Square, formerly the heart of the
protests.
   That trip may have backfired, as the travel agents noticed
lingering evidence of the violence that accompanied the crackdown.
   ``I saw the scars on the concrete from the tank tracks and it
reminded me of what I'd seen on television a month ago. Frankly, it
was depressing,'' said an American who spoke on condition of
anonymity.
   Not all responses were negative. Several agents said they had
canceled June and July tours but planned to send groups in August
and September despite continued warnings from foreign governments,
including the United States, against travel to China.
   ``I think the situation may be better than most of us thought it
would be,'' Ms. Copeland said. ``The airport was fine, the hotel was
fine. The only problem we had was when we were on the street and saw
the soldiers and wondered if we would be stopped.''
   She said ``diehard types'' likely will visit this year, ``but
that's not the bulk of the tourists. Many are middle-America types
and they need a bit more time. They will come back, but they're
probably going to say, `Do it next year.'''
</TEXT>
