<FIRST>r i AM-China-Shanghai     07-12 0298</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-China-Shanghai,0308</SECOND>
<HEAD>Police Raids Close Shanghai Bars in Crackdown on Night Life</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-China-Tourism, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police raided Shanghai bars last week in a
crackdown on prostitution in the city's night spots, newspapers
reported.
   Shanghai recently established a Cultural Management Bureau to
oversee the city's ``flourishing cultural market'' of bars, discos,
tea houses, orchestras, art groups and fashion shows, the Guangming
Daily reported Wednesday.
   Regulations imposed by the bureau include a relicensing of all
bands, and a ban on bar girls.
   Before the communists came into power in 1949, the port city was
famous for its nightlife, which in recent years began to flourish
again.
   Shanghai's Liberation Daily, in its Tuesday editions, said
Shanghai has 667 dance halls, tea houses and Japanese-style bars,
288 bands, 1,500 musicians and 450 singers.
   During a three-day investigation last week, authorities visited
87 bars in four districts, closed five of them, suspended the
license of two and arrested 22 bar girls, Shanghai's Wen Hui Bao
reported Sunday.
   The Liberation Daily, another Shanghai newspaper, gave a detailed
account of the midnight bar raid in its Tuesday editions.
   ``This was just a small shop ... with an aisle going down the
middle and dining car-type chairs on the sides .... Using the light
from the television, one could see three pretty and coquettishly
made up girls, one of whom was small and skinny and looked about 15
years old,'' the report said.
   The paper said the women called themselves bar girls, but
actually were prostitutes, and described the bar as a house of
prostitution.
   The crackdown is part of the state's effort to show authorities
rooting out corruption and ``bourgeois liberalization'' _ the
attraction to Western culture.
   Despite the reported Shanghai crackdown, bars in Beijing seem to
be operating as usual.
</TEXT>
