<DOCNO> AP890712-0121 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-12-89 1230EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i PM-Ireland-Politics     07-12 0282</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Ireland-Politics,0289</SECOND>
<HEAD>Haughey Forms New Government in Coalition</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DUBLIN, Ireland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Charles Haughey today won the votes
necessary to form a coalition government after his long-dominant
Fianna Fail party failed to win a majority in national elections.
   The six votes of the Progressive Democratic Party members in the
Dail, Ireland's parliament, gave the 63-year-old Haughey the margin
he needed to head the government for the fourth time.
   Haughey did not immediately name his Cabinet, but it was
announced that two of the 15 ministers and one junior minister would
come from the Progressive Democrats.
   The party's leader, Desmond O'Malley, 50, is a former Fianna Fail
member who led two unsuccessful revolts against Haughey and was
expelled from the party in 1985. The other five Progressive
Democrats in the Dail also defected from Fianna Fail.
   With six members, down from 14 in the previous parliament, the
Progressive Democrats had lost their right to automatic places on
committees.
   Haughey called a national election June 15 in hopes of winning a
majority in the 166-seat Dail, but Fianna Fail wound up with just 77
seats.
   Haughey was forced to resign as prime minister last week after an
inconclusive vote in the Dail, but he remained as head of the
caretaker government.
   Fianna Fail, Gaelic for ``warriors of destiny,'' was formed from
the losing side in Ireland's civil war of 1922-23. Led by Eamon de
Valera, the party formed its first government in 1932 and has been
the top vote-getter since.
   Haughey, the son-in-law of former Prime Minister Sean Lemass, was
elected party leader and prime minister in 1979 in a government that
survived until 1981. He also led governments in 1982 and 1987-89.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
