<FIRST>u a PM-NAACP 1stLd-Writethru a0517 07-12 0614</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-NAACP, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0517,0628</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush Committed to Civil Rights, Quayle Tells NAACP</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 12 grafs to UPDATE with Quayle speech; picks up 7th
graf, `Chrysler became ...</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto DT3</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FREDERICK STANDISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   High infant mortality and dropout rates among
blacks are problems all America must work to overcome, Vice
President Dan Quayle told the NAACP convention today.
   Quayle spoke on the fourth day of the National Association for
the Advancement of Colored People's annual convention in Detroit.
   ``If President George Bush were in the country, you know he would
be speaking to you,'' Quayle said. Bush was in Hungary today as part
of his tour of Eastern Europe.
   Quayle said the Bush administration was committed to promoting
civil rights and the president had met several times with civil
rights leaders. He reviewed the history of the civil rights
movement, including the removal of government-sanctioned racial
segregation.
   ``Now, thanks to much of the work by the NAACP, these racial
barriers have been struck down. But as the slogan says, the struggle
continues,'' he said. ``Today, there is less bigotry than before,
but there is still bigotry _ and bigots.''
   Quayle cited statistics indicating the social and economic
disadvantage of blacks.
   ``Let us not forget that the black infant mortality rate is twice
as high as for whites,'' said Quayle, who also spoke of the
disproportionately high dropout rate among young blacks.
   ``These are not just black problems, these are America's
problems,'' Quayle said.
   NAACP Executive Director Benjamin Hooks, as he had done two days
before, for Secretary of Housing and Urban Development Jack Kemp,
gave a warm introduction to a member of the Bush administration.
   ``When Vice President Quayle was a senator, he did vote to make
Martin Luther King Day a holiday,'' Hooks said. ``He was one of the
few Republicans who voted to override President Reagan's veto of
South African sanctions.''
   On Tuesday, Chrysler Corp. Chairman Lee Iacocca and Hooks
announced the company was pledging to boost opportunities for
minorities and women in salaried positions.
   The ``fair share'' pledge commits the No. 3 automaker to doubling
the number of women and minorities in management roles to 20
percent, said Anthony St. John, Chrysler's vice president for human
resources.
   Chrysler became the nation's 62nd company and the last of the Big
Three automakers to join the program.
   Generally, companies signing the agreement make commitments to
expand access of blacks to entry- and mid-level jobs, increase the
number of black-owned suppliers and appoint blacks to boards of
directors.
   The program also calls on Chrysler to increase the number of
black-owned dealerships, which currently number 72 of about 5,300.
But Iacocca said increasing that would be more difficult than
putting more blacks in management ranks because ``you don't become
an entrepreneur just by raising you hand and saying, `I'd like to be
an entrepreneur.'''
   St. John also said the company expects to maintain its 23-percent
level of minority hourly workers during the next five years.
   Earlier Tuesday, Detroit Mayor Coleman Young told the conference
that blacks who want to help the inner cities should stop spending
money with retailers that move out to the suburbs.
   ``We have to learn to spend our money with our own, and in our
own city,'' he said.
   Michigan Gov. James Blanchard praised a speech Monday by Housing
Secretary Jack Kemp calling for major efforts to upgrade urban
neighborhoods, but said his words must be matched by action.
   ``I understand Secretary Kemp gave a stirring speech here, but
the key will be whether Jack can deliver the Reagan-Bush
administration behind what he wants to do,'' said Blanchard, a
Democrat.
</TEXT>
