<FILEID>AP-NR-07-12-89 1236EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-PenryRetrial     07-12 0286</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Penry Retrial,0295</SECOND>
<HEAD>Prosecutor Seeking Penry Retrial</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LIVINGSTON, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prosecutors have decided to retry a
retarded man whose death sentence for a murder and rape was struck
down last month by the U.S. Supreme Court.
   Without a retrial, the state would have to commute Johnny Penry's
sentence to life imprisonment.
   Penry, 33, was sentenced to death in 1980 for the slaying of
Pamela Carpenter, the 22-year-old sister of former Washington
Redskins kicker Mark Moseley.
   The sentence was vacated by the high court, which said jurors at
Penry's trial should have been instructed that his history of mental
impairment and child abuse might have warranted life in prison
instead.
   But the court disagreed with Penry's lawyers that it is
unconstitutional to execute the mentally retarded.
   Penry's IQ is estimated at between 50 and 60, and experts say he
has the reasoning ability of a 7-year-old.
   District Attorney Terry Brown said Tuesday he hopes to have the
case back in the courtroom by fall, although questions over the
location of the trial, the admission of a 10-year-old confession and
other issues could delay matters.
   Brown said he is convinced the verdict and sentence will be the
same as before.
   ``You're always concerned when you're dealing with this kind of
time lag. For instance, I know of at least two witnesses who have
died since, including one of the arresting officers and Penry's
mother,'' Brown said.
   ``But if I didn't think we'd be able to obtain a death penalty in
retrial, I wouldn't have decided to retry the case.''
   Curtis Mason, a Texas Department of Corrections staff attorney
who represented the former laborer in his Supreme Court appeal, said
Brown wants a retrial for political reasons.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
