<SECOND>PM-North Dakota Drought,0195</SECOND>
<HEAD>Officials Declare Statewide Drought Disaster</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BISMARCK, N.D. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Officials declared a statewide drought
disaster in North Dakota today _ the first step in making farmers
eligible for federal assistance.
   ``The 1988 drought never really ended, although we had some
relief until just a few weeks ago,'' Lt. Gov. Lloyd Omdahl said, in
announcing the disaster declaration for Gov. George Sinner, who is
out of the state.
   ``Now, we're back to a very serious situation,'' Omdahl said.
   Sinner and Omdahl said in a statement that they hoped the
declaration would also call attention to North Dakota's plight. A
North Dakota State University study estimates farmers could lose at
least $541 million in small grains and hay crops as a result of a
deepening drought.
   ``Congress is currently debating a 1989 drought relief package,
so we want to send them an appropriate message regarding our
needs,'' Omdahl said.
   In Washington, Sen. Kent Conrad, D-N.D., introduced a bill
Tuesday to add spring crops to a 1989 drought relief measure. Conrad
said a dozen counties in North Dakota already have suffered crop
losses ranging from 60 percent to 80 percent.
