<FIRST>r a PM-SmoothTalker     07-12 0334</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Smooth Talker,0342</SECOND>
<HEAD>`Smooth Talker' Arrested For Alleged Bigamy</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 58-year-old man who passed himself off as a
doctor had a string of wives and girlfriends across the United
States whom he bilked out of thousands of dollars, police said.
   William R. Dickens was arrested Monday in a downtown Chicago
motel after police collected evidence of at least two women he
married and abandoned, police said.
   He remained in custody today and faced outstanding warrants from
other states. No charges have been filed yet in Illinois, according
to Dan McCullough of the Cook County state's attorney's office.
   ``Apparently his charm worked on women across the country,'' said
Detective Henry Thomas. ``We've had reports of wives or girlfriends
in Texas, Louisiana, Connecticut and Utah, and I don't think they've
all surfaced yet.''
   The 5-foot-10 inch, 265-pound Dickens, who has a South Side
Chicago address, identified himself as Dr. Holis McPhail to many
women he dated or married, said Detective Mike Herbert.
   His alias was the name of an Ogden, Utah, woman Dickens had dated
before stealing her credit cards and disappearing, Herbert said.
   Police said they were tipped off by a Chicago woman who had been
planning to marry Dickens on July 29 in Palm Springs, Calif., but
the woman became suspicious and did some checking on him.
   She subsequently contacted police, and they learned he was wanted
in Louisiana and Texas for felony theft and parole and probation
violations, officials said.
   ``He wasn't the best-looking man you've ever seen,'' said the
woman, who was interviewed by the Chicago Tribune and identified
only as Antoinette, 35. ``He's a big guy. It wasn't that that
attracted me. It was his personality. It was like a dream.''
   Dickens often requested loans of $100 to $150 from Antoinette
because he said he was doing work on a government project and his
assets were put on hold by the Internal Revenue Service, she said.
Dickens allegedly duped another Chicago woman out of $20,000, Thomas
said.
