<SECOND>PM-Second Abduction, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0502,0598</SECOND>
<HEAD>Woman Pleads Innocent to Killing Second Daughter Who Was Reported
Abducted</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 13 grafs with mother pleading innocent, edits to
conform; Picks up 13th graf: `But Herb...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAUL DE LA GARZA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>EDWARDSVILLE, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The mother a 6-week-old girl whose
smothered body was found in a garbage can pleaded innocent today to
murder in a case nearly identical to the death of the woman's older
child three years ago.
   Paula Sims, 30, was indicted Tuesday by a Madison County grand
jury that still was weighing whether to charge her husband, Robert
Sims, 37, in the slaying of their daughter, Heather, said State's
Attorney William Haine.
   Wearing an orange jail jumpsuit and shackles, Mrs. Sims entered
the courtroom of Judge Edward Ferguson to hear the charges against
her and have a written plea entered by attorney Donald Groshong.
   A formal arraignment probably will be scheduled for next week,
said the judge, who refused a motion that bond be set. Mrs. Sims is
being held in Madison County Jail.
   She faces the death penalty if convicted.
   Neither prosecutors nor Groshong made any statement in court
today.
   The nude body of Heather Sims was found May 3 in a trash can
across the Mississippi River from the family's Alton home, four days
after Mrs. Sims reported that a masked gunman had abducted the girl.
   It was an almost identical story she gave police three years
earlier when her first daughter, Loralei, disappeared 13 days after
her birth in 1986. Skeletal remains believed to be Loralei's were
found a few days later about 150 yards from the Simses' home in
rural Brighton in Jersey County.
   That death remains unsolved.
   Alton Detective Jody O'Guinn arrested Mrs. Sims at her parents'
home in Cottage Hills shortly after the indictment was returned and
led her away in handcuffs.
   The grand jury heard more than four hours of testimony from her
parents Tuesday before returning the indictment. They were ordered
to testify after being granted immunity.
   But the prosecutor said other evidence made the state's case.
``The physical evidence was very important,'' Haine said, but he did
not elaborate.
   Defense attorney Groshong refused to comment.
   But Herb Condray, Mrs. Sims' brother-in-law, said police are only
trying to save face by arresting her.
   ``I think the police have egg on their face so bad that they
would do anything,'' Condray said.
   The Simses also have a 17-month old son, Randy, who was placed
into the custody of the Illinois Department of Children and Family
Services during the investigation of Heather's death.
   Before the indictment, Mrs. Sims had been charged in Jersey and
Madison counties with obstruction of justice and concealment of a
homicide in connection with her daughters' deaths.
   She was free on $350,000 bond on those charges.
   Jersey County Sheriff Frank Yocom said the investigation into
Loralei's death continues, but is difficult because the cause of
death was never established.
   The autopsy on Heather revealed she had been suffocated with a
hand over her mouth. The body had freezer burns, leading
investigators to conclude that she had been put in a freezer before
the body was dumped in the trash.
   Mrs. Sims was indicted on two counts of murdering Heather.
   The first count alleges that Mrs. Sims intended to kill the girl.
The second count alleges Mrs. Sims committed an act she knew had the
strong probability of ending in death or great bodily harm.
</TEXT>
