<SECOND>AM-BRF--Thailand-Press,0191</SECOND>
<HEAD>Hello, Sweetheart, Get Me a Tailor</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Reporters attending briefings at
Thailand's Government House have been told to tidy up or stay away.
   Jeans-clad journalists will no longer be welcome in Bangkok's
main government office, Deputy Government Spokesman Likit
Hongladarom said Wednesday.
   A shirt with a collar and tie, or a smart safari suit are now de
rigeuer for all those attending official press conferences, despite
Bangkok's stifling average daytime temperature of about 90 degrees,
he said.
   The order to smarten up was issued by Gen. Kamol Dabbaransi,
personal assistant to Thailand's Prime Minister Gen Chatichai
Choonhaven, Likit said.
   Some reporters chasing the latest hot news story complain that
briefings at Government House can be intolerably sweaty affairs as
the lofty, 19th century building lacks an efficient air conditioning
system.
   Likit said he sympathized with reporters, but they were complying
with the new rules, despite some complaints.
   ``This week everybody is looking very tidy,'' he said.
   Some Bangkok newspapers said that they would pay an allowance to
their reporters and photographers to cover the cost of new suits.
