<FILEID>AP-NR-07-12-89 1336EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a PM-Fires-Glance 1stLd-Writethru a0498 07-12 0367</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Fires-Glance, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0498,0373</SECOND>
<HEAD>Western Forest Fires At A Glance</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 8th graf to show Nebraska fire contained, change acreage
figure, downgrading from 100,000 to between 50,000 and 100,000 acres.</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Fires Rdp, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Here is a state-by-state glance at details on fires in the West:
   _Arizona: About 50 fires have burned 63,000 acres of forest,
range and brush since last week from Grand Canyon to Mexico. Largest
fire had burned up to 14,650 acres along the New Mexico line but was
nearly contained Tuesday.
   _California: Two major brush fires in northern California were
declared contained Tuesday. An arson blaze continued in Big Sur.
They had charred 10,955 acres. In Southern California, the
4,600-acre Mount Laguna fire east of San Diego was 30 percent
contained and some residents were allowed to go back home.
   _Colorado: Higher humidity and lower temperatures helped
firefighters against three major fires that had burned more than
5,000 acres and destroyed 37 homes.
   _Idaho: A 250-acre blaze in Payette National Forest in
west-central Idaho was contained after charring mostly grass and
sagebrush.
   _Montana: A 300-acre blaze near Libby in northwestern Montana was
controlled. Fire started late last week by an untended campfire.
   _Oregon: Crews contained a blaze that charred almost 1,100 acres
on the edge of the Fremont National Forest, the last of the state's
three fires to be contained this week.
   _Nebraska: Firefighters today contained a blaze in the state's
northwest corner that burned between 50,000 and 100,000 acres. About
150 firefighters from about 20 volunteer fire departments, Forest
Service and National Guard fought the blaze.
   _New Mexico: A 10,000-acre fire in Gila National Forest 50 miles
from Silver City was contained late Monday. Two other fires burned
5,700 acres of brush in El Malpais National Monument.
   _Utah: Some firefighters were released after containing three
fires in the Ashley National Forest and a 15,500-acre fire 20 miles
west of the Utah-Colorado border.
   _Washington: Couple of very small lightning-caused fires burned
Tuesday in northeast Washington.
   _Wyoming: One fire burning Tuesday, in Bridger Teton National
Forest about 150 miles southeast of Yellowstone National Park,
charred 3,477 acres from July 4 until it was contained Monday.
</TEXT>
