<FIRST>r a AM-Brites     07-12 0487</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Brites,0511</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bright &amp; Brief</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TRENTON, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   They all represent the same state and
they're all members of the same legislature, but there's a big
difference between members of New Jersey's Senate and Assembly. It
has to do with their appetites.
   During two night-long sessions last month to produce a new
budget, the 80 members of the Assembly chowed down on takeout pizza
and meatball sandwiches.
   ``It cost $400.28 for the two nights,'' said Bradley Brewster,
executive director of the Assembly Republican majority. ``This is
standard fare for late nights. It was pretty austere.''
   Senators, however, were allowed $25 for dinner each day _ or a
maximum of $2,000 for the 40 lawmakers, said a Senate spokesman. The
bills are still coming in, but the senators apparently spent a
little less than their limit, he said.
   The senators also could have used one of several rooms reserved
at a Marriott hotel, although only one or two senators did, the
spokesman said.
   No rooms were set aside for Assembly members, said Majority
Leader Garabed Haytaian.
   ``We only called up and ordered pizzas,'' he said. ``We are not
the Senate.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The city failed to fix a leaky water main at a
city-owned building, so the city gave the city a warning and turned
off the water.
   ``Only in New York,'' moaned Raymond Pilarte, superintendent of
the building.
   Pilarte reported the leak to the city's Department of Housing
Preservation and Development in April.
   Calls went back and forth, but it wasn't fixed.
   On Friday, the city Bureau of Water Supply told Pilarte that
unless the owner repaired the leak by Monday, the water would be
turned off.
   ``They just came in and turned the water off,'' said Pilarte's
wife, Angelina.
   HPD spokeswoman Roz Post said a contractor had agreed to make an
emergency trip.
   ``With the thousands of repairs the city makes on its buildings,
things like this can unfortunately happen,'' Post said.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>ORLANDO, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A flock of ducks skipped town before they
could be evicted from the Wet 'n Wild amusement park for taking free
rides and begging for food.
   The ducks were known for crashing the Lazy River ride and the
water slides, riding along with paying guests.
   An eight-hour effort to capture the birds last week left would-be
captors with only one bird in hand while about 30 of the mallards
still enjoyed their freedom.
   A second roundup was planned Tuesday, but park officials sent
word that the ducks had checked out.
   ``It seems that all the commotion has frightened them away,''
said Carmen Shaw, an environmentalist who led the relocation attempt.
   General manager Richard Faber received hundreds of suggestions
for getting rid of the birds, several saying the ducks could be
moved if they were fed bread doused with liquor.
   ``That was a bit extreme,'' he said. ``We have some juvenile
ducks floating out there.''
</TEXT>
