<FIRST>r i AM-Soviet-Economy     07-12 0550</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet-Economy,0567</SECOND>
<HEAD>Soviet Co-ops in New Alliance Fighting Taxes, Bureaucrats</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CAREY GOLDBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Embattled leaders of new private businesses
protested Wednesday they are being strangled by oppressive taxes and
bureaucrats who portray them as greedy swindlers.
   Officers of the new Alliance of United Cooperatives told a news
conference they were alarmed by signs of swelling anti-cooperative
sentiment from the populace, the state-run media and even President
Mikhail S. Gorbachev, whose reforms gave rise to the privately run
businesses.
   On July 1, some localities in the Ukraine and Byelorussia began
taxing revenues rather than profits at rates as high as 50 percent,
said Vladimir Tikhonov, president of the alliance.
   ``There is an intentional direction toward strangling the
cooperative movement,'' Tikhonov said. The alliance is pressing for
a maximum tax of 20 percent, on profits rather than revenues.
   The small businesses, which usually share their profits among
several owners, are virtually the only visible success in the
economic reform. More than 100,000 have sprung up in just 2{ years,
and they have created 2 million jobs in an otherwise stagnant
economy.
   Although Gorbachev praised the co-ops Jan. 1, he gave them only
lukewarm support Tuesday in a meeting with Leningrad residents. In
response to their complaints that cooperatives charge exorbitant
prices for poor-quality goods, he said local authorities can
regulate their activity.
   Tikhonov said Gorbachev's statement was ``disturbing'' and ``not
thought through.''
   ``It implied that, `We're giving you the right to tax
cooperatives, and if they're stifling you with their prices, you can
stifle them with taxes,''' he said.
   An article in Wednesday's edition of the Communist Party
newspaper Pravda that was headlined, ``Crazy money,'' slammed
cooperatives for hogging bank loan funds, fueling corruption,
laundering money and charging unjustified high prices.
   Pravda said it was in favor of cooperatives, but against ``dirty
wheeler-dealers.''
   Speakers at the news conference said if the cooperatives fail,
the sluggish economy, already plagued by shortages, will slip even
further into crisis.
   ``It is my conviction there can be no economic reform without
intensive development of the cooperative sector,'' Tikhonov said.
   Tikhonov said bureacratic opposition to the cooperatives,
including stereotypes cultivated by state-run media, is intensifying
as government ministries try to fight competition from the private
sector.
   But in an apparently conciliatory move, Tikhonov said the
cooperatives' alliance is seeking ``a dialogue with the government''
and the businesses hope to win more orders from state firms. The
news conference was held in the Foreign Ministry Press Center, an
indication of a certain amount of government support.
   Although the general law on cooperatives encourages their
development, thousands of lesser directives and decrees issued in
bureacratic forays on the upstart businesses threaten their
existence, speakers said Wednesday.
   For example, one Health Ministry decree forbade cooperative
medical clinics from renting state diagnostic equipment, said Yuri
Vorontsov, head of a medical cooperative.
   The cooperative alliance is seeking repeal of all directives
limiting cooperative activities. ``Now we are a united force that
can stand against those decrees,'' said Artyom Tarasov, head of the
cooperative ``Tekhnika'' and depicted by the Soviet press as a
millionaire.
   Tikhonov said if the restrictions on cooperatives are not
canceled, many cooperatives ``will collapse, they'll fall apart,''
hurting not only their employees but also the state enterprises that
have contracts with them.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
