<FIRST>r w AM-BucketSafety     07-12 0147</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bucket Safety,150</SECOND>
<HEAD>Commission Warns Children May Drown in Buckets</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Children should be kept from large buckets,
especially containers that have been converted to household use,
because of the possibility of drowning, the Consumer Product Safety
Commission said Wednesday.
   At least 67 children, most 8- to 12-months-old, drowned in
buckets from 1985-87, the commission said.
   Most drowned in 5-gallon containers, including those originally
designed for bulk products such as paint, food and spackling
compound.
   ``The 5-gallon bucket is particularly dangerous because its
heavier weight makes it more stable than a smaller bucket and
unlikely to tip over when a child uses it to pull up,'' the
commission said.
   The commission said the Cook County, Ill., medical examiners
office first reported the hazard. The office said all 11 bucket
drownings it has investigated since 1985 involved 5-gallon shipping
containers being used as household buckets.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
