<FIRST>r i AM-Cambodia-Commander     07-12 0316</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Cambodia-Commander,0324</SECOND>
<HEAD>Feared Khmer Rouge Commander Asks to Retire</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Khmer Rouge military commander feard
for his supervision of purges and massacres during the group's
Cambodian rule said he wants to retire after Vietnamese troops leave
Cambodia.
   Ta Mok is the third Khmer Rouge leader to announce his retirement
since last month. Diplomats say the Khmer Rouge, the largest
guerrilla group fighting Vietnamese troops in Cambodia, is trying to
clean up its image before an international conference on Cambodia
starting July 30 in Paris.
   Khmer Rouge army radio on Monday carried the text of a June 9
letter that Ta Mok wrote to Khieu Samphan, the nominal leader of the
group. A translation of the broadcast was seen in Bangkok on
Wednesday.
   After a genuine Vietnamese pullout, he wrote, ``I will from then
on ask to cease all activities within Cambodian state
organizations.'' Khieu Samphan approved this Monday, the radio said.
   Vietnam has pledged to pull its troop from Cambodia by the end of
September.
   Ta Mok was a regional military commander when the Khmer Rouge
ruled Cambodia from 1975 to 1978. During that time, hundreds of
thousands of Cambodia's 8 million people died from Khmer Rouge
executions, famine and civil unrest.
   Ta Mok and the other Khmer Rouge leaders fled to the
Thai-Cambodian border to wage a guerrilla war after Vietnam invaded
in late 1978. In recent years, he is believed to have been the top
commander in the northern sector of the border, according to Western
relief workers.
   A radio broadcast Sunday said 63-year-old Nuon Chea, for years
the No. 2 man in the Khmer Rouge hierarchy, had asked to retire. On
June 4, the radio said Pol Pot, who led the Khmer Rouge revolution,
had asked to step down.
   The three men are among a small group of Khmer Rouge leaders
widely considered unacceptable in any peace settlement.
</TEXT>
