<FIRST>u a PM-CottonClub     07-12 0447</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Cotton Club,0460</SECOND>
<HEAD>Judge Orders Defendants to Stand Trial</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LINDA DEUTSCH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A reputed cocaine dealer and two former
bodyguards of ``Hustler'' publisher Larry Flynt were ordered to
stand trial today in the 6-year-old ``Cotton Club'' murder of
theatrical producer Roy Radin.
   Municipal Judge Patti Jo McKay, who heard two months of testimony
about the Hollywood-related killing, said there was sufficient
evidence presented to support convictions of the defendants at a
trial.
   ``It appears to me the offenses ... have been committed and there
is sufficient reason to find (the defendants) guilty,'' she said.
``They are held to answer.''
   The judge also eliminated one special circumstance, but allowed
two others to stand, making the defendants eligible for the death
penalty if convicted at a trial.
   ``It's what we expected,'' said Deputy District Attorney Sally
Thomas.
   The defendants, Karen DeLayne ``Lanie'' Greenberger, Alex Marti
and William Mentzer were impassive as they stood to hear the judge
render her ruling.
   Moments before the decision, Deputy District Attorney David Conn
had argued that Mrs. Greenberger ordered the killing of Radin
because she perceived him as a threat to her business relationship
with producer Robert Evans.
   Conn said Mrs. Greenberger was determined to get Radin out of the
way so she could continue a lucrative deal with Evans to finance the
movie ``The Cotton Club,'' the story of a Harlem nightclub starring
Richard Gere.
   ``Mr. Radin was an obstacle to further negotiations on the
`Cotton Club' deal,'' Conn said. ``Mrs. Greenberger had a motive to
murder Mr. Radin to remove him from the deal. She knew that Mr.
Evans wanted and desired her to have a greater share in the deal
than Mr. Radin wanted her to have.''
   In addition, he said Mrs. Greenberger blamed Radin for a theft of
drugs and cash from her home and held a grudge against him.
   He portrayed Mentzer and Marti as hired killers who carried out
her instructions.
   Radin was last seen stepping into a limousine with Mrs.
Greenberger on May 13, 1983, en route to a business dinner.
   A month later, his body was found in a dry riverbed 65 miles
north of Los Angeles _ a location identified at the hearing as a
frequent target shooting range for the Flynt bodyguards. Radin had
been repeatedly shot in the head.
   The judge ordered the defendants to be arraigned in Superior
Court on July 18. She ordered no bail and said, ``The defendants are
remanded.''
   The defense attorneys presented no final arguments at the
preliminary hearing, which probed the inner workings of Hollywood
deal-making, the private militia of Flynt and the
multimillion-dollar business of cocaine trafficking.
</TEXT>
