<SECOND>PM-Nursing Contract, 2nd Ld - Writethru, a0585,0460</SECOND>
<HEAD>Nurses At Northern California's Largest Pediatric Hospital Walk Off
Job</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 3rd graf to UPDATE number of children transferred, CORRECT
number discharged to 15 sted 20 and UPDATE number of children remaining.</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto OAT1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICH CARTIERE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>OAKLAND, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Striking nurses walked picket lines today
for a second day outside northern California's largest pediatric
hospital, which transferred dozens of critically ill children to
other facilities.
   A line of ambulances began moving young patients out even before
the strike began with the day shift Tuesday morning as some 200
nurses struck for a 26 percent wage increase. Children's Hospital
spokesman Steve Tiger said most of those transferred went to nearby
hospitals, but many children could eventually be sent to facilities
as far away as Los Angeles and Seattle.
   The hospital has transferred 88 children so far, discharged 15
and 41 remained today, Tiger said. Those remaining are the most
critically ill and will be taken care of by doctors and supervisors.
   The hospital issued a statement saying a 7-week-old premature
baby died Tuesday afternoon after being transferred to a Berkeley
hospital. But Tiger said they were not implying the death was linked
to the transfer.
   ``We're definitely not saying that. We think it would be
irresponsible to imply that,'' Tiger said. ``We assumed that the
information would get out anyway. We thought it was more appropriate
that we release it.''
   California Nurses Association spokeswoman Maureen Anderson said
nurses on the picket line didn't know about the death until they
were approached by reporters. Anderson said she was upset the
hospital decided to issue the statement.
   ``This is just going to inflame the situation and I'm sure the
family is having a hard enough time already,'' Anderson said.
   One of the placards carried by a nurse on the picket line read:
``Improve Pay to Improve Care.''
   ``We're special people with special skills and we need special
pay,'' said a 34-year-old picketing nurse, who identified herself
only as Jean.
   The California Nurses Association, which represents the 700
nurses at Children's, rejected an 18 percent wage hike over two
years by a 4-1 margin on Monday.
   ``If we don't do enough to attract people, we won't have the best
and the brightest nurses around for these children,'' said intensive
care nurse Karen Cooper, calling the strike ``a painful step'' to
avert ``an even worse (labor shortage) crisis in the 1990s.''
   Union officials are seeking salaries that would range between
$39,400 and $49,100.
   Children's nurses now make between $32,000 and $39,000, which
places them among the highest paid in the nation.
   No new talks were scheduled. The nurses' previous contract
expired June 30.
</TEXT>
