<HEAD>Eds: `Sonshine' cq</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BARTOW, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A former live-in maid pleaded guilty to
stealing more nearly $900,000 from an elderly paraplegic woman kept
prisoner in her own home.
   Barbara June Stevens, 55, could receive three years in prison at
sentencing Aug. 10.
   Prosecutors said Ms. Stevens confined 71-year-old Valeria Lust to
her Lakeland home by taking away the woman's alker and telephone and
by giving her illegally obtained prescription drugs to keep her
sleepy.
   Some of the $883,534 stolen from the widow in 1987-88 went to
Fountain of Life Inc., a TV ministry in Greenville, N.C., and to
Sonshine Cathedral in Highland City, authorities said.
   Ms. Stevens pleaded guilty Tuesday to charges including
kidnapping, forgery, grand theft and conspiracy. Prosecutors agreed
to drop 55 other charges. She could have received life in prison if
convicted as charged.
