<FIRST>r i AM-China     07-12 0593</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-China,0612</SECOND>
<HEAD>Chinese Leaders Urge Officials to Stress Their Side of Suppression</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-China-Tourism, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM ABRAMS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   China's premier and Communist Party chief on
Wednesday urged their top diplomats to do a better job in presenting
the official version of its suppression of unarmed pro-democracy
demonstrators.
   State-run media also highlighted visits by foreigners in a
propaganda campaign to show that diplomatic relations have not
suffered from international condemnation of the June 3-4 military
crackdown in Beijing.
   Jiang Zemin, newly appointed general secretary of the Communist
Party, told 151 ambassadors and senior diplomats they must ``help
foreign friends get rid of their misunderstandings'' of recent
events in China.
   Jiang said the diplomats must ``increase their work in explaining
the truth to counter rumors of Western reports.''
   The United States and other Western countries have suspended
high-level government contacts and imposed other sanctions to
protest the attack.
   Foreign countries have also denounced the reported arrests of
more than 2,000 people and the executions of at least 27 who joined
protests.
   China claimed the use of force was necessary to put down what it
says was a ``counterrevolutionary rebellion'' to overthrow the
government. It says about 200 civilians were killed in the military
assault on the city.
   Chinese witnesses and Western intelligence sources said the death
toll may have been as high as 3,000.
   Premier Li Peng told the diplomats that overseas Chinese students
who participated in protest rallies will be welcomed back to China
and won't be punished.
   ``Because they were far from the motherland and influenced by the
Western media, they didn't understand the true situation and
participated in protests and said some extremist words,'' state-run
TV quoted Li as saying.
   Many Western countries have extended the visas of students who
say they fear arrest or persecution if they return to China. Many
students say they don't want to return to their country,
accelerating a brain drain of Chinese students who abandon their
homeland and settle abroad.
   The official media told domestic audiences that foreigners were
returning to China and the nation's relations with foreign countries
were back to normal.
   Television showed senior leaders in meetings with tourism
delegates from East Germany, Kuwait and the United States.
   President Yang Shangkun, a key player in the military assault on
student-occupied Tiananmen Square, met David F. Lee and Peter M.
Chow of the Los Angeles branch of the National Association of
Chinese-Americans and praised their efforts to promote U.S.-Chinese
friendship.
   Lee and Chow were in Beijing for a tourism conference. China's
annual $2 billion tourist industry has nearly dried up in the past
month because of the imposition of martial law and the violence in
the capital.
   The official People's Daily on Wednesday also appealed to Taiwan
not to let China's troubles slow down the easing of tensions.
   The daily acknowledged the crackdown on the student movement,
cited by Taiwan as proof the communists cannot be trusted, had hurt
efforts to increase their contacts.
   ``The recent turmoils in some places on the mainland and the
counterrevolutionary rebellion in Beijing plus truth-distorting
propaganda by some Chinese and foreign news media have to some
extent had a negative impact on such activities,'' it said.
   In the past two years, Taiwan has eased restrictions on travel to
the mainland and allowed indirect trade estimated at $2.7 billion
last year, but rejected Beijing's overtures for direct talks.
   Chinese police have arrested 13 people accused of spying for
Taiwan in connection with the pro-democracy movement, and on Tuesday
expelled Taiwanese journalist Huang Teh-pei.
</TEXT>
