<FILEID>AP-NR-07-12-89 1526EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Irish     07-12 0638</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Irish,0659</SECOND>
<HEAD>Haughey Accepts Coalition He Said Wouldn't Work</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DUBLIN, Ireland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Charles Haughey was elected Wednesday to
lead a coalition government, reluctantly ending the go-it-alone
tradition of his Fianna Fail party.
   It will be Haughey's fourth term as Taoiseach, as the Irish prime
minister is called.
   ``The formation of this administration is a new departure in our
political life,'' Haughey told the Dail (parliament). ``My Fianna
Fail colleagues and I are making a wholehearted and sincere
commitment to this new administration.''
   The pact with the six-member Progressive Democratic party ended
nearly a month of uncertainty and maneuvering since Fianna Fail fell
short of a majority in the June 15 elections.
   The government pledged to try to cut the standard tax rate, now
34 percent, to 25 percent by 1993, to create 35,000 jobs per year,
and to restore some of the spending cut from the health service.
   It was the first time that Fianna Fail, which formed its first
government in 1932, had accepted a coalition.
   ``Coalitions don't work,'' Haughey said last week as he tried to
line up the votes to put a minority government in power.
   In the end, however, Haughey was forced to meet Progressive
Democratic leader Desmond O'Malley's demand for two seats in the
cabinet.
   O'Malley will be minister for industry and commerce, and his
party also gained the energy portfolio.
   Brian Lenihan will continue as deputy prime minister but will
shift from foreign minister to defense minister. Lenihan missed the
election campaign while recovering from a liver transplant at the
Mayo Clinic in the United States.
   Gerry Collins, the former justice minister, succeeds him as
foreign minister.
   O'Malley, 50, of Limerick, had been expelled from Fianna Fail in
1985 after leading two unsuccessful revolts against Haughey, the
party leader since 1979.
   Fianna Fail deputies in the Dail voted for the coalition
agreement Tuesday following a private meeting in which, according to
The Irish Times, nearly every speaker opposed the coalition.
   Haughey's previous government, elected in 1987, enjoyed the
support of the second-largest party, Fine Gael, as it embarked on
drastic spending cuts and a round of tax reductions.
   Under that government, Ireland posted trade surpluses after years
of deficits, government borrowing was reduced from 12.9 percent of
gross national product in 1986 to 4 percent this year, and inflation
remained under 4 percent.
   However, a drop of nearly two points in the unemployment rate
still left it at 16 percent, and the numbers of job-seekers leaving
the country increased.
   Haughey called the election after the government was unable to
block a bill to create a fund for hemophiliacs who had contracted
AIDS. That defeat, he said, foreshadowed future difficulties for the
government and he appealed to the nation for a majority.
   After opinion polls found a deep distaste for yet another
election and Haughey agreed to talk about a coalition last week,
Conor Cruise O'Brien wrote in The Times of London that it was the
end of ``civil war politics'' in Ireland.
   ``It was only this week that the politics of civil war _ or
rather the Fianna Fail ideology derived from that memory _ were seen
to interfere with the business of governing the country,'' O'Brien
wrote. ``When the people saw that, they called a halt to it.''
   The coalition was unprecedented, said Michael Gallagher, a
lecturer in politics at Trinity College, but its ``long-term
significance will be apparent only some time down the road.'' If the
coalition falters, he said Wednesday, Fianna Fail might revert to
its no-coalition stance.
   Fianna Fail was formed from the losing side of the 1922-23 civil
war. The losers wanted an independent and united Ireland.
   The winners, who were willing to accept a divided island within
the British commonwealth, are associated with Fine Gael, the
second-largest party with 55 seats in the Dail.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890712-0161 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-12-89 1544EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w AM-B-2Bomber Bjt   07-12 0761</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-B-2 Bomber, Bjt,760</SECOND>
<HEAD>Armed Services Panel Doesn't Budge on Stealth</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DONNA CASSATA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Air Force officials taking their case for the
stealth bomber to the House were met Wednesday with stiff resistance
from budget-conscious lawmakers and a warning that the
half-billion-dollar aircraft could become a ``museum piece.''
   ``Seven to eight billion dollars a year on one weapons system is
twice as much as we're spending on Star Wars. I just can't sell
that,'' Rep. Les Aspin, D-Wis., chairman of the House Armed Services
Committee, told Air Force officials arguing for the second straight
day on Capitol Hill for the B-2 bomber.
   Air Force Secretary Donald Rice and Chief of Staff Larry Welch
said that the radar-evading bomber outpaces improvements in Soviet
air defenses and that termination of the $70 billion program would
undermine the nation's nuclear deterrent force.
   The officials also reminded lawmakers that the government has
already invested about $23 billion in the plane and that stretching
out the program over a number of years could raise the aircraft's
price considerably.
   By Aspin's calculations, a single B-2 bomber could cost about $1
billion.
   ``We hope our witnesses today will be able to put the B-2 program
into perspective for us,'' Aspin said at the start of the hearing.
``Otherwise, there remains the very real possibility that the B-2
will become a museum piece.''
   Members of the House panel reacted to the presentation much the
same way as did members of the Senate Armed Services panel who
listened to the Air Force officials on Tuesday.
   ``When the chairman tells you you're not going to get it
politically, you can put it in your pocket and take it to the
bank,'' said Rep. William Dickinson of Alabama, ranking Republican
on the committee.
   ``I don't want to equate you to a used car salesman _ you did a
good job with the charts,'' said Rep. Larr J. Hopkins, R-Ky. ``We
have to decide do we want to put this much money in a single
program, can we afford to buy this program.''
   Rep. Herbert H. Bateman, R-Va., put it more poignantly.
   ``I want to put my head down and cry,'' he said. ``You made a
compelling case but I don't know where to get the money to pay for
it.''
   Recent estimates put the B-2 bomber at a cost of between $500
million and $750 million a plane, making it the most expensive
aircraft in history.
   The Pentagon is proposing spending $4.7 billion in fiscal 1990
for the bomber and about $24 billion over a three-year peak period _
$7.8 billion in fiscal 1992, $8.4 billion in fiscal 1993 and $7.7
billion in fiscal 1994.
   ``Eight billion on one weapons system,'' Aspin said. ``Only 12
other countries have a defense budget higher than that. ... Is this
conceivable. No chance.''
   Lawmakers have balked at the price for a single plane, and
responded with incredulity to the possiblity of stretching out the
program at an increased cost of about $2 billion more a year.
   ``If you make annual cost acceptable, the sticker price becomes
unacceptable,'' said Aspin. ``If you make sticker price acceptable,
the annual cost becomes unacceptable. I don't know how to fix it.''
   In response, Rice stressed that the B-2 is ``critical to
deterrence,'' and told the committee that ``this system, despite the
sticker shock, comes down as the only candidate for some categories
of things we want to do.''
   Rice and Welch said Pentagon estimates show that the Soviet Union
has spent more than $350 billion on air defense over a 20-year
period and plans to invest more money.
   ``That very expensive array of defenses in largely ineffective
against an aircraft with B-2 capabilities,'' the Air Force said in
its presentation.
   But Aspin questioned why the Air Force always argues that the
Soviet air defense is robust when it discusses the B-2 but then
suggests that the Soviet system is not as impenetrable when it asks
for just $1.4 billion to improve the electronics system of the B-1
bomber, which could be used instead of the B-2.
   ``Soviet air defense let a fellow coming in from Germany in Red
Square,'' Aspin said, referring to the West German youth, Matthias
Rust, who flew undetected into the Soviet Union two years ago.
   Rice argued that the United States cannot predict the level of
capability in the Soviet air defense, ``but we certainly can see the
trend.''
   ``There is no doubt that capability is increasing and increasing
dramatically with improvements to their radars,'' Rice said.
</TEXT>
