<FIRST>r i AM-Afghanistan     07-12 0418</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Afghanistan,0432</SECOND>
<HEAD>Soldiers Fire on Guerrillas After Cease-Fire Ignored</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DILIP GANGULY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KABUL, Afghanistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soldiers fired on guerrilla bases
around Kabul and the eastern city of Jalalabad on Wednesday after
the insurgents rejected a cease-fire call and fired rockets into the
capital, the government said.
   The cease-fire took effect at midnight Tuesday to mark the
Islamic holiday of Eid Al-Adha and was to have lasted four days. It
collapsed after the rebels launched seven rockets on the capital and
government forces fired back, said Foreign Ministry spokesman
Mohammad Nabi Amani.
   He did not know the number of casualties because most offices,
including the Military Information Department, were closed in
observance of the holiday.
   Amani also said rebels fired rockets on Jalalabad, the capital of
Nangarhar province. The guerrillas have been trying to capture the
city, Afghanistan's fifth largest, since March.
   ``We had no option but to fire back,'' the Foreign Ministry
spokesman said.
   Hours before the cease-fire began, government soldiers fired at
least 100 rockets at guerrilla bases in the hills around Kabul, a
city of 2.25 million people.
   The rockets were fired late Tuesday into the Paghman mountains,
12 miles northwest of Kabul, Amani said.
   ``We had information that the opponents had massed a large number
of rockets to hit Kabul during the Eid, so we carried out a
pre-emptive operation,'' he said.
   The government had said its troops would halt offensive actions
until midnight Saturday to celebrate the Islamic holiday, held 40
days after the end of Ramadan, the Moslem month of fasting.
   But a spokesman for one of the seven main guerrilla groups based
in Pakistan rejected the offer.
   ``The cease-fire doesn't have any meaning for the muhajedeen
because we began our fight to get rid of the communists, and the
problem is not solved,'' said the spokesman, who goes by the name of
Wakil.
   The guerrillas, supported by the United States and mostly based
in Pakistan, are trying to overthrow the Soviet-backed government
that seized power in a 1978 coup.
   Afghanistan and the Soviet Union have alleged the guerrillas,
along with Pakistani military advisers, are planning an offensive on
Kabul and President Najib's government has warned it may shell
Pakistan.
   Pakistan has denied Najib's charges it is directly involved in
the attacks.
   The Soviet Union ended nine years of military involvement in
Afghanistan when it withdrew the last of its troops on Feb. 15 under
a U.N.-mediated accord. Moscow has continued to supply arms to the
Kabul government.
</TEXT>
