<FILEID>AP-NR-07-12-89 1621EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Afghanistan-US     07-12 0293</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Afghanistan-US,0302</SECOND>
<HEAD>American Phtographer Says He's Bored With Captivity</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Afghanistan</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DILIP GANGULY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KABUL, Afghanistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An American photographer who has been
jailed in Afghanistan more than a month said Wednesday he is eagerly
awaiting his promised release _ and a chance to see the Baltimore
Orioles play.
   ``It is very depressing here,'' said Tony O'Brien, a free-lance
photographer who was on assignment for Time-Life Inc. when he was
arrested June 8 for illegally entering Afghanistan with Moslem
rebels.
   ``They treat me very well,'' O'Brien said of his jailers. ``But
it (has been) a long time and I get very depressed. My favorite
Baltimore Orioles baseball team is in first place ... I want to go
home and cheer them.''
   O'Brien, 43, of Santa Fe, N.M., met with journalists on the eve
of the Moslem Eid Al-Adha festival. Agents of the Afghan secret
police, KHAD, watched from a distance as the photographer spoke with
reporters in the courtyard of a Kabul residence, where he was
brought from prison.
   The government said it will release O'Brien if a State Department
official comes to Kabul to escort him home.
   The U.S. Embassy in New Delhi said arrangements to send an
officer to Kabul are complete but it has been told O'Brien cannot be
released before the Moslem holiday ends Saturday.
   O'Brien was covering the Afghan civil war from Pakistan, the base
for the seven main guerrilla groups fighting the Afghan government.
   The photographer said he passed time trying to make chess pieces
so that he could teach the game to his cellmate, Nader Ali, an
Afghan.
   ``Whenever I play checkers with him he beats me,'' O'Brien said.
``I want to him make him play chess and then beat him.''
</TEXT>
