<FIRST>r i AM-Korea     07-12 0480</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Korea,0496</SECOND>
<HEAD>Police Arrest Reporter; Secret Agents Raid Dissident Newspaper</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By M.H. AHN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police on Wednesday arrested a
television reporter and five other people accused of anti-government
writing, and intelligence agents raided the newsroom of a dissident
newspaper.
   Police said leaflets written by television scriptwriter Yoo
Mong-hee, 24, and five others, aimed at promoting North Korea,
Seoul's communist foe. The leaflets denounced ``Yankee imperialists
who have colonized Korea'' _ a slogan common among radical South
Koreans. They are a minority demanding the United States withdraw
its 43,000 troops in the country.
   The six were charged with violating national security laws,
police said.
   About 40 intelligence agents and 100 police forced their way
through the locked gates of the Hankyoreh newspaper and seized
pictures and notepaper as evidence of a lawmaker's illegal trip to
North Korea.
   About 1,000 riot troopers surrounded the compound and laid out
mattresses to prevent suicide attempts.
   Scuffles broke out when about 30 reporters tried to block the
agents, shouting, ``We refuse to be searched!'' and ``Press
freedom!''
   Police shoved the reporters into a van until they completed their
search.
   ``The surprise search at dawn of the newspaper's editorial room
is unprecedented and is never tolerable,'' said Hankyoreh publisher
Song Kon-ho. ``We will continue our struggle to win a free and
independent press.''
   Wednesday's raid came two days after reporters staged a sit-in
and prevented officers using a search warrant to obtain the material.
   The legislator, Suh Kyung-won, was charged with national security
violations for his August 1988 trip to see North Korean leader Kim
Il Sung. Nine others were jailed and charged with failing to report
Suh's trip, a crime in South Korea.
   An arrest warrant has been issued for Hankyoreh reporter Yun
Chae-gol but action was delayed because he was hospitalized.
   Suh reportedly approached Yun and suggested a story about his
trip, but changed his mind later and the story never was written.
   Witnesses said intelligence agents and police searched the
reporter's desk and files Wednesday and took 23 photographs and some
sheets of memo paper with a North Korean letterhead.
   Opposition parties and the National Federation of Journalist
Labor Unions, which represents most South Korean reporters,
protested that the search violated press freedom.
   President Roh Tae-woo has said he is cracking down on radicals
who want the divided peninsula unified and whom he accuses of
threatening national security. Opponents say the clampdown is an
excuse to suppress all dissent in South Korea.
   Roh accuses North Korea of encouraging secret visits by South
Koreans to stir up unrest. He has postponed parliamentary and other
talks with North Korean officials this month.
   In a letter sent Wednesday to North Korea, Seoul proposed Red
Cross talks on the exchange of hometown visits by separated families
be delayed until Aug. 2. North Korean has proposed holding the talks
Friday.
</TEXT>
