<FIRST>r i AM-SriLanka     07-12 0504</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Sri Lanka,0519</SECOND>
<HEAD>India Says No Withdrawal Until Peace Accord Implemented</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PARICK CRUEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COLOMBO, Sri Lanka (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   India said Wednesday it will not
withdraw its peacekeeping troops from Sri Lanka until the
implementation of a peace accord aimed at ending an insurgency by
Tamil rebels.
   Indian Prime Minister Rajiv Gandhi made the declaration in a
letter to President Ranasinghe Premadasa.
   ``India has traditionally been mindful of the sanctity of the
agreements it signs with other countries and of commitments solemnly
undertaken under such agreements,'' Gandhi said in the letter.
``India will under no circumstances deviate from this policy
affecting our concerns.''
   The message amounted to a rejection of Premadasa's appeal to
Gandhi to withdraw the 40,000 Indian soldiers deployed in Sri Lanka
by the end of the month.
   The troops were deployed after India and Sri Lanka signed an
accord July 29, 1987, that called for ethnic Tamil rebels to
surrender their weapons in exchange for limited autonomy.
   India moved in troops to enforce the Tamil surrender, but the
Indian soldiers began fighting the largest Tamil militia, the
Liberation Tigers of Tamil Eelam, when the group refused to accept
the accord.
   Colombo asked India to withdraw its troops after it started talks
with the Tamil Tigers in May, the first direct contact between the
two sides since the insurgency began in 1983.
   India says a premature withdrawal of its troops could spark more
ethnic violence on the Indian Ocean island and could lead to the
killing of moderate Tamils. The impasse has soured relations between
the nations.
   ``I have repeatedly said that the Indian peacekeeping forces'
withdrawal should be worked out through joint consultations along
with a simultaneous schedule for the implementation of the India-Sri
Lanka agreement,'' Gandhi said in his letter. ``We are willing to
resume discussions on this subject at any time and place of your
convenience.''
   Gandhi also said that if joint consultations were not possible,
``we will have to decide the details of the .. withdrawal
unilaterally, consistent with our responsibilities and obligations.''
   The Tamil insurgency has left about 9,000 people dead, including
about 800 Indian soldiers.
   India became involved in the ethnic troubles because of the
sympathies of its politically powerful 60 million Tamils to the
rebel cause.
   The 3 million predominantly Hindu Tamils in Sri Lanka complain of
discrimination by the Buddhist Sinhalese, who make up 75 percent of
the island's 16 million people.
   Also Wednesday, the government closed the nation's six
universities and sent in security forces to search the campuses in a
crackdown on Sinhalese militants.
   Colleges reopened May 10 after being closed for two years in an
effort to curb student unrest and violent anti-government
demonstrations.
   Four of the universities are in the island's central and southern
districts, the stronghold of the Sinhalese radical People's
Liberation Front. The other two are in the northeast.
   The government blames the Sinhalese radicals for more than 3,500
political killings since then. The extremists allege too many
concessions were given to the Tamils.
</TEXT>
