<FIRST>u i AM-Tasnadi'sReturn     07-12 0388</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Tasnadi's Return,380</SECOND>
<HEAD>Return After 38 Years Seems Like a Dream</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KEVIN COSTELLOE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BUDAPEST, Hungary (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Charles Tasnadi, who flew home to
Hungary aboard Air Force One 38 years after fleeing his communist
homeland, said Wednesday he's worried his return is all a dream that
has made him late for work in Washington.
   Tasnadi, 64 and an Associated Press photographer covering
President Bush's trip here, spoke of the emotion he feels seeing the
sites from his childhood, including the bridge he used to cross on
the way to school and the church he attended.
   ``It's so unreal that I see Hungarian writing over shops and
commercial places, as well as on street signs _ all in Hungarian,''
Tasnadi told a colleague.
   ``I said to myself, `now I am going to wake up in Washington,
discovering that I am late to work.'''
   In reality, Tasnadi has become something of a celebrity.
   Wednesday night, as other photographers took his picture, Tasnadi
and members of his wife's family, who still live in Hungary, posed
with George and Barbara Bush at a presidential reception held in the
U.S. ambassador's house.
   ``How are you, Sir?'' Bush boomed out as Tasnadi approached.
``Good to see you.''
   Bush had met with Tasnadi as the presidential jetliner flew
toward Budapest on Tuesday and, the photographer said, told him,
``I'm so happy for you that you are returning the way you are
returning.''
   Tasnadi said he told Bush that several relatives, including two
of his wife's sisters, were still in Hungary.
   ``I would like to meet them,'' Tasnadi quoted the president as
saying.
   So, after a day as part of the photographic pool covering the
president, Tasnadi gathered up his relatives and introduced them to
the president.
   Tasnadi was just shy of his 26th birthday when he and his
sweetheart, Maria, seized upon the first heavy snowfall of the
1950-51 winter to seek a new life. A championship skier, he
concocted a story about heading for the slopes for skiing to avoid
suspicion.
   Joining a group of six other adults and two children, the couple
slipped into Austria through communist mine fields, eluded Soviet
guards and made it to Salzburg several days later. He quickly
married Maria, who stayed home this time even though she has been
back to Hungary twice..
</TEXT>
