<FIRST>u i AM-Bush-Crowds 1stLd-Writethru a0642 07-12 0622</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bush-Crowds, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0642,610</SECOND>
<HEAD>Throughout Budapest, a Warm Welcome</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Inserts 2 grafs with Bush commenting on reception after 14th
graf pvs, The youngsters.</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Bush Rdp, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GIRARD C. STEICHEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BUDAPEST, Hungary (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Wherever he went Wednesday in this city
of old world charm, George Bush was given a warm welcome that
reflected Hungary's fascination with America.
   At the university where he got a standing ovation, in the market
where he bought a dozen peaches, on the running track where he
jogged with Hungarian children, his reception was enthusiastic.
   And it was clear from his first remarks here, to 10,000 people
who had withstood torrential rains and high winds for Tuesday's
arrival ceremony, that Bush was appreciative.
   ``Long after this rain is gone,'' he said then, ``I'm going to
remember the warmth of the welcome of the people of Hungary.''
   Wednesday's events, if anything, were fodder for even fonder
memories. Thousands lined the presidential motorcade routes, pouring
out of offices and stores to wave or just get a glimpse of their
important guest.
   The fascination of Hungarians extended even to the downtown press
centers set up for the Bush trip, where gaggles gathered throughout
the day.
   ``Look, White House,'' one Hungarian father proudly told his son
as a reporter wearing a White House pass dashed by.
   After early morning meetings with the country's leaders, Bush met
with 13 students and wound up giving two a ride to Karl Marx
University for his speech lauding Hungary's moves toward a
free-market economy.
   Along the way, he abruptly had his motorcade stopped to greet
wellwishers lining his path. Plunging into the crowd, at one point
he spent more than a minute talking with three small children.
   After the speech, interrupted numerous times by applause and
given a standing ovation at its end, Bush was surrounded by another
adoring crowd at the nearby Dimitrov Square food market.
   The president paid for his peaches and, making his way through
the crowded wrought-iron market, told trailing reporters, ``I
recommend these to you.''
   Ebullient, Bush shook hands, signed autographs and blew kisses to
the crowds.
   Later on, he was signing autographs again _ this time on kids'
jogging shoes.
   The youngsters were his workout partners as he did laps at a
sports complex. The gaggle of 30 young runners then crowded around
Bush, thrusting their shoes and scraps of paper for his signature.
   Asked at day's end to assess his visit, Bush told a Hungarian
television interviewer:
   ``My reaction is a very emotional reaction because they (the
crowds) made both Barbara and me feel welcome. ... I think they were
saying they liked the United States of America very much and, of
course, as an American I'm very moved by that.''
   The warm welcome reflected the Hungarian _ indeed, east European
_ fascination with anything from America, the land that symbolizes
the freedom and prosperity many Soviet bloc citizens feel they have
been denied for 40 years.
   Budapest's crowds have been larger and more exuberant than those
in Warsaw, where turnouts of just 2,000 to 4,000 people at
wreath-laying ceremonies on Monday led to press speculation that
Bush's first presidential foray into eastern Europe would not rival
the rapturous crowds that recently greeted Soviet President Mikhail
S. Gorbachev in West Germany or France.
   Even before Budapest's warm welcome, however, that had begun to
change in Gdansk, the tough port city that gave birth to the East
bloc's strongest opposition movement, Solidarity.
   Thousands lined the streets when Bush rode into the city Tuesday.
More than 25,000 massed when Bush and Solidarity founder Lech Walesa
spoke at the Gdansk monument to workers killed when government
troops opened fire on strikers in 1970.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
