<FILEID>AP-NR-07-12-89 1707EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Mexico-Elections     07-12 0498</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Mexico-Elections,0515</SECOND>
<HEAD>Durango Votes as Count Continues in Previous Elections</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ISAAC A. LEVI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Voters in the state of Durango chose a new
state legislature and mayors Wednesday, while opposition politicians
complained about slow returns in other state elections and accused
the governing party of fraud.
   The governing Institutional Revolutionary Party, known as PRI,
always has been strong in Durango and was expected to win a majority
of the 39 races for mayor and the 15 seats in the legislature.
   Another 10 seats are distributed to five minority parties in
proportion to the votes they receive.
   Most of the state's 1,488 polling stations opened on schedule at
8 a.m. Workers were given the day off, and turnout was reported
strong among the 709,000 registered voters.
   ``It's a holiday, and all is very peaceful,'' said Ruben
Cardenas, editor of the newspaper Cima in the city and capital of
Durango. ``Only seven polling stations opened about an hour late
because they didn't receive ballots and other documents on time.''
   As is usual in Mexico, official returns were not expected for at
least a week. Parties may obtain partial results through their poll
watchers.
   The conservative National Action Party hoped to win eight
municipal elections. ``Let's be realistic, we can't go whole hog,''
said the party's leader, Federico Linc Altamirano.
   The leftist Democratic Revolutionary Party said it hoped to win
seven municipal elections.
   There are also four other small leftist parties.
   Landlocked Durango, where John Huston's film ``The Treasure of
the Sierra Madre'' was filmed, lives from timber, mining, farming
and cattle ranching.
   Wednesday's Durango elections and those in five other states July
2 were seen as a test of President Carlos Salinas de Gortari's
promise to reform an election system that has kept the PRI in power
for 60 years.
   The PRI easily won the July 2 elections for state legislatures in
its strongholds of Campeche and Zacatecas, but the elections for a
new legislature and mayors in the northern state of Chihuahua were
marred by accusations of irregularities.
   For the first time in its history, the PRI conceded defeat in a
gubernatorial race. The winner in the state of Baja California was
Ernesto Ruffo of the National Action Party.
   But PAN leaders complained Wednesday because the state election
board had not yet released full returns for the election of four
mayors and the 24-seat legislature.
   Ruffo, who takes office Nov. 1 for a six-year term, told a news
conference Tuesday night his party plans to contest some of the
results when the state legislature meets to certify the elections.
   In Michoacan state, leaders of the leftist Democratic
Revolutionary Party were demanding a new election, claiming the
returns giving the PRI 12 of the 24 seats in the new assembly were
fraudulent.
   The electoral board in that western state gave the Democratic
Revolutionary Party six seats. Another six seats are being
distributed to minority parties in proportion to the votes they
polled.
</TEXT>
