<FILEID>AP-NR-07-12-89 1710EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Colombia     07-12 0459</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Colombia,0475</SECOND>
<BYLINE>Organization of Four Rebel Groups Says It Wants Peace Talks ^By
TOM WELLS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOGOTA, Colombia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An alliance of leftist guerrillas said in
a message published Wednesday that it wants peace talks with the
government of President Virgilio Barco.
   However, another guerrilla force, the National Liberation Army,
launched two attacks, one on an oil pipeline and another on oil
storage tanks owned by the U.S. company Texaco. A series of such
attacks has seriously damaged oil production in this country.
   The Simon Bolivar Organization, a loose political organization
that speaks for four guerrilla groups, said in its message that it
wants to work toward ``peace with democracy and social justice.'' It
did not elaborate.
   The group takes its name from the Colombian independence hero.
   Its message was sent to a commission appointed by Barco, a
civilian president, to advise him on the possibility of talks with
guerrilla groups. It was also published by the Bogota newspapers El
Tiempo and El Espectador.
   The commission's members are Roman Catholic Cardinal Mario
Revollo Bravo, former presidents Misael Pastrana Borrero and Alfonso
Lopez Michelsen, and the president of Colombia's National
Organization of Industrialists, Fabio Echeverri.
   Peace talks have had several false starts in Colombia in the last
six years.
   One guerrilla group belonging to the Simon Bolivar Organization,
the April 19 Movement, or M-19, declared a cease-fire earlier this
year. It is working independently toward negotiations with the
government.
   M-19 takes its name from the date of a 1970 presidential election
that dissidents dismissed as fraudulent.
   In an effort to encourage peace talks, Barco offered pardons last
week to guerrillas who give up their weapons. He said legislation
for pardons will go to Colombia's congress next week.
   Other groups in the Simon Bolivar Organization are the Colombian
Revolutionary Armed Forces, the People's Revolutionary Army and the
Quintin Lame.
   There are an estimated 10,000 leftist guerrillas in Colombia.
   The National Liberation Army, which has sworn never to negotiate
with the government, blew up a pipeline and attacked storage tanks
Tuesday night, the national police said in statements.
   One attack on the country's Pacific coast oil pipeline caused a
spill of thousands of gallons of oil near the town of Bugalagrande,
the Colombian radio chain RCN said. Bugalagrande is 125 miles west
of Bogota.
   The group's other attack was in Medellin, where guerrillas hurled
hand grenades at big storage tanks owned by Texaco, the national
police said.
   The tanks did not explode, and there was no loss of oil, the
police said.
   No casualties were reported in either attack.
   Guerrilla attacks have brought Colombia's oil production down to
312,000 barrels a day from 420,000 barrels last January, the state
oil company Ecopetrol said in a news release Wednesday.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
