<FIRST>r i AM-BarbaraBush     07-12 0414</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Barbara Bush,400</SECOND>
<HEAD>First Lady Tours Home for Handicapped, Refugee Camp</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Bush Rdp, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BUDAPEST, Hungary (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Barbara Bush had an emotional tour of a
home for handicapped children on Wednesday and visited a refugee
camp for some of the 30,000 ethnic Hungarians driven from their
homes in Romania.
   She also said she'd love to come back to Hungary when the
president sends the first Peace Corps volunteers to this East Bloc
country to spread the teaching of English.
   The first lady was greeted by 11 children when she arrived at the
St. Anne's home for handicapped children, one of only two the Roman
Catholic church is allowed to operate under the Hungarian Ministry
of Health.
   Mrs. Bush appeared on the verge of tears several times as the
youngsters, many in wheelchairs, performed a skit of Biblical songs
and recitations.
   Mrs. Bush hugged a child and exclaimed, ``Beautiful, beautiful.''
   ``I feel God's love in this wonderful house,'' Mrs. Bush wrote in
the guest book. ``God bless you all. Thank you for letting me share
this great moment. I will care more, thanks to you.''
   Later in the day, Mrs. Bush traveled to a refugee settlement
outside Budapest to tour the facility, which houses ethnic
Hungarians who have fled what they say are repression and dire
shortages in Romania.
   Hungarian officials have said that up to 30,000 ethnic Hungarians
have fled Romania.
   As Mrs. Bush toured the facility, she was told that the family
whose house she was to visit was unable to get through the tight
security for her visit.
   ``Let's get them,'' she said to an aide.
   Peter and Dalmo Felfaliva were escorted to the house and the
first lady exclaimed ``your house is lovely'' as they walked through
the small kitchen and dining room.
   Mrs. Bush, who rounded out her tour of the settlement by signing
autographs and patting children in an eager crowd of well-wishers,
told reporters:
   ``I have often thought the worst thing that could happen to you
would be to have your country taken away from you, and the second
worst thing would be to have no one accept you in their country with
loving arms.''
   At the impromptu press conference, she also declared she'd ``like
to come back with the Peace Corps. I love the Peace Corps.''
   Earlier in the day, her husband announced to applause at
Budapest's Karl Marx University that he would send Peace Corps
volunteers so that more Hungarians could learn English.
</TEXT>
