<FIRST>r w AM-CongressionalTravel     07-12 0568</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Congressional Travel,560</SECOND>
<HEAD>Congress Flies Frequently and Free, Study Says</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LARRY MARGASAK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Members of Congress spent more than $13.5
million for overseas travel in 1987-88, often shunning commercial
arlines in favor of the military's more expensive executive
transport service, a study said Wednesday.
   Public Citizen, an independent congressional watchdog, counted
1,053 trips abroad in the two-year period, with House members
stopping most frequently in West Germany, France and the United
Kingdom and senators preferring Switzerland, France and Costa Rica.
   ``A review of congressional foreign travel reveals that some
trips appear to be mere junkets with no compelling purpose,'' the
report, entitled ``Free Flying Congress,''concluded.
   In the junket category, the report said, was a journey to five
countries by four House Rules Committee members and four panel staff
members. The committee sets rules for floor debate, but unlike other
committees, has no role in drafting legislation.
   Public Citizen also questioned the need for a trip by 13 House
members and seven staffers to Australia for seven days to help
celebrate the centennial of that nation's parliament.
   The report said it is legitimate for the public to ask Congress,
``Why is the more expensive military transportation used when
commercial travel is generally available?''
   The likely answer, the report said, is that members like the
convenience of the Air Force's 89th Military Airlift Wing, which has
most of its planes at Andrews Air Force base in Washington's
Maryland suburbs. The wing includes the presidential jets and and
other aircraft that fly members of Congress and top executive branch
officials around the world.
   Spouses of members often get free transportation on the overseas
trips, because they don't have to pay when empty seats are available
on military aircraft that have already been chartered for lawmakers.
   ``Because they are not assessed these travel costs, spouses and
other guests are not generally listed in congressional travel
documents, thus making it difficult for constituents to discern when
family or other guests travel with members,'' the report said.
   Reporting rules are so inadequate, the report added, that
published costs of overseas trips are often underestimated.
   The information on members of the 100th Congress, who served in
1987 and 1988, was compiled from figures furnished by committees and
from military records.
   Altogether, 306 House members took 827 trips abroad at a cost of
at least $11.5 million, the report said, while 80 senators went on
226 trips costing more than $2 million.
   The most ``frequent flier'' in the House was Rep. Stephen Solarz,
D-N.Y., chairman of the Asian and Pacific affairs subcommittee of
the Foreign Affairs Committee. He made 14 trips during the two-year
period, making 39 stops in foreign countries, the report said.
   Other frequent travelers, with nine trips, were Rep. George
Crockett, D-Mich., chairman of the House Foreign Affairs western
hemisphere subcommittee, whose trips included 29 stopovers; House
Armed Services Committee Chairman Les Aspin, D-Wis., with 20 stops;
and House Agriculture Chairman E. Kika del la Garza, D-Texas, who
had 13 stops.
   The top Senate overseas fliers were Christopher Dodd, D-Conn.,
chairman of the Senate Foreign Relations western hemisphere
subcommittee, with nine trips and 19 stopovers; Arlen Specter,
R-Pa., a member of the Intelligence Committee, with nine trips and
at least seven stops (some of his stopovers were not revealed); and
John McCain, R-Ariz., a member of the Armed Services Committee, with
eight trips and 10 stops.
</TEXT>
