<FILEID>AP-NR-07-12-89 1851EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-Children'sTV     07-12 0428</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Children's TV,440</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bill Would Impose Federal Control Over Children's TV</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAY ARNOLD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Congress must impose significant federal
control over children's television so the medium can be used to
educate the young, Sen. Tim Wirth said Wednesday.
   Broadcasters must ``transform children's television from a `vast
wasteland' to a source of intellectual stimulation and enrichment,''
the Colorado Democrat said in testimony before the Senate
Communications subcommittee.
   Wirth, testifying for a bill he authored to condition license
renewal on broadcasters providing educational shows aimed at
children, said ``broadcasters seem to have abandoned educational
children's programs'' in the wake of the ``deregulation frenzy'' of
the Reagan administration.
   ``Today, not one of the three major commercial broadcast networks
offers a single, regularly scheduled, weekday educational program
for children,'' he said. ``There is no question about it _ the
educational needs of America's children are not being serviced by
the nation's television broadcasters.''
   Wirth's bill goes considerably beyond another measure on
children's TV introduced by Sens. Howard Metzenbaum, D-Ohio, and
Frank Lautenberg, D-N.J.
   Wirth's bill would:
   _Reimpose limits on advertising time in children's TV shows that
the Federal Communications Commission repealed in 1984. Those limits
are 9.5 minutes of commercials per hour on weekends and 12 minutes
per hour during weekdays.
   _Reclassify so-called program-length commercials as
advertisements, thereby effectively eliminating them.
   _Require broadcasters to give advance public notice of programs
designed specifically to educate and inform children.
   The Metzenbaum-Lautenberg bill is identical to a measure that
passed Congress last year, only to be pocket-vetoed by President
Reagan. A companion measure is before the House.
   Metzenbaum called children's television an ``abomination'' that
``is truly an embarrassment to our nation.''
   Edward O. Fritts, president of the National Association of
Broadcasters, said his group supported the Metzenbaum bill, which he
called a ``fair and reasonable compromise.'' He called Wirth's bill
``unwise and unworkable.''
   Fritts said broadcasters are losing young audiences to cable TV
and VCRs, while production costs for kids' shows are increasing.
   ``Further restrictions and more stringent programming
requirements run the risk of knocking the children's television
marketplace even further out of balance,'' Fritts said, urging the
subcommittee to reject Wirth's bill.
   DeWitt Helm, president of the Association of National
Advertisers, opposed both bills, contending the restrictions are
unconstitutional, don't protect children and invite further federal
advertising curbs.
   Subcommittee Chairman Sen. Daniel Inouye, D-Hawaii, said Congress
had ample precedent for imposing TV ad restrictions. Children, he
said, were a special audience and called the children's TV bill the
most important legislation the panel would consider this year.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
