<FILEID>AP-NR-07-12-89 1856EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-TribalPartnership     07-12 0474</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Tribal Partnership,463</SECOND>
<HEAD>Hopi Tribe, University Join to Improve Reservation Life</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JILL LAWRENCE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Education Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Hopi tribe and a state university signed an
unusual agreement Wednesday making them partners in a drive to
improve education, cultural resources and economic opportunities on
the tribal reservation.
   ``Today we are beginning to work at trying to intertwine our
culture with the needs of the progressive world,'' Ivan Sidney,
chief of the insular Hopi tribe, said at a signing ceremony
witnessed by Interior Secretary Manuel Lujan and other officials.
   ``We want to be self-sufficient,'' Sidney said. ``We need a
helping hand from the federal government but we do not want to be
totally dependent on the social programs of this country. We have
chosen Northern Arizona University to help us achieve
self-sufficiency.''
   NAU is located in Flagstaff near the Hopi reservation and enrolls
about 800 American Indian students, one of the largest enrollments
in the country.
   Under the agreement, the university and the tribe will work
together to set up a model elementary school; increase child and
family education services; train Hopi teachers; develop a
reservation-wide tourism plan; build a shopping center; set up a
credit association; conduct a labor market study, and strengthen
local businesses.
   Other projects include drafting plans to manage natural
resources, handle solid waste and improve roads; establishing
capital improvement and trust funds; building a new Hopi museum; and
developing two new cultural centers including restaurants, shops and
motels outside the reservation in Winslow and Scottsdale.
   ``We don't believe that there's any program like this in
existence in the country, nor has there ever have been,'' said NAU
president Eugene Hughes. ``We're going to be working with them on
their goals. We see it as a very cooperative venture of mutual
benefit to the Hopi and the university.''
   Hughes estimated the first-year cost of the arrangement, which
takes effect immediately, at $500,000. Sources of money include the
tribe, the university budget, private foundations and corporations,
and the federal Bureau of Indian Affairs, which already is involved
in education activities on the reservation.
   Lujan called the agreement ``a model that can be used in other
areas. Unless those affected set the priorities, the program is not
going to be effective. Everything I see about this spells success.
This is truly self-determination.''
   Asked if the Bureau of Indian Affairs was supposed to be doing
the types of things identified in the agreement, Sidney said yes.
But he added, ``We can't wait on BIA. We have to go forward... We
have to provide direction, set up priorities for what we want. We
have not done that'' until now.
   Hughes said half of the country's Indians live within 250 miles
of NAU. He said the university already has discussed entering into
similar agreements with the Navajo and White Mountain Apache tribes.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
