<FIRST>r w AM-HazardousMaterials     07-12 0481</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Hazardous Materials,470</SECOND>
<HEAD>Panel Concerned About Half Million Hazardous Materials Trips Daily</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID BRISCOE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Government rather than the chemical industry
should track the half a million daily shipments of hazardous
materials over the nation's roadways, the chief sponsor of a bill
supported by the nation's firefighters said Wednesday.
   Another congressman said, however, that the relatively low number
of fatalities, injuries and property losses may not justify
proposals that could cost the chemical and trucking industries
hundreds of millions of dollars a year.
   The House Public Works and Transportation subcommittee on surface
transportation is considering changes in the law to increase
training requirements for drivers, make regulations more uniform
from state to state and keep track of all hazardous cargo with a
nationwide computer system.
   Rep. Douglas Applegate, D-Ohio, said the bill he is sponsoring
would shift control of hazardous materials shipments, sometimes
abbreviated on road signs as ``hazmat,'' from the chemical industry
to federal, state and local governments.
   ``We believe this shift is vital to protect the health and safety
of our constituents and our communities,'' Applegate said.
   A 1980 agreement between the Transportation Department and
chemical manufacturers set up an industry-run system called Chemical
Transportation Emergency Center, or Chemtrec. It gives local police,
firefighters and others a number to call for information on
hazardous cargo so they will know how to handle various chemicals in
an accident.
   But Applegate said the ``answering service'' is useful only when
the materials involved are known, and this may be difficult at the
site of a crash where chemicals have spilled out and the vehicle is
smashed or ablaze.
   He said placards required on trucks carrying hazardous materials
often are missing or incorrect and the Transportation Department's
emergency response guidebook is not always up to date.
   The Chemtrec system, said Applegate, is ``totally inadequate to
protect the American public.''
   But Rep. Bud Shuster, R-Penn., ranking minority member of the
subcommittee, said hazardous cargo hauls were involved in only 17 of
the 48,200 traffic fatalities in 1988 and 158 of the nearly 700,000
injuries.
   Shuster questioned whether the hundreds of millions of dollars
that might be collected from shippers or others under proposed
legislation were needed.
   Clifford J. Harvison, president of the National Tank Truck
Carriers, said the tank truck industry supports legislation that
would make laws more uniform regarding hazardous materials.
   ``Trucks cross thousands of jurisdictional boundaries daily, and
carriers cannot tailor the equipment and operational characteristics
of each truck and driver to meet the singular requirements of a
given community,'' Harvison said.
   Frederick H. Nesbitt of the International Association of Fire
Fighters said a system is needed to give emergency personnel quick
information about any hazardous cargo involved in an accident.
   ``The unnecessary dangers our firefighters face every day due to
an antiquated reporting system are inexcusable in this age of high
technology,'' Nesbitt said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
