<FIRST>r w AM-US-HungaryFund     07-12 0340</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-US-Hungary Fund,350</SECOND>
<HEAD>First Mutual Fund Set Up to Deal in Hungarian Stocks</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CARL HARTMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Communist-ruled Hungary will allow its National
Bank to set up a $50 million mutual fund to invest in securities
issued by the nation's private companies.
   The announcement of First Hungarian Fund Ltd., the first mutal
fund among the Communist-ruled countries of Eastern Europe, was made
Wednesday by the International Finance Corp.
   The corporation, a part of the World Bank, is owned by 133
governments _ including Hungary and the United States. Its
president, Barber Conable, is an American.
   Corporation spokeswoman Monique Amaudry said the Hungarian
government would own some, but not a majority, of shares in some
companies in which the fund will invest.
   ``The fund is an offshoot of Hungary's privatization program,''
she said.
   Budapest, after more than 40 years, also has a small stock market.
   The corporation makes loans to private companies in Third World
countries, and to some companies run along private lines but owned
largely by Communist governments. It often buys a small number of
shares in such companies.
   It has already made four investments in Hungary, including stock
in Unicbank, a Hungarian commercial bank opened two years ago.
   It will invest $7.5 million in the new fund, 15 percent of the
fund's $50 million target. It is providing another $40,000 to buy 20
percent of the stock in an group to be set up in Budapest to manage
the fund's investments.
   Ms. Amaudry declined to say how much the Hungarian National Bank
will invest.
   The fund will be closed-end. That is, unless there is a decision
later to increase its capital, no new investors will be accepted
after the corporation and Bear Stearns and Co. Inc. of New York have
placed the shares. These will go to what the announcement called ``a
limited number of sophisticated imnvestors.''
   Each will have to put in at least $500,000, Ms. Amaudry said,
adding that it is not expected that shares will be traded on markets.
</TEXT>
