<FIRST>r a AM-SecondAbduction     07-12 0525</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Second Abduction,0541</SECOND>
<HEAD>Mother Accused in Infant's Death Enters Innocent Plea</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAUL DE LA GARZA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>EDWARDSVILLE, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A woman pleaded innocent Wednesday to
murder charges in her 6-week-old daughter's suffocation death nearly
three years after her first baby girl died under almost identical
circumstances.
   Circuit Judge Edward Ferguson told Paula Sims she could be
sentenced to death if convicted of two first-degree murder charges
in the death of daughter Heather Lee, whose body was found in a
trash can May 3.
   Mrs. Sims, 30, told authorities that masked gunmen abducted
Heather and 13-day-old Loralei Marie, who died in 1986, while her
husband was at work. Witnesses have said Mrs. Sims had wanted sons
and was unhappy with daughters.
   The Madison County grand jury, which indicted Mrs. Sims on
Tuesday, said it was weighing whether to charge her 37-year-old
husband, Robert.
   Mrs. Sims, wearing a baggy orange jail jumpsuit and wrist and
ankle shackles, was somber during the 15-minute hearing in this
county seat nearly 30 miles northeast of St. Louis.
   Defense attorney Donald Groshong entered a written plea, and
asked that bail be set for Mrs. Sims, who has been held in the
Madison County Jail since her arrest Tuesday night at her parent's
house in nearby Cottage Hills.
   Ferguson refused to set bond for Mrs. Sims, who had been free on
$350,000 bail on other charges stemming from the deaths. A formal
arraignment will probably come next week, the judge said.
   Mrs. Sims has already been accused of hiding the babies' deaths
and lying to investigators. She has been charged in Madison County
and neighboring Jersey County with obstruction of justice and
concealing a homicide.
   The trial of the Jersey County case has been postponed until next
month. Those charges stem from Loralei's death.
   ``I hope they find out the truth in both cases,'' said Bonnie
Trail, a former neighbor of the Simses in Alton. ``Two babies in
three years, God.''
   Heather's body was found across the Mississippi River from the
family's home four days after Mrs. Sims reported her abducted.
   Loralei vanished 13 days after her birth. Skeletal remains
believed to be those of the child were found a few days later about
150 yards from the Sims home.
   That death remains unsolved. Authorities have said the Simses are
the main suspects.
   Tuesday indictment came after the grand jury heard more than four
hours of testimony from Mrs. Sims' parents, Nylene and Orville Blew.
They were ordered to testify after being granted immunity from
prosecution.
   State's Attorney William Haine said other evidence made the
state's case. ``The physical evidence was very important,'' he said,
but did not elaborate.
   Haine said no decision has been made on whether to seek the death
penalty.
   The first murder count alleges that Mrs. Sims intended to kill
Heather and the second alleges she committed an act she knew had the
strong possibility of ending in death or great bodily harm.
   The Simses also have a 17-month old son, Randy, who was placed in
the custody of the state Department of Children and Family Services
during the investigation of Heather's death.
</TEXT>
