<FIRST>r w AM-Senate-Cambodia     07-12 0620</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Senate-Cambodia,620</SECOND>
<HEAD>Senate Committee Shelves Military Aid for Cambodian Opposition</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAWRENCE L. KNUTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In a setback for the Bush administration, the
Senate Foreign Relations Committee on Wednesday shelved a bid to
give U.S. weapons to the non-communist opposition in Cambodia.
   After that decision and several others, the panel voted 17-0 to
report to the Senate floor a bill authorizing $11.6 billion in
foreign aid for the next two fiscal years, a period beginning next
Oct. 1.
   The panel took no action on the Cambodia plan after several
Democrats voiced fears that any arms provided might find their way
into the hands of the Khmer Rouge, the Cambodian faction blamed for
the deaths of at least one million people when it held power during
the 1970s.
   The move by the committee does not necessarily kill the proposal.
Senators said it might be renewed in the form of an amendment on the
Senate floor or during a conference with the House on its version of
foreign aid authorization legislation.
   The committee also voted to impose a $90 million cap on U.S.
military aid for the government of El Salvador, a move intended to
symbolize fears that right-wing death squad activity might be
renewed under that nation's newly elected conservative government.
   The action sparked a brief debate in which Sen. Jesse Helms,
R-N.C., said the Senate action would encourage communist insurgents
inside El Salvador.
   The Bush administration's plan to begin arming non-communist
forces in Cambodia opened up deep divisions in the committee and in
Congress generally, fanning memories of the U.S. involvement in the
war in Vietnam.
   The situation is complicated by the fact that Prince Norodom
Sihanouk, the former Cambodian leader, has joined a loose alliance
of various Cambodian factions _ including the Khmer Rouge. The
combined aim of the coalition is to oust the government of Hun San
which was installed by occupying Vietnamese forces.
   The administration's position was backed by Sen. Charles Robb,
D-Va., who offered an amendment authorizing the president to make
military aid available to ``non-communist resistance forces and
non-communist civilians in Cambodia.''
   Robb said his amendment was designed ``to facilitate the
withdrawal of the Vietnamese from Cambodia and to prevent the Khmer
Rouge from regaining power'' by arming their opponents.
   But other members objected that the funding provided by the
amendment was open-ended and expressed concern that Sihanouk is an
unreliable and ``mercurial'' ally.
   ``I feel the preponderance of the evidence makes it unwise to
proceed with the Robb amendment at this time,'' said Sen. Alan
Cranston, D-Calif. ``It authorizes virtually unlimited military
assistance to a resistance force that is allied with the Khmer
Rouge.''
   In the end, Robb dropped his proposal.
   On El Salvador, Sen. Christopher Dodd, D-Conn., first proposed
capping military aid at $85 million, last year's level. He agreed to
a $5 million increase.
   Helms told the committee the enemy in El Salvador is the
communist insurgency there, not the conservative government of
President Alfredo Cristiani.
   ``By your vote on this amendment you indicate which way you
stand,'' Helms said.
   Dodd replied: ``To say that because you favor an $85 million cap
you favor Marxism is ludicrous. No one on this committee favors
Marxism.''
   He said the idea of a limit on military spending is to send a
signal that a return to widespread human rights abuses in El
Salvador will not be tolerated.
   ``There are elements that would like to go back to the days where
you could go around that country and pick out people for
assassination,'' Dodd said.
   The committee voted, 11-8 to leave the cap on military aid in the
bill. It then approved the higher $90 million level by voice vote.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
