<DOCNO> AP890712-0197 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-12-89 1805EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a AM-FlemingExecution     07-12 0523</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Fleming Execution,0537</SECOND>
<HEAD>Georgia Court Blocks Execution; Alabama Stay Refused</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SONYA ROSS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Georgia's Supreme Court blocked the execution
Wednesday of murderer Son Fleming an hour after a parole board ruled
that his low IQ doesn't entitle him to leniency.
   Elsewhere, a federal judge in Birmingham, Ala., refused to halt
Friday's execution of Horace Franklin Dunkins Jr., rejecting claims
that the jury should have been allowed to consider Dunkins'
retardation in deciding whether to impose the death penalty.
   The cases follow a U.S. Supreme Court ruling in June that the
Constitution's ban on cruel and unusual punishment does not bar
states from executing killers who are retarded.
   In the Georgia case, the court, in a 4-3 vote, granted an
indefinite stay of execution five hours before Fleming was to die in
the electric chair and an hour after the Board of Pardons and
Paroles denied clemency.
   Fleming, 59, was convicted with two other men in the 1976 murder
of Police Chief Ed Giddens of Ray City, who was shot to death and
his body dumped in a swamp after he stopped a car matching one used
in a robbery.
   In their appeal, Fleming's lawyers cited a 1988 Georgia law that
says a defendant's mental condition can be considered in some cases
when applying the death penalty. However, the law doesn't apply
retroactively to cases like Fleming's.
   His IQ scores range from 64 to 72; a person with an IQ of 70 is
considered mentally handicapped.
   ``Philosophically, I don't want to see mentally retarded people
executed. But my job and oath is to see that the law is carried
out,'' said Attorney General Michael Bowers. He said he made no
recommendation to the parole board.
   Pardons and Paroles Chairman Wayne Snow said the board rejected
Fleming's appeal on grounds that Fleming was aware of the
consequences of his actions despite his low IQ.
   ``We wanted the decision to reflect what the (U.S.) Supreme Court
and others have said in this case,'' Snow said. ``We had to look at
the deliberate action on the part of the person. And we had to look
at their understanding of good and of evil and the consequences to
it.''
   In the Alabama case, defense attorney Steve Ellis argued that the
U.S. Supreme Court ruling requires that a jury consider a
defendant's retardation in weighing imposition of the death penalty.
Ellis said that was not done at Dunkins' 1981 trial.
   U.S. District Judge James Hancock denied a stay of execution,
ruling that that even if jurors didn't consider Dunkins' mental
condition, the judge did.
   ``And that's what's important since the judge is the one who
actually sentenced him to die in Alabama's electric chair,'' he said.
   Dunkins is scheduled to be electrocuted at 12:01 a.m. Friday. His
appeal now proceeds to the 11th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals in
Atlanta.
   A jury convicted Dunkins in 1981 of murder in the rape and
slaying of Lynn McCurry, a 26-year-old mother of four from Warrior.
She was found in 1980, tied to a tree near her home with surgical
tape and stabbed 66 times.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
