<FIRST>r w AM-Jackson-Mayor     07-12 0370</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Jackson-Mayor,380</SECOND>
<HEAD>Jackson to Move to the District</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD KEIL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Rev. Jesse L. Jackson will move to the
District of Columbia next month but he remains undecided about
whether to run for mayor of the nation's capital, Jackson aides said
Wednesday.
   The sources confirmed that Jackson will take up a temporary
residence in an apartment building in northwest Washington by the
first week of August while renovation work is completed on a home he
owns.
   By moving to the apartment house, Jackson can switch his voter
registration to the district, easily meeting an election law
deadline that requires mayoral candidates to have lived in
Washington for at least one year prior to the balloting. The next
mayoral election is scheduled for November 1990.
   However, the sources, who spoke only on condition of anonymity,
said Jackson has not yet committed to running for mayor.
   ``I talked to him recently about running for mayor, and he said,
``I'm still praying about it.''
   Jackson was traveling from Chicago to Detroit on Wednesday and
could not be reached for comment.
   Jackson's advisors remain divided about whether the two-time
Democratic presidential hopeful should try for the mayor's job in
Washington.
   Some advisors feel it would give Jackson the hands-on political
experience his detractors say he lacks, while others fear that he
could become bogged down with the problems of running an urban
government and tarnish his national image.
   To further complicate his mayoral decision, Jackson has
repeatedly said he would never run against Mayor Marion Barry, a
friend and ally from the civil rights movement.
   Barry, under federal investigation for his ties to a drug suspect
and struggling with city budget woes, has not said publicly whether
he will seek an unprecedented fourth term.
   Jackson's move also is timed to coincide with relocation of the
offices of the National Rainbow Coalition from Chicago to the
nation's capital. While the Rainbow Coalition offices are set to
open by Sept. 1, the sources said Jackson plans to keep his
residence in Chicago.
   In addition, Jackson wants to be based in Washington to more
effectively work on a drive to gain statehood for the nation's
capital, the sources said.
</TEXT>
