<FIRST>r w AM-ConyersAccident     07-12 0185</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Conyers Accident,190</SECOND>
<HEAD>Congressman Hurt in Accident</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rep. John Conyers, D-Mich., was injured
Wednesday when his car rammed into a security barrier as he was
being driven across the Capitol parking lot to reach the House floor
for a vote.
   Conyers, chairman of the House Government Operations Committee,
was treated at Washington Hospital Center for a cut on his forehead
and released, a hospital spokesman said.
   The windshield of the car was shattered when Conyers and the
driver, Cedric Hendricks, were thrown into it, said Capitol police
spokesman Dan Nichols. Hendricks was admitted to the hospital, but
no condition report was immediately available, a spokeswoman said.
   A Capitol ambulance called to the scene stalled, and a city
ambulance had to be called to take the two to the hospital, Nichols
said.
   For security, the Capitol is surrounded by concrete barriers.
Cars may enter only at designated points, and those are protected by
metal barricades that rise hydraulically from the ground and are
controlled by police at a nearby guard station.
   Nichols said the car's speed was one of things being investigated.
