<FIRST>r w AM-ArtsFunding     07-12 0463</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Arts Funding,450</SECOND>
<HEAD>Interior Appropriations Bill Used to Punish Arts Endowment</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: Contents of 5th graf may be offensive to some readers.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DIANE DUSTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The House voted Wednesday to eliminate $45,000
from the National Endowment of the Arts budget as punishment for
helping fund artworks that desecrate religious articles and show
explicitly homosexual imagery.
   The move, proposed by Rep. Charles Stenholm, D-Texas, was
approved 361-65 as an amendment to the $11 billion Interior
appropriations bill. It was an alternative to two other proposals by
members of Congress who were outraged at the NEA.
   Stenholm said he was ``concerned about the way the endowment was
moving on certain taxpayer funded projects,'' and wanted to send a
political message that the endowment had to be ``sensitive to the
general public concern.''
   A measure offered by Rep. Dana Rohrabacher, R-Calif., would have
wiped out the NEA's entire $144.2 million appropriation. Another was
proposed by Rep. Richard Armey, R-Texas, would have cut the NEA
budget by 10 percent.
   The fight centered on a photograph by Andres Serrano of a plastic
crucifix submerged in a container of amber liquid later identified
as the artist's urine, and an exhibition of photographs by Robert
Mapplethorpe that included depiction of homoeroticism, child nudity,
and sadomasochism.
   The NEA gave the Institute of Contemporary Art at the University
of Pennsylvania $30,000 to display the Mapplethorpe works, and the
Southeastern Center for Contemporary Art in Winston-Salem, N.C.,
$70,000 from which it awarded Serrano a $15,000 prize.
   The Serrano award also included funds from the Equitable
Foundation and the Rockefeller Foundation, said Josh Dare, spokesman
for the NEA.
   Stenholm said he did not see his measure as censorship, but
Armey, whose opposition to the art works led to the floor fight,
disagreed.
   ``The Stenholm effort was censorship by reprisal, specifically
and clearly confined to instances,'' said Armey. ``My effort was
designed to give a very large slug on the head to a stubborn mule,
to say procedurely and systemically you've got to change your
attitude and change your behavior.''
   Armey referred called the arts endowment ``arrogant'' and it was
not in compliance with ``standards of taste, decency, sensitivity,
tolerance.''
   Rep. Ted Weiss, D-N.Y., who opposed all three plans, said they
``take a piece out of America and what America is about and that is
freedom of expression.''
   Rep. George Miller, D-Calif., said it was ``a disgrace for this
body to be considering these amendments.''
   ``Once again we have politicians rushing in to define what is
work of artistic endeavor,'' he said.
   After the NEA battle, the full appropriations bill was approved
374-49.
   The bill also contained language restricting oil leasing in areas
off the coast of California, Florida, Maine to Maryland and for the
first time Alaska.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
