<FIRST>r w AM-Baseball-CableTV     07-12 0480</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Baseball-Cable TV,470</SECOND>
<HEAD>Cable Association Says Baseball Growing on Local TV, Too</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAY ARNOLD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Local television stations, not just cable TV
networks, are increasing the number of Major League baseball games
they carry, a cable TV group said Wednesday in disputing claims that
cable companies are stealing baseball from ``free TV.''
   Local broadcast coverage of professional baseball has grown by
nearly 40 percent over the past 15 years, from 1,190 games in 1975
to 1,647 games in 1989, the National Cable Television Association
said.
   Since 1985, the number of baseball games televised by both local
broadcast stations and by regional cable sports networks has
increased 7 percent, the NCTA said.
   ``As a result, cable's baseball coverage has served to
supplement, rather than reduce, the number of games aired by local
broadcasters,'' the cable association said in a report,
``Availability of Baseball Games on Broadcast and Cable Television.''
   It said some broadcasters have contended that baseball on cable
has reduced the number of games carried by local television stations.
   Complaints about once-free sports television going to cable have
not fallen on deaf ears in Congress. Rep. Norman Lent, R-N.Y., in
May introduced a bill covering sports on cable because of a contract
dispute that blacked out telecasts of New York Yankees baseball
games to 400,000 cable subscribers in the New York City area.
   Lent's bill would allow local authorities to make carriage of
local TV and sports broadcasts part of a franchising agreement.
   The dispute over the Yankees games was settled earlier this month
between Madison Square Garden Network and Cablevision Systems Corp.,
but only after the New York State Assembly passed a bill requiring
cable companies to pay a fine to customers when it pulls previously
guaranteed programs.
   Earlier this year ESPN became the first basic national cable
network to obtain rights to Major League baseball since USA
Network's contract expired in 1982. ESPN will carry 175 games per
season beginning in 1990.
   ABC-TV and NBC-TV have carried between 37 games and 40 games per
season since the early 1980s, and they will air 40 regular season
games this year, the cable association said. Beginning in 1990,
however, CBS will have the rights, and it will air only 12 regular
season games.
   The NCTA study said local stations will televise about 40 percent
of all baseball games in 1989, up from 36 percent of all games in
1985. It said Major League franchises have granted TV rights to 16
of 29 regional cable sports networks for 1989.
   Between 1985 and 1989, 14 of the 26 Major League Baseball teams
made more games available for local broadcast coverage, seven
maintained their level of broadcast coverage and four decreased
their rights agreements with local TV stations, NCTA said.
   At the same time, eight teams increased the number of games for
regional cable network coverage.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
