<FIRST>u a AM-WeatherpageWeather     07-12 0425</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0435</SECOND>
<HEAD>Widely Scattered Thunderstorms, Heat Waves Continue</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Thunderstorms developed Wednesday over parts of the Plains, the
Midwest and the Appalachians, and in the West, and a heat wave
continued over North Carolina and the middle Mississippi Valley.
   Thunderstorms produced locally heavy rain from the central and
southern Appalachians across the Tennessee Valley, from sections of
Missouri and Arkansas to northern Oklahoma, and in parts of Iowa.
   Heaviest rainfall during the 6 hours up to 2 p.m. EDT was 1.83
inches at Ottumwa, Iowa.
   One to 2 inches of rain fell within an hour in the Appalachians
of southeastern Kentucky, southwestern Virginia and northeastern
Tennessee.
   Thunderstorms also were widespread across the Rockies and the
Great Basin area of Nevada and western Utah, with a possibility of
locally heavy rain.
   More showers and thunderstorms were scattered across much of the
Ohio Valley and the lower Great Lakes region. An isolated severe
thunderstorm produced a tornado near Marion, Ohio.
   Thunderstorms rumbled over sections of Virginia and the
Carolinas, producing wind gusts to 50 mph in Tyrrell County, N.C.
   And temperatures in North Carolina surged toward 100 degrees for
the fifth consecutive day. By 1 p.m., Cherry Point had already hit
100. At 11 a.m., a temperature of 95 and 58 percent humidity
produced a heat index of 113 at the New River Marine Base.
   St. Louis, Mo., had its ninth day of temperatures in the 90s. The
heat there has been blamed for three deaths. During a heat warning
last month, at least five deaths were blamed on the heat. At this
time last year, said the Missouri Department of Health, there were
25 heat-related deaths.
   Temperatures around the nation at 3 p.m. EDT ranged from 57
degrees along the California coast at Crescent City, San Simeon,
Arcata and Hayward to 104 in at Palm Springs, Calif. Wednesday's low
in the Lower 48 states was 35 in the California Sierras, at Truckee.
   For Thursday, scattered showers and thunderstorms were forecast
from the northern and central Rockies across sections of the great
Plains, Arkansas and the Tennessee Valley to the East Coast states.
Widely scattered thunderstorms were forecast over the central Gulf
Coast states and along the Texas Coast.
   Highs in the 60s and 70s were predicted along the Pacific Coast;
in the 70s from New England to the Great Lakes region, and in
sections of the northern and central Rockies; over 100 in the desert
Southwest, and in sections of south-central and southwestern Texas;
and in the 80s and 90s elsewhere.
</TEXT>
