<FIRST>u i AM-Israel 1stLd-Writethru a0684 07-12 0809</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Israel, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0684,0835</SECOND>
<HEAD>Report U.S. Urging Israel to Save Coalition for Sake of Peace</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS thruout to UPDATE with Palestinian killed, quote from
other State Department official, date for school reopening, wounded woman's
husband also beaten. No pickup. ^With AM-Israel-Village, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NICOLAS B. TATRO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Bush administration and prominent American
Jewish leaders are urging Israeli politicians to preserve their
coalition government to prevent the collapse of peace efforts,
Israeli officials said Wednesday.
   A newspaper quoted sources in the Likud bloc as saying Washington
was meddling in Israeli politics, but a U.S. official denied such
interference.
   In the occupied West Bank, soldiers shot and killed a masked
Palestinian teen-ager who threw stones at an Israeli bus, an army
spokesman said.
   The spokesman, who cannot be identified under standing rules,
said soldiers chased the youth and opened fire after he refused to
stop. He said another Arab was arrested.
   Since the Palestinian revolt began 19 months ago, 559
Palestinians and 35 Israelis have been killed.
   Arab reports said Arab attackers Wednesday shot and wounded a
42-year-old Palestinian woman suspected of cooperating with Israeli
authorities. The attackers also beat her husband, the reports said.
   Also Wednesday, Israeli troops shot and wounded 11 Palestinians,
including a 3-year-old girl.
   The Defense Ministry, meanwhile, said the army will reopen the
1,200 West Bank schools that have been closed for most of the
uprising.
   The army announcement gave no date, but Israel radio said Defense
Minister Yitzhak Rabin was considering starting classes within 10
days.
   The United States repeatedly has asked that the 300,000
Palestinian students be allowed to continue their educations.
   U.S.-Israeli relations have been strained by the decision of
Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir's Likud bloc to harden its stand on
Middle East peace negotiations.
   The left-of-center Labor Party of Vice Premier Shimon Peres has
threatened to quit the coalition in protest.
   ``It's true that the Americans are asking us to wait a little bit
and see whether the peace initiative can be saved,'' said a Labor
source close to Peres.
   The conservative newspaper Maariv quoted Likud sources as saying
the Bush administration has committed ``vulgar political
interference'' in Israel's internal politics. It cited a message
reportedly sent via U.S. Ambassador William Brown urging Labor to
stay in the government.
   In Washington, State Department spokesman Richard Boucher
described such reports as ``blatantly absurd.'' ``We're not getting
involved in Israel's domestic political issues,'' he said.
   Assistant Secretary of State John H. Kelly made similar comments,
but he also said he believes hard-liners are damaging prospects for
Palestinian elections in the occupied lands. Kelly, the State
Department's top Middle East official, was testifying before the
House Foreign Affairs subcommittee on Europe and the Middle East.
   Labor party sources said Washington may downgrade a delegation to
visit Israel next week that was to have been led by Deputy Secretary
of State Lawrence Eagleburger.
   Kelly denied the delegation's mission is to persuade the
coalition partners to stay together and said it will discuss
prospects for Israeli-Palestinian negotiations.
   Shamir spokesman Yossi Ahimeir said the prime minister will
stress to the U.S. delegation that the hard-line decisions are not
binding on the Cabinet, which approved the peace plan by 20 votes to
six on May 14.
   ``They will hear that the peace initiative exists untouched, with
not a single comma changed,'' Ahimeir said.
   Labor won't make its decision about leaving the government until
early August, but sources predicted it will be difficult for Shamir
to restore credibility to his peace proposals.
   Ahimeir said two prominent Jewish leaders, fund-raiser Max Fisher
of Detroit and Seymour Reich of New York, chairman of the Conference
of Presidents of Major Jewish Organizations, called the premier to
urge a continuation of the coalition.
   ``Shamir does not need pressure since he believes the national
unity government should be continued,'' said Ahimeir, noting Likud
Cabinet ministers earlier urged Labor to stay in the government.
   The liberal American Jewish Committee sent a letter Tuesday to
Shamir demanding the Likud leader show in ``words and deeds'' his
commitment to the plan to start the negotiating process with
elections in the occupied territories.
   On July 5, Shamir accepted Likud hawks' demands that appeared to
severely limit his flexibility in selling the plan to Palestinians.
   These included barring 140,000 east Jerusalem Arabs from
participating, ruling out a Palestinian state, endorsing new Jewish
settlements in the occupied West Bank and Gaza Strip, and ending the
uprising a precondition for elections.
   Harry Wall, director of the Anti-Defamation League of B'Nai
B'Rith in Israel, said many U.S. Jews fear new elections could bring
an extreme right-wing government to power and raise again the ``Who
is a Jew?'' issue.
   They fear small ultra-Orthodox parties would seek a law requiring
all conversions meet Orthodox criteria, alienating Reform and
Conservative sects that predominate in the United States.
</TEXT>
