<FIRST>r a AM-DroughtSuits     07-12 0384</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Drought Suits,0397</SECOND>
<HEAD>Trial Opens for Agent that Sold Drought Insurance</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BILL VALE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CINCINNATI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A New York agency that allegedly oversold
millions of dollars worth of drought insurance to farmers in 10
states claimed Wednesday it only was acting on the orders of the
insurer, Chubb Insurance of New Jersey.
   James Ringer, representing Chubb, contended in opening arguments
in U.S. District Court that Good Weather International Corp. was
``an agent that went wild and did enormous harm to the farmers and
to Chubb.''
   Chubb is seeking $77 million in damages and some 8,800 farmers in
10 states have asked $20 million plus punitive damages. Chubb
already has agreed to pay the farmers $53 million in an earlier
out-of-court settlement.
   Good Weather of Long Island, N.Y., and Fresno, Calif., is owned
by Henry Cox. The company sold drought insurance for Chubb in 1987
and 1988.
   ``Good Weather was not acting as an insurance company in this
case but as an insurance brokerage,'' said defense attorney James
Moore. He said Good Weather and its agents sold the insurance on the
orders and guidance of Chubb.
   ``You don't sell what you don't have,'' Ringer said.
   Chubb contended Good Weather violated its contract with Chubb by
selling more than the available number of crop insurance policies.
Chubb contends it lost at least $75 million because of the action
and for lawyers' fees to defend itself in the resulting lawsuits.
   The lawsuit represents farmers in Ohio, Illinois, Iowa, Kentucky,
Indiana, Tennessee, Minnesota, Michigan, Missouri and Wisconsin.
   Stanley Chesley, representing the farmers, told the eight-member
jury in his opening statement Wednesday that Good Weather knowingly
oversold the policies hoping they would not have to pay off.
   He said the $20 million and damages demanded by the farmers would
make up the losses they suffered when the policies did not pay off.
   The farmers said they suffered emotional distress in being denied
the drought insurance, and sustained crop losses as well as losses
from not being given interest on the money they invested in the
insurance.
   The money sought is in addition to the $53 million Chubb
settlement, which Rubin's special master, Cincinnati lawyer Lawrence
Kane Jr., has been distributing since March.
   The trial is expected to take about two weeks, court officials
said.
</TEXT>
