<FIRST>r i AM-Nicaragua     07-12 0294</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Nicaragua,0307</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ten People Killed in Rebel Attacks</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FILADELFO ALEMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANAGUA, Nicaragua (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man dressed in a Contra rebel uniform
stopped a bus in eastern Nicaragua, forced the passengers out and
killed six of them with a submachine gun, according to government
reports Wednesday.
   Four more people were killed and one man was wounded when the
U.S.-backed rebels attacked the village of Rancho Grande, in eastern
Chontales province, shortly before midnight Tuesday, the Voice of
Nicaragua government radio said.
   About 250 army troops, police with dogs and helicopters, searched
for the attackers Wednesday, according to military sources who spoke
on condition of anonymity.
   Both the pro-government newspaper El Nuevo Diario and Barricada,
the newpaper of the governing Sandinistas, said the attack on the
bus occurred Monday in Camoapa, 54 miles east of Managua. Barricada
carried witness accounts.
   No further details on either attack were immediately available.
   El Nuevo Diario quoted regional army commander Lt. Col. Antonio
Castillo as saying the Contras plan to undermine Feb. 25 general
elections by kidnapping people and carrying out acts of sabotage in
the northern provinces.
   The Contras, supported by the United States since they began
fighting the leftist government in 1981, are preparing for these
attacks in southern Honduras, where they have base camps, Castillo
was quoted as saying.
   Meanwhile, the rebels' clandestine radio station, Radio
Liberation, accused the army of carrying out anti-rebel sweeps using
helicopters, heavy artillery and tanks.
   The broadcast, monitored in Managua, said this violated a
cease-fire that the Contras and Sandinistas signed in March 1988.
The cease-fire has been renewed by tacit agreement monthly since
January.
   Only scattered skirmishes have been reported during most of the
last 16 months, but reports of fighting have been increasing.
</TEXT>
