<FIRST>u i AM-Mexico-Elections     07-12 0601</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Mexico-Elections,1st Ld-Writethru,a0685,0625</SECOND>
<HEAD>Opposition Sweeps Elections in Baja; Durango Votes</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS thruout to UPDATE with official returns in Baja California.
No pickup.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ISAAC A. LEVI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The conservative National Action Party swept
state elections for governor and the legislature in Baja California,
handing the governing party its biggest upset in 60 years, according
to returns Wednesday.
   In the race for mayors and city halls, National Action candidates
tied with the governing Institutional Revolutionary Party, known as
PRI, taking Tijuana and Ensenada. The PRI won in Mexicali and Tecate.
   The returns, released by the state election board, showed that
National Action took eight of 15 seats in the Baja California
legislature in July 2 balloting.
   Four more seats were distributed through proportional
representation among four small leftist parties to ensure a minority
voice in the legislature.
   Last week, the PRI formally conceded defeat to the National
Action candidate for governor of Baja California, Ernesto Ruffo.
   Ruffo takes office Nov. 1 for a six-year term.
   ``This is no time to look for blame,'' PRI state coordinator Rene
Trevino Arredondo said in a news release.
   It was the first time the PRI has lost an election for a govenor
or a state legislature since the party was founded in 1929.
   ``We lacked electoral strength among the voters. We have to
accept that,'' Trevino said. ``We must learn from our mistakes so as
not to repeat them, and we must work hard and with a clear strategy
so that what happened in Baja California should not happen
elsewhere.''
   The elections in Baja California and four other states, and a
state election in Durango on Wednesday, were seen as a test of
President Carlos Salinas de Gortari's promise to clean up Mexico's
fraud-ridden election system. Salinas' own election in July 1988 was
marred by accusations of irregularities.
   Long delays by election boards in making returns public have
again raised opposition cries of fraud.
   In western Michoacan state, leaders of both the leftist
Democratic Revolutionary Party, National Action, and the PRI filed
protests accusing each other of fraud in at least eight districts.
   In that state, final returns released by the election board
Wednesday showed no clear majority. There was a 12-12 tie between
PRI and the combined opposition in the state legislature.
   According to the returns, the PRI won 12 seats, the Democratic
Revolutionary Party six, National Action two, and the leftist
Authentic Revolutionary and Popular Socialist parties two each.
   The voter turnout was only 28 percent, the election board said.
   PRI easily won the legislative races in Zacatecas and Campeche,
two of its strongholds, and was also expected to win a majority of
the 39 races for mayor and the 15 legislature seats in Durango where
it is also strong.
   Ten more seats are distributed among five minority parties in
proportion to votes received.
   In Durango, most of the state's 1,488 polling stations opened on
schedule at 8 a.m. Workers were given the day off, and turnout was
reported strong among the 709,000 registered voters.
   ``It's a holiday, and all is peaceful,'' said Ruben Cardenas,
editor of Cima, a newspaper in the rural state. ``Only seven polling
stations opened about an hour late because they didn't receive
ballots and other documents on time.''
   National Action hoped to win eight municipal elections.
   The Democratic Revolutionary Party said it hoped to win seven
municipal elections. Four other small leftist parties also were
competing.
   The economy of landlocked Durango, where John Huston's film ``The
Treasure of the Sierra Madre'' was filmed, depends on timber,
mining, farming and cattle ranching.
</TEXT>
