<FIRST>r w AM-Drought-Yeutter     07-12 0499</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Drought-Yeutter,535</SECOND>
<HEAD>Yeutter Appears to Open Door for Expanding Drought Relief</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PHILIP BRASHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Agriculture Secretary Clayton Yeutter, who has
favored limiting drought relief to winter wheat, appeared Wednesday
to open the door to aid farmers of other weather-damaged crops.
   Some southern crops, including rice and cotton, have been
devastated by flooding this year, and drought damage to
spring-planted crops elsewhere in the country is still being
assessed, Yeutter said after a meeting with Senate Republican Leader
Robert Dole and several other GOP senators.
   ``This is a fluid situation and legislation is not being
finalized at this point,'' Yeutter said.
   The Bush administration has threatened to veto a drought relief
package approved by the House that would provide more than $900
million to farmers facing crop losses from severe weather this year.
   Yeutter had agreed with Dole that relief to this year's crops
should be limited to crops planted in 1988 and damaged by drought _
primarily winter wheat. The House measure, and legislation
introduced in the Senate Tuesday by Sens. Kent Conrad, D-N.D., and
Tom Harkin, D-Iowa, would provide assistance for crops planted this
year.
   The Senate Agriculture Committee is scheduled to vote on drought
legislation next week. In a letter Yeutter sent to the House in
June, he said he would recommend that President Bush sign a drought
relief bill only if it was targeted to ``1989 crops affected by
drought.'' That meant mainly winter wheat, according to an aide.
   Yeutter said Wednesday crops in the South had been severely
damaged by flooding and that drought damage to spring-planted crops
is being assessed ``almost on a day-to-day basis.''
   ``When we first discussed the issues that are involved here the
primary concern was drought. It was basically winter wheat and
livestock producers. In terms of damage that has already occurred
that's still the case with the exception of the severe flooding,''
he said.
   After the meeting with Yeutter, Dole said senators and the
administration were trying to agree on drought legislation that
``takes care of those (farmers) who have a demonstrated loss.'' He
did not elaborate.
   Earlier Wednesday, North Dakota Gov. George Sinner declared a
statewide drought disaster, the first step in making farmers
eligible for federal assistance.
   Sinner said in a statement that he hoped the declaration would
also call attention to North Dakota's plight. A North Dakota State
University study estimates farmers could lose at least $541 million
in small grains and hay crops as a result of a deepening drought.
   The U.S. Department of Agriculture estimated the government would
save $950 million in farm program payments to winter wheat growers
because wheat prices are high.
   But Dole's staff said he sees a shrinking ``window of
opportunity'' for funding winter wheat drought aid because the
Agriculture Department is expected to revise those savings downward
_ to between $300 million and $350 million.
   Conrad said the savings will be higher and that spring crop
program payments will provide additional savings.
</TEXT>
