<FIRST>r a AM-NursingContract     07-12 0344</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Nursing Contract,0353</SECOND>
<HEAD>Nurses' Strike Continues at Pediatric Hospital</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JENNIFER McNULTY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>OAKLAND, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Nurses walking the picket line outside
northern California's largest pediatric hospital are prepared for a
long strike, and a spokeswoman for the group said Wednesday the
dispute could last for months.
   ``We're prepared to stay out as long as possible to get a
reasonable contract,'' said Susan Cieutat, a member of the
bargaining council of the California Nurses Association.
   ``It could be a week and it could be three months, but most
nurses here have other work,'' said Cieutat of the strike against
Children's Hospital. ``We can afford to stay out a long time.''
   On the second day of the strike, about 25 nurses picketed outside
the hospital, carrying signs that read ``We're Here for the
Children'' and ``Nursing Counts.''
   Hospital officials, too, are ``prepared to take a strike that
will last for a while,'' said spokesman Steve Tiger, adding that
about 30 non-union nurses were working inside the hospital, which is
not accepting new patients.
   A total of 700 nurses walked off their jobs Tuesday after
rejecting by a 4-1 margin the hospital's offer of an 18 percent wage
increase over two years. The nurses want a 26 percent increase over
two years.
   Union officials want salaries to be in a range between $39,400
and $49,100. Children's Hospital nurses now make between $32,000 and
$39,000 and are among the highest paid in the nation. The previous
contract expired June 30.
   No new talks are scheduled.
   The hospital transferred 87 critically ill children from the
195-bed facility to other hospitals in the San Francisco Bay area,
Tiger said. Only 41 children, who are too ill to be moved, remained
at the hospital Wednesday, said Tiger. Fifteen others were released.
   The hospital's pediatric trauma and intensive care units were
closed, although the emergency room remained open and out-patient
services were available, he said.
   Children's Hospital, which was founded in 1912 to serve poor
children, has one of only 14 pediatric trauma centers in the country.
</TEXT>
