<FILEID>AP-NR-07-12-89 2107EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Peru     07-12 0253</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Peru,0261</SECOND>
<HEAD>Army Kills 39 Rebels in Major Sweep</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LIMA, Peru (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The army said it attacked a group of Shining
Path guerrillas Wednesday and killed 39 of them, including seven
women, in a major jungle sweep.
   A spokesman for the joint military command in Lima said one
soldier was killed and one wounded in the battle near Ambo, in
Huanuco state, 180 miles northeast of Lima.
   It was the third major operation in a week by the army in the
region, which encompasses much of the Upper Huallaga river valley.
The valley is rich in coca leaves, the raw material for cocaine.
   The military said 75 Shining Path rebels have been killed in the
sweeps, carried out jointly by the army and the air force. Before
Wednesday's battle, only one soldier had been wounded in the
operations.
   The official, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said the army
seized dozens of assault rifles, handguns, shotguns, grenades and
sticks of dynamite in the raid.
   The Shining Path, a Mao-inspired group started by a Marxist
university professor in the early 1970s, took up arms against Peru's
elected government in 1980.
   The nine-year insurgency began in the highland state of Ayacucho,
235 miles southeast of Lima, but has spread through most of the
highlands and northern jungle regions.
   The government has said nearly 15,000 people have been killed,
including soldiers, police, guerrillas and government officials.
Most of the dead have been peasants killed in the cross fire between
the army and the rebels.
</TEXT>
