<FIRST>r a AM-ShippingPleas     07-12 0350</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Shipping Pleas,0361</SECOND>
<HEAD>Brothers Plead Guilty to Illegal Shipping Military Parts to Iran</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BALTIMORE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two Iranian-born brothers accused of illegally
shipping $1.6 million worth of military parts to Iran through
Savannah, Ga., pleaded guilty Wednesday.
   Mohammad Emamhosseini, also known as John Emam, 42, of Chevy
Chase, and Gholareza Emamhosseini, also known as Reza Emam, 38, of
Rockville, pleaded guilty to one count each of making false
statements on U.S. Customs Service export documents to facilitate
the parts shipments in 1984 and 1985.
   The shipments violated a U.S. embargo on military supplies to
Iran.
   U.S. District Judge Paul V. Niemeyer set sentencing for Sept. 19.
   Assistant U.S. Attorney Charles P. Scheeler said one shipment in
April 1985 led to the federal indictment of the two mean, two of
their other brothers and the Georgia supplier, William Whaley.
   Scheeler said the Emams gave co-defendant Whaley, owner of
Worldwide Military Sales Inc. in Augusta, Ga., an ``Iranian wish
list'' of military supplies Iran needed for its war against Iraq.
   Customs agents seized 22 crates containing 880 embargoed military
truck generators in that shipment.
   The prosecutor said the Emams, who are naturalized U.S. citizens,
made 10 parts shipments to Iran but federal authorities have been
unable to determine the contents of the other shipments.
   The Emam brothers were indicted in Savannah March 8 on two export
conspiracy counts and the false statement charge. Whaley and two
other brothers, Ali and Djalil Emamhosseini, who were partners in
E&amp;S International, were co-defendants in that indictment.
   In bargains with federal prosecutors, John and Reza Emam agreed
to plead guilty in Baltimore, near their homes, to the lesser false
statement felony in return for a government recommendation of
leniency at sentencing.
   Each faces a maximum sentence of five years in prison and a
$10,000 fine instead of the 10-year terms and $250,000 fines that
could have been imposed on each of the conspiracy charges had they
been convicted.
   The government also agreed not to prosecute Djalil Emamhosseini.
Ali Emamhosseini died recently of cancer, Scheeler said. Whaley
already has pleaded guilty in the case in Georgia.
</TEXT>
