<FIRST>u a AM-TropicalWeather     07-12 0163</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Tropical Weather,0168</SECOND>
<HEAD>Tropical Storm Barry Forms In Open Atlantic</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Tropical Storm Barry formed Wednesday in the open
Atlantic and carried top winds of 40 mph as it marched slowly
northward, forecasters said.
   At 10:30 p.m. EDT Wednesday, Barry was near latitude 24.3 north,
longtitude 55.1 west, about 675 miles northeast of the northern
Leeward Islands in the Lesser Antilles.
   Barry, which was moving to the northwest earlier, turned sharply
to the north Wednesday night at 6 mph and posed no threat to land,
said forecaster Hal Gerrish at the National Hurricane Center in
suburban Coral Gables.
   The storm formed as a depression earlier this week off the
western coast of Africa.
   No important change in strength was expected through Thursday
morning, forecasters said. If Barry gathers sustained winds of 74
mph it would become the first hurricane of the season.
   Tropical Storm Allison, the season's first named storm, caused
widespread flood damage in Texas and Louisiana last month.
</TEXT>
