<FIRST>a a PM-ReligionRoundup Adv14   07-12 0513</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Religion Roundup, Adv 14,0535</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv14</HEAD>
<HEAD>For release Fri PMs July 14, or thereafter</HEAD>
<DATELINE>YOUNGSTOWN, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Although stressing that it's an exception
and not normal practice, Youngstown's Catholic Bishop James W.
Malone has approved celebrations of the old Latin Mass on six
occasions in his diocese this summer.
   The action was in response to 135 letters requesting it.
   It provides for specific afternoon Masses in July and August at
chapels of several parishes in Canton, Ohio, for persons who had
asked for services in the Tridentine Mass, as used before English in
the liturgy became customary..
   The Rev. Bradford Helman, diocesan vicar for worship, emphasized
that regular parish Masses would remain in English. He said a
recently formed group, Ecclesias Dei, based in Glenview, Ill., has
misrepresented that the Tridentine Mass is the will of the pope.
   Deploring such confusion, Helman said ``the Tridentine Mass by
the typical Mass-goer is neither the will of the Holy Father nor the
agenda for the contemporary church.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WICHITA, Kan. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Rev. Ralph A. Bohlmann was elected to
his fourth one-year term as president of the Lutheran
Church-Missouri Synod at its convention here July 7-14.
   He won on the first ballot with a 52.4 majority as head of the
2.6 million-member denomination, the nation's second largest
Lutheran body.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>ELGIN, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Using a specially developed paper, David C.
Cook Publishing Co. has plans for publishing a new ``Illustrated
Bible,'' including four-color illustrations.
   The company says this previously has been impossible because the
ultrathin pages required to bind 1,300 pages of text in a hand-held
volume allowed coloring ink to bleed through the sheets.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>JACKSON, Miss. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The mechanics of merging Mississippi's two
United Methodist conferences were formally approved by 1,700 lay and
clergy delegates at the first annual conference of the new
organization.
   The merger involves the Mississippi and North Mississippi
conferences, including 1,300 congregations totalling more than
200,000 members.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>FORT WORTH, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The United Church of Christ has affirmed
``cautious, thoughtful and just use of genetic engineering,'' and
urged congregations to study its implications.
   The church's general synod said ``we must guard against ...
misuse and undue risks'' but ``greater immorality would be for the
church to stifle or ignore genetic engineering's promise for human
benefit.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hungarian and Czechoslovakian rabbis have agreed
to affiliate formally with the Rabbinical Assembly in what it calls
the beginning of renewal of Jewish life in Eastern Europe.
   The Assembly is the international, mostly American body of
Conservative rabbis, the middle-ground branch between Reform and
Orthodox Judaism.
   Calling the step in the new ``spirit of glasnost,'' Rabbi Albert
Lewis, RA president, said it presaged ``a new resurgency of Eastern
European Jewry decimated at the hands of Nazism.''
   The only recognized rabbinic seminary in Eastern Europe, the
Jewish Theological School of Budapest, has graduated about 75 rabbis
since World War II and a number of cantors.
   Discussions were planned for a fuller exchange of educational
materials and teachers.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Fri PMs July 14</NOTE>
