<FIRST>a a AM-ReligionToday Adv14   07-12 0850</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Religion Today, Adv 14,0876</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv14</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Friday AMs July 14 and thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Episcopal Uprising Seen Tempered by Special Arrangements</HEAD>
<HEAD>With Laserphoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE W. CORNELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Religion Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   As the dust clears, an uprising in the Episcopal
Church over women priests and lately a woman bishop appears to be
settling into a working, though edgy, adjustment.
   Keen differences still exist between church policy affirming
women's ordination and opponents of it. But earlier indications of
breakup have given way to stopgap accommodation.
   The modus vivendi has emerged, on both sides, in the wake of a
June gathering of nearly 2,000 Episcopalian traditionalists, who
were summoned to organize resistance to women in the clergy.
   The protesters decided, after initial harsh talk of rupture, that
they would try to stick with the denomination through some special
arrangements. The church's leadership seemed responsive.
   ``I believe that there are ways we can not only stay together but
enrich one another,'' says the Most Rev. Edmond L. Browning,
presiding bishop of the 2.5 million-member denomination.
   Asked about the implications of the large meeting of
traditionalists in Fort Worth, Texas, he said he has ``a great deal
of hope.''
   Similarly optimistic reactions came from the dissident camp.
   ``We can live together,'' said retired Fort Worth Bishop A.
Donald Davies, who was elected executive director of the new
Episcopal Synod of America, which was organized by the meeting to
stay in the denomination yet help traditionalist parishes.
   ``We could have separated if we'd have pursued that course, but
I'm glad we didn't,'' Davies said in a telephone interview. ``We
want to be the church in the church and work with fellow bishops to
provide a comprehensive ministry.''
   Browning, who has strongly supported women in the priesthood,
said ``there is not only a place'' in the church for those opposing
that position but ``what they bear witness to is needed for the
health of the whole body.''
   ``Without them we would be a weaker church,'' he said.
   He said the threat to the church ``comes not from people who call
themselves `traditionalists''' but ``from superheated rhetoric that
polarizes people.''
   ``I am working, as are others, to keep the climate one where
people can hear each other and not become polarized. We are working
for openness and a spirit of respect and courtesy,'' Browning said.
   The Fort Worth meeting was triggered by the Massachusetts
diocese's election to the episcopate last fall of a woman, now
Suffragan Bishop Barbara Harris. The session started out in a
bitter, defiant mood, but gradually mellowed.
   ``Originally some wanted to leave'' the denomination, Davies
said, but bishops of the Evangelical and Catholic Mission, the
sponsoring group of traditionalists, ``were determined if possible
to stay within the church.''
   ``I'm very pleased we didn't get into angry reaction,'' he said,
adding that in the end ``a sense of unity and harmony prevailed,''
recognizing that maintaining it necessitates room for diversity.
   The meeting adopted a plan for ``Episcopal Visitors'' _ bishops
of traditionalist views from outside a diocese _ to handle episcopal
duties such as confirmations in traditionalist congregations that
ask for it.
   Such arrangements, requiring permission of the diocesan bishop
involved, were approved by the church's 1988 convention. The
requests have to be channeled through Browning, the presiding bishop.
   An international commission of the worldwide Anglican Communion,
which comprises the Episcopal Church and 26 other national branches
totaling about 70 million members, sanctioned such special
arrangements.
   Six of the 27 branches have authorized women priests, although
not the ``mother church'' of England, thus producing varying
practices worldwide.
   Asked what would occur if a diocesan bishop declined to approve
an ``Episcopal Visitor'' in an area where a traditionalist
congregation wanted one, Davies said, ``We hope that doesn't
happen.''
   However, he added, ``if we ask for permission to come in, and get
a negative response, and if after asking the presiding bishop to
intervene, the answer still is `no,' we might feel compelled to go
in anyhow.''
   That would violate canonical provisons regarding episcopal acts
in neighboring dioceses, and presumably could lead to formal rifts
or schism.
   ``If there is no cooperation whatsoever, we probably would go in
without it,'' Davies said. ``If we didn't, the traditionalist
congregation would be cut off.''
   However, he said he felt the system was a ``basis for reconciling
differences.'' He said that Browning in conversations ``has given
his assurance of a place for traditionalists.''
   ``He will make sure of it,'' Davies said. ``It fits his pattern
of leadership. He has taken the issue seriously and the people that
raised it seriously.''
   Traditionalists also have opposed the church's revised prayerbook
of 1979, but Davies said ``it's now pretty well accepted,'' mainly
because an extended option allowed for using it or the old 1928
version.
   Asked if it were possible traditionalists eventually would accept
women priests in a church that now has 1,200 women among 14,000
clergy, Davies said:
   ``It's always a possiblity. But it's a different kind of issue.
It would break with a 2,000-year tradition of an undivided church.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Fri AMs July 14</NOTE>
