<FIRST>r f PM-BusinessHighlights     07-12 0926</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Business Highlights,0964</SECOND>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Chicago Board of Trade issued an emergency
order aimed at breaking up an attempted corner of the soybean
market, described by one analyst as ``the biggest market play since
the Hunts'.''
   The exchange's board of directors on Tuesday ordered all traders
holding commitments to buy or sell more than 3 million bushels of
soybeans for delivery this month to reduce those positions by at
least 20 percent each trading day through July 20, when the July
contract expires.
   Analysts said the order would likely result in a sharp drop in
the July contract's price at the opening of trading Wednesday.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A powerful investment trio plunged Britain into the
dazzling big leagues of debt-financed takeovers with a surprise
offer of $21 billion in mostly borrowed money for leading tobacco
giant BAT Industries PLC.
   BAT immediately rejected the hostile bid Tuesday from financiers
Sir James Goldsmith, Jacob Rothschild and Kerry Packer, whose plan
to buy the company and break it up would nearly match the record $25
billion debt-financed buyout of RJR Nabisco Inc. last year by
Kohlberg Kravis Roberts &amp; Co.
   The trio's offer, if successful, would be nearly quadruple the
size of Britain's previous largest takeover. It incited a buying
frenzy of BAT shares that helped buoy the stock markets of Britain
and the United States.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A former Merrill Lynch stockbroker, his mother
and three others were accused by the Securities and Exchange
Commission of insider trading by using tips from advance copies of
Business Week magazine.
   The civil suit, filed Tuesday in federal court in New Haven,
Conn., seeks a total of more than $3.4 million in illicit profits
and penalties.
   Ex-broker William J. Dillon, who was charged in the suit, already
has pleaded guilty to criminal charges and been sentenced to six
months in jail.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Corporate raider T. Boone Pickens Jr. told
Congress the Japanese are resisting his foray into corporate
ownership in Japan to prevent him from exposing a closed,
monopolistic economy.
   The millionaire Texas oilman purchased 20.2 percent of Koito
Manufacturing Co. for $800 million but was rebuffed two weeks ago at
a shareholders meeting in Tokyo when he sought three seats on
Koito's 20-member board of directors.
   Pickens told Congress Tuesday he poses no threat to the company's
management because the web of interconnected shareholders, including
Koito's customers, can easily outvote him.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WILMINGTON, Del. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Paramount Communications Inc. charged in
court that Time Inc. directors violated their duty in refusing to
let shareholders vote on Paramount's hostile $12.2 billion bid and
Time's own $14 billion tender offer for Warner Communications Inc.
   Attorneys for Paramount and for some Time shareholders told
Delaware Chancery Court Judge William T. Allen Tuesday that the Time
board effectively put the company up for sale when it agreed to a
stock-swap merger with Warner last March, and was required under
Delaware law to entertain any bids that maximize shareholder value.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The chairman of the House Ways and Means
Committee offered a package of deficit-reduction tax increases that
would hit airline passengers, pipe smokers, farm workers, banks and
everybody who uses the telephone.
   The plan that Rep. Dan Rostenkowski, D-Ill., presented to his
committee behind closed doors Tuesday would raise tax collections by
$5.3 billion during the fiscal year beginning Oct. 1.
   The target budget adopted by Congress requires a revenue increase
of that size.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Major banks have been slow to follow Chase
Manhattan Bank's cut in the prime lending rate due to uncertainty
over the Federal Reserve's monetary strategies as well as the slow
summer vacation season, economists say.
   Chase stood alone among the nation's large money-center banks
Monday in lowering its prime rate a half percentage point to 10.5
percent, the second such decline in as many months and the level at
which the prime stood at the start of the year.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The commissioner of the Food and Drug
Administration told Congress he is ``shocked, embarrassed and
angered'' by revelations that FDA scientists accepted bribes from
generic drug companies.
   Commissioner Frank E. Young promised Tuesday to seek maximum
penalties against the companies. But he said ``we're having a
difficult time trying to determine what we can do to remove these
particular products'' from the market.
   Young and his top aides were called before the House Energy and
Commerce subcommittee on oversight and investigations.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pro-democracy protests that paralyzed Beijing and
other Chinese cities did not hurt the economy badly, but
longstanding problems such as inflation remain serious, a government
spokesman says.
   Yuan Mu told a news conference Tuesday that retail prices rose an
average of 25.5 percent in the first six months of the year,
compared with the same period of 1988.
   He said most of the increase actually took place at the end of
last year, when inflation peaked at about a 36 percent annual rate.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>By The Associated Press</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Stock prices climbed Tuesday as the market extended its advance
for a sixth straight session. The Dow Jones industrials average
finished with a gain of 11.95 points at 2,514.61, significantly
lower than its best level of the day.
   The dollar was higher against key foreign currencies.
   Most bond prices finished unchanged to lower.
   Frozen pork belly futures sank below 30 cents a pound; hog
futures also retreated while cattle futures rose; grains and
soybeans were sharply lower; oil futures advanced; and precious
metals were mixed.
</TEXT>
