<FILEID>AP-NR-07-12-89 0053EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-Britain-BAT-Goldsmith     07-12 0561</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Britain-BAT-Goldsmith,0581</SECOND>
<HEAD>Goldsmith Offer For BAT Is Characteristically Flamboyant</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Britain-BAT, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By COTTEN TIMBERLAKE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Anglo-French takeover strategist Sir James
Goldsmith is being characteristically flamboyant with his joint $21
billion offer for BAT Industries PLC.
   The hostile offer for the diversified British conglomerate _
which may be best known in the United States by its Kool and Benson
and Hedges cigarettes and Saks Fifth Avenue and Marshall Field's
department stores _ is only the latest bold move by Goldsmith, a
jet-setter who already has established a reputation as an
international takeover strategist.
   The 56-year-old Goldsmith was joined in the BAT Industries bid by
British investor Jacob Rothschild and Australian entrepreneur Kerry
Packer.
   Earlier this year, Goldsmith formed a takeover vehicle called
Anglo Group PLC, which he said would be an ``industrial improvement
organization.'' Its bids for undervalued firms, he said, could well
be ``thoroughly hostile.''
   So far, the investment group has bought a 29.9 percent stake in
the British food company Ranks Hovis McDougall PLC.
   But long before Anglo Group, Goldsmith had created a reputation
as a takeover strategist both in Europe and in the United States,
where his conquests included Crown Zellerbach Corp., Diamond
International and Continental Group. Goldsmith reaped profits by
breaking up and cutting costs at acquired businesses.
   Goldsmith also became embroiled in a lengthy, bitter takeover
battle for Goodyear Tire &amp; Rubber Co. in 1986 that ended after the
company undertook a major restructuring, selling off most of its
non-tire businesses, and agreed to buy Goldsmith's Goodyear stock,
which he sold at an estimated $87 million profit.
   Goldsmith was born in 1933 to a father who was a British member
of Parliament, had taken a French wife and became a hotelier in
France.
   The young Goldsmith went to Eton, the exclusive British boys
boarding school. He left in his mid-teens, already having
established a reputation for being an audacious gambler, and later
held jobs as a waiter and cook.
   At the age of 20, he eloped with Bolivian tin heiress Isabel
Patino. Pursued by the world's press and her enraged family, they
married in Scotland. She died in childbirth several months later.
   Goldsmith is married to his third wife, Lady Annabel Birley. He
has seven children.
   Tall, mostly bald and blue-eyed, Goldsmith has British and French
passports. He owns homes in London, Paris and New York, and an
estate in Mexico.
   Descriptions of him have included such terms as charming,
petulant and meticulous.
   Although is descended from a German banking family, he is a
self-made man who started out with little money of his own.
   He had a variety of early business ventures, selling diet aids,
starting shops catering to pregnant women with clothing and other
products such as strollers, and ultimately merging various food
companies into one British group, Cavenham Ltd.
   In France, he headed the General Occidentale SA conglomerate,
which has interests in oil, publishing and retailing, including the
Grand Union supermarket chain in the United States. He sold most of
his General Occidentale holdings for an estimated $243 million about
three months before world financial markets crashed in October 1987.
   The Times of London ranks Goldsmith as Britain's 10th richest
person, with a fortune estimated at $1.2 billion.
   Goldsmith received his knighthood in 1976 from then-British prime
minister Harold Wilson and has been awarded France's Legion
d'Honneur.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890712-0239 </DOCNO>
