<FIRST>r f PM-Fortune-Foreign500     07-12 0250</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Fortune-Foreign 500,0266</SECOND>
<BYLINE>Profits of Big Foreign Companies Up 50 Percent in 1988</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Profits of the 500 largest industrial companies
outside the United States soared nearly 50 percent in 1988 from the
year before while employment at the companies jumped, according to a
survey by Fortune Magazine.
   Total profits of the Fortune International 500 rose to $116.5
billion last year from $78.1 billion in 1987, the business magazine
said Tuesday. Together, the companies added 300,000 new jobs.
   Japan had the largest number, 159, of companies in the group of
500, two more than in the previous survey. Britain came next with 74
companies, followed by West Germany (53), France (39), Canada (28),
Sweden (20), Australia and Switzerland (13 each) and Finland and
South Korea (11 each).
   Royal Dutch@Shell Group, an Anglo-Dutch oil giant, retained its
No. 1 spot on the list for the twelfth straight year. Japanese
automaker Toyota jumped into the No. 2 spot for the first time,
while British Petroleum dropped to No. 3 after 11 straight years as
No. 2.
   Fortune attributed the changes to Toyota's relentless annual
sales growth, which has averaged 22 percent for the past five years,
and to the slump in the oil industry affecting British Petroleum.
   The other top ten foreign companies were:
   _4. IRI, Italy, metals.
   _5. Daimler-Benz, West Germany, automobiles, electronics.
   _6. Hitachi, Japan, electronics.
   _7. Siemens, West Germany, electronics.
   _8. Fiat, Italy, automobiles.
   _9. Matsushita Electric Industrial, Japan, electronics.
   _10. Volkswagen, West Germany, automobiles.
</TEXT>
