<DOCNO> AP890712-0240 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-12-89 0055EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-Britain-BATProfile     07-12 0511</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Britain-BAT Profile,0533</SECOND>
<HEAD>BAT's Diversification Strategy Made It A Takeover Target, Analysts
Say</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Britain-BAT, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By COTTEN TIMBERLAKE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   BAT Industries PLC's strategy of diversifying away
from its core tobacco business principally into financial services
made it a tempting takeover and breakup target for a group led by
Anglo-French financier Sir James Goldsmith, analysts said.
   The group launched a $21 billion, all-securities offer on Tuesday
for BAT, the world's biggest tobacco company. The conglomerate
quickly rejected the offer, which is second in size only to this
year's $24.5 billion buyout of RJR Nabisco Inc. of the United States
by the New York investment firm Kohlberg Kravis Roberts &amp; Co.
   London-based BAT, once known as British-American Tobacco, has
been the target of takeover speculation, partly because analysts
consider the company's businesses worth more if sold off separately.
   Analysts estimate BAT's pieces could easily fetch more than $25
billion, compared with its stock market valuation of about $22
billion, based on its closing stock price Tuesday.
   ``It always has been a lowly rated stock because of its tobacco
business and despite the recent sucessful Farmers Insurance
purchase,'' said Charles Pick, an analyst with Nomura Research
Institute.
   Pick also said the financial community's lower rating of BAT's
tobacco business has been applied even to the company's other
businesses, which include retailing and paper manufacture.
   Earnings also have been variable in recent years because of
exchange rate fluctuations, Pick said.
   Bruce Davidson, an analyst with Smith New Court PLC, said some of
BAT's acquisitions have performed better than others, but overall
its diversification has been ``largely beneficial.''
   Nevertheless, Goldsmith told a news conference Tuesday that BAT's
``strategic error'' had been using the cash flow of its core tobacco
business to buy businesses that are entirely unrelated.
   The financial consequences of the diversification have been
``pedestrian earnings,'' Goldsmith said. He and his partners now see
restructuring as ``the only logical course to follow.''
   Goldsmith said that by selling BAT's non-tobacco businesses he
intended to unlock ``shareholder value.''
   BAT operates in about 90 countries and employs 310,000 people.
   BAT chairman Patrick Sheehy spent more than $8 billion in the
past five years buying financial services companies, including
general insurer Eagle Star; Hambro Life, renamed Allied Dunbar; and
Canada Trustco, Canada's seventh largest financial institution.
   In its most recent acquisition, BAT took over Los Angeles-based
Farmers Insurance Group Inc. for $5.2 billion cash last year after a
protracted takeover battle.
   Last year, tobacco contributed less than 50 percent of BAT's
profits for the first time.
   Sales of the tobacco busineses were flat at the equivalent of $11
billion, with operating profit of $1.2 billion, also little changed.
   BAT's cigarette brands include Benson and Hedges, Kool, Kent,
John Player Special, Lucky Strike and Viceroy.
   Its brand names in paper products are Wiggins Teape in Europe and
Appleton in the United States.
   BAT also operates the Saks Fifth Avenue, Marshall Field's and
Argos stores.
   BAT's after-tax earnings rose 21 percent to $1.55 billion in
1988, while revenue rose 3 percent to $28.9 billion.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
