<FIRST>r f PM-UnitedAttendants     07-12 0170</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-United Attendants,0178</SECOND>
<HEAD>United Attendants Authorize Strike</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Flight attendants at United Airlines have
overwhelmingly voted to authorize a strike, the Association of
Flight Attendants said.
   However, the negotiations between the union and United are under
the supervision of a federal mediator who would have to declare an
impasse and call for a 30-day cooling-off period before a strike
could be called.
   The negotiations, which fall under the jurisdiction of the
Railway Labor Act, are in recess, the union said Tuesday.
   The union represents about 13,500 United attendants and has been
negotiating with the carrier for nearly two years.
   One tentative agreement that included major concessions, reached
in November 1987, was rejected by the rank and file.
   The Association of Flight Attendants said 95 percent of the 9,980
ballots favored giving union leaders the authority to call a strike.
   United also is involved in negotiations with its pilots and later
this year is scheduled to open talks with the Machinists union,
which represents mechanics and ground personnel.
</TEXT>
