<FILEID>AP-NR-07-12-89 0120EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-TVSignal Bjt   07-12 0712</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-TV Signal, Bjt,0736</SECOND>
<HEAD>Company Claims to Have Technology To Make High-Definition TV Possible</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CARRIE FIGDOR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Seattle-based partnership says it has developed
a way to send both high-definition television and standard broadcast
signals on the bandwidths currently used to transmit conventional TV
signals.
   The development, which would be a breakthrough in television
technology, could speed the arrival of the vastly improved pictures
and sound available with HDTV. But some industry analysts were
skeptical of the claims.
   Officials of Northwest StarScan say their product will be
marketed first to private companies that can't afford space on a
satellite. The first customers are expected to be signed in December.
   ``We are not doing high-definition (television) because there is
no reason to now,'' said StarScan general partner A. Frederick
Greenberg, citing the virtual lack of television sets on the market
capable of receiving high-definition signals.
   However, StarScan spokesman Wiley Brooks said the company will be
``a major participant'' in HDTV when it is commercially viable.
   StarScan officials say they can compress a standard television
broadcast signal to fit in a bandwidth one-tenth the size it now
requires on a satellite.
   This enables the company to transmit at least 10 times as many
pictures over a satellite channel without disrupting the TV signals.
The cost of using satellites could be reduced to one-tenth, they
said.
   ``We do the compression in a way that does not reduce the power
of the signal. There is no degradation of the signal,'' said Brooks.
   Currently, HDTV signals cannot fit on a standard bandwidth
because they require much more information than a regular television
signal.
   Stephen Roberts, the company's chief financial officer, said
StarScan's technology compresses multiple broadcast signals into one
signal that can be separated at the receiving end with ``almost nil
degradation.''
   Other companies developing compression technology, such as Zenith
Electronics Corp., are compressing a single broadcast signal, he
said.
   Bruce Franca, deputy chief of the Federal Communications
Commission's engineering and technology office, said compressing
individual signals to factors of 4-to-1 on satellite and 2-to-1 on
cable can be done fairly regularly.
   At first the company plans to go into point-of-purchase
advertising, in which televisions could be set up in department
stores to advertise to consumers while they are in the store, Brooks
said. Commercials could be broadcast tailor-made for each
department, he said.
   Satellites and underground cables would not require modification
to receive the compressed signal, he said. A compressed signal and a
standard signal could be transmitted side by side in the same
bandwidth, he added.
   The FCC's said the company does not require the agency's approval
for closed-circuit broadcasts.
   The technology is a proprietary secret that has not been
patented, Brooks said. He said the patent had not yet been applied
for ``so as not to give people a road map on how to do it.''
   Other companies have developed compression technology but only
with a reduction in picture quality.
   The company's claims, if proven true, could have a tremendous
impact in the telecommunications field, analysts said. But several
were skeptical about StarScan's claims.
   ``If you could carry a lot more information on the same spectrum,
and with the push today for HDTV, it would be very beneficial. The
big question is, can they do it?'' said William Hassinger, assistant
bureau chief of the FCC's mass media bureau.
   ``If they are achieving tenfold compression and they're not going
into HDTV, they would be withholding from the industry something the
industry has been on its knees begging for,'' said Dale Cripps,
publisher of ``HDTV Newsletter,'' a Portland, Ore.-based newsletter
on high-definition television.
   ``I think it's real neat stuff, but the question is is their
technology faster, better, cheaper than what's on the market?'' said
Greg Francfort, telecommunications analyst at First Boston Corp. in
New York.
   ``If it's viable, it's damn valuable,'' said Dave Willis,
director of engineering at Denver-based Tele-Communications Inc.,
the nation's largest cable television operator.
   Controlling interest in the company is held by Greenberg and his
brother Richard Greenberg. Frederick Greenberg is chairman of First
City National Bank and Trust Co. in New York.
   The technology was purchased last year from from Kent,
Wash.-based Northwest Transforms Inc., which is now controlled by
the Greenbergs, Brooks said.
</TEXT>
