<FILEID>AP-NR-07-12-89 0200EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-InterestRates Bjt   07-12 0615</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Interest Rates, Bjt,0633</SECOND>
<HEAD>Economists Still Expect Other Banks To Lower Their Prime Rate</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VIVIAN MARINO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The delay by major banks in following Chase
Manhattan Bank's cut in the prime lending rate stems from
uncertainty over the Federal Reserve's monetary strategies as well
as the summer vacation season, economists say.
   ``I guess we'll have to give it a few more days,'' Kathleen
Camilli, a money market economist for Drexel Burnham Lambert Inc.,
said Tuesday.
   Chase stood alone among the nation's large money-center banks
Monday in trimming its prime rate a half percentage point to 10.5
percent, the second such decline in as many months and the level at
which the prime stood at the start of the year.
   Other major banks generally were expected to follow the move _
which Chase said reflected its own declining costs of borrowing _
but had not done so by late Tuesday.
   Reflecting the banks' dropping costs of funds, the average yield
on six-month certificates of deposit fell to 8.79 percent last week
from 8.84 percent the previous week. Thirty-year fixed mortgage
rates dropped to an average 10.17 percent, a 14-month low, according
to HSH Associates, a Butler, N.J.-based mortgage research firm.
   In addition, the Treasury's bellwether 30-year bond dipped to
7.97 percent at one point Tuesday _ the lowest level since April 8,
1987, according to Camilli _ before closing up at 8.03 percent.
   The prime, a laggard among other interest rates, is a benchmark
banks use to set interest on a variety of consumer and business
credit, including home-equity lines of credit. It also determines
the rate for many credit cards.
   Economists said Tuesday that other banks undoubtedly have seen
reductions in their cost of funds in recent weeks but that they
probably want to wait until the Federal Reserve further eases its
credit policies before they cut their prime rates.
   The Fed has shown signs of loosening its grip on the nation's
money supply in reaction to a continued slowdown in economic growth
and an easing of inflation.
   The federal funds rate, which reflects the Fed's credit moves,
dipped as low as 8~ percent last week after hovering around 9{
percent. But economists said most banks probably won't cut their
prime until fed funds remains firmly at the 9 percent level. Fed
funds _ the rate banks charge each other for overnight loans _
closed at 9 3-16 percent late Tuesday.
   Some economists also said slow summer business may have delayed
widespread prime cuts.
   ``I think they are dragging their feet in lowering the prime
because activity has dropped off a little bit this summer, and one
way of earning profits is to keep the spread wide,'' said Ward
McCarthy, an economist and principal with Stone &amp; McCarthy Research
Associates Inc.
   ``When rates drop banks tend to lag, whereas they're much quicker
to increase the prime when rates are rising,'' he said.
   By spread, McCarthy means the difference between the banks' cost
of borrowing and lending money.
   Some economists said prime cut delays also might be due to the
fact that a number of key decision makers at the major banks are on
vacation.
   ``I know at least one bank where that's true,'' said one source
at Chase.
   Elliott Platt, an economist with Donaldson Lufkin &amp; Jenrette
Securities Corp., said the Fed probably will push the fed funds rate
to 9 percent once a spate of new economic data is released later
this month.
   The producer price index, industrial production, retail sales and
capacity utilization figures for June are scheduled for release
Friday, and many analysts predicted those numbers would point to a
further economic slowing.
</TEXT>
