<FILEID>AP-NR-07-12-89 0210EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-Time-EntertainmentWeekly     07-12 0662</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Time-Entertainment Weekly,0682</SECOND>
<HEAD>Time Inc. Plans to Launch New Weekly Magazine</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Time, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SKIP WOLLENBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   On the same day that it fought to retain its
independence from an unwanted suitor in a Delaware courtroom, Time
Inc. announced plans to launch a new magazine, Entertainment Weekly,
in February 1990.
   Time executives insisted that is was coincidence that the
magazine announcement came on the same day as Tuesday's
widely-anticipated Chancery Court hearing on Paramount
Communications Inc.'s request for an order blocking Time's proposed
acquisition of Warner Communications Inc.
   Paramount is making its own bid for Time.
   Nonetheless, the launch of Entertainment Weekly would be Time's
first new weekly since the costly failure of its cable TV guide six
years ago.
   The new magazine has been under study for nearly two years, Time
said, and will contain reviews and reporting on television, movies,
video, music and books. Time's other weeklies are Time, People and
Sports Illustrated.
   Reginald K. Brack Jr., the head of the Time Inc. Magazine Co.,
said the new magazine will capitalize on what he called an explosion
of interest in entertainment by focusing on products rather than
personalities.
   The company said the American appetite for such material is
clear: Americans watch almost seven hours a day of television and
each year rent 2 billion videocassettes, buy more than a billion
movie tickets, spend $8 billion on popular books and $43 billion on
electronic equipment and buy more than 750 million records, tapes
and compact disks.
   Time declined to disclose how much it is investing in the launch
of Entertainment Weekly, but some industry observers said they
expect it would require at least $20 million.
   Time lost about $47 million in connection with its TV-Cable Week,
which was launched in April 1983 and folded five months later.
   After that costly experience, some analysts said Time became more
conservative in approaching new magazines.
   It has invested as a partner in several magazines developed by
others, including a 50 percent stake in a joint venture that
publishes Working Woman and Working Mother magazines. It confirmed
Tuesday that it plans to sell its stake to its partner in that
project, Dale W. Lang, for a reported $25 million.
   Over the past 18 months, Time has been involved with two
launches. Its Southern Progress Inc. subsidiary started Cooking
Light magazine and Time more recently launched Sports Illustrated
for Kids, a monthly sports magazine.
   But Time has not tried a national launch of a weekly magazine
since TV-Cable Week folded. Its executives note that no one has
successfully launched a weekly in the United States since Time's
People magazine debuted in 1974.
   Brack said no comparisons should be drawn between Entertainment
Weekly and TV-Cable Week, which was a TV listings guide distributed
and marketed mainly through cable system operators.
   He said Entertainment Weekly will cover a broad range of
entertainment topics, won't carry TV listings and will be marketed
by Time itself.
   Michael Moore, worldwide media director at the advertising agency
D'Arcy Masius Benton &amp; Bowles, said he thinks the magazine has a
good chance for success since ``people are spending more on
experiences than they ever have.''
   Publisher Michael J. Klingensmith, who has been testing reaction
to this type of magazine through direct mailings, said Entertainment
Weekly will start with a circulation of 500,000 and expects more
than 80 percent of the magazines will be sold through subscriptions
at $1 a copy. The newstand price will be $1.95 a copy.
   Managing Editor Jeff Jarvis, who is now the TV critic for People,
said the magazine will have its own roster of critics who will
review movies, video, television, music and books. He said other
critics including professionals, readers and entertainers also will
appear, along with stories describing what goes on behind the scenes
in shows, songs and books.
   One sample cover, for instance, called attention to a story on
``How they make a James Bond action scene.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
