<FILEID>AP-NR-07-12-89 0727EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f PM-Japan-Markets     07-12 0368</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Japan-Markets,0384</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Up Against Yen, Shares Off</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. dollar finished higher today against the
Japanese yen while share prices on the Tokyo Stock Exchange edged
down.
   The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues lost 45.25
points, or 0.13 percent, ending at 33,701.52. The index, a
70.75-point gainer Tuesday, added 66.66 points in early trading.
   The dollar ended at 140.50 yen, gaining 0.88 yen from Tuesday's
139.62-yen close. The currency opened at 140.70 yen and moved
slightly downward while ranging between 140.40 yen and 140.95 yen.
   The dollar's strength followed its uptrend in New York overnight,
but trading in Tokyo was directionless, traders said.
   Masafumi Koyama, a Bank of Tokyo trader, said the U.S. unit,
which reached the day's high at 140.95 yen during the early session,
gradually fell in the afternoon as participants sold the dollar for
technical position adjustments.
   The dollar's rise was halted by the Bank of Japan's
dollar-selling intervention, he said.
   ``Tokyo was lacking fresh market-affecting news, and investors
were unable to determine the appropriate level of their
dollar-holding positions,'' Koyama said.
   He added that Japanese investors were hardly paying attention to
the nation's trade report for June, released late in the afternoon
Wednesday.
   Japan's June trade surplus with the United States totaled $3.634
billion, up from $3.622 billion a year earlier.
   On the stock exchange, the index fell in part because of the
yen's weakness against the dollar, dealers said.
   Market players were reluctant to buy despite the downward trend
in U.S. interest rates, because of political uncertainties ahead of
a July 23 parliamentary election, said a dealer with the New Japan
Securities Co.
   It is widely expected that the ruling Liberal Democratic Party
will lose badly in the upcoming upper house election. The party has
been hurt by an influence-peddling stock scandal, an unpopular 3
percent consumption tax and Prime Minister Sousuke Uno's reported
involvement with paid mistresses.
   Investors avoid buying due to fears that the ruling party's
election loss will result in a market plunge.
   Trading was thin, with first section volume estimated at 600
million shares, up from Tuesday's 550 million. Among the winners
were steels, constructions and shipbuildings, while automobiles and
machineries fell.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
