<DOCNO> AP890712-0250 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-12-89 0730EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-S&amp;Ls     07-12 0635</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-S&amp;Ls,0657</SECOND>
<HEAD>Confusion Marks House-Senate Meeting on Thrift Bailout</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: No conference meeting today; no tops expected; also ran on general
news wires</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVE SKIDMORE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   House-Senate negotiators attempting to craft a
compromise savings and loan bailout are off to a slow start, with
some House members complaining about the unwieldiness of their
94-member delegation.
   ``The point is we don't know what we're doing here,'' Rep. Stan
Parris, R-Va., complained at one moment of confusion in Tuesday's
session.
   Sen. Donald Riegle, D-Mich., who is leading a leaner team of five
senators, tried to persuade the House side to agree to delete 11 to
17 ``special interest'' provisions, each affecting one or a handful
of companies.
   But the House balked, even though it had already deleted the
special interest sections before passing its own bill last month.
Because of the way the House delegation is organized, it was unable
to consider the provisions as a group.
   The chairman of the House Banking Committee, Rep. Henry B.
Gonzalez, D-Texas, has divided his conferees into platoons of 20 to
30 members, with each group handling one part of the legislation.
   ``It would take the House staff at least two, three hours to
figure out the jurisdiction'' on the special interest package,
Gonzalez said.
   There was more evidence of disarray as members of one House
platoon attempted to raise issues already addressed by another
platoon. At one point, House and Senate conferees found themselves
working from different documents and unsure of what they were voting
on, prompting Parris' complaint.
   ``I have never seen anything quite like this in my 15 years in
Congress,'' said Rep. Carroll Hubbard, D-Ky. ``It's confusing to say
the least.''
   But, Rep. Charles Schumer, D-N.Y., said major conference
committees typically start slow and then build steam.
   Gonzalez has said he organized his delegation in order to dilute
the influence of senior members, who bucked the majority in the
House on many issues to support S&amp;L interests. He said Tuesday that
the test of his system will be whether the conferees finish the work
carved out for them each day. So far, they have.
   Among the deals struck:
   _A special Justice Department anti-fraud task force will be
established in Dallas. The House also wanted a task force in
Southern California, but compromised with the Senate, which wanted
neither.
   _Conferees adopted the House section providing the Justice
Department with $75 million a year to detect and prosecute bank and
S&amp;L fraud. The Senate had voted to spend $50 million a year.
   _The House side, on a 13-7 vote, defeated a move by Rep. Frank
Annunzio, D-Ill., to delete provisions for dozens of special
studies. He complained they would be costly and most members of
Congress would be unlikely to read them.
   _Employees, including political appointees, of the Federal Home
Loan Bank Board, which is being broken up in a regulatory
reorganization, will have their jobs protected for a year or get
severance pay.
   _A provision to give the Federal Deposit Insurance Corp., which
under the bill guarantees bank and S&amp;L accounts up to $100,000, the
authority to second-guess the decisions of other commercial bank
regulators was scrapped.
   On the special interest provisions, House and Senate staff
members had substantially worked out which would be deleted.
   But some conferees, including Reps. Doug Barnard, D-Ga., and
Barney Frank, D-Mass., and Sens. Jake Garn, R-Utah, and Alan
Cranston, D-Calif., argued the provisions ought to be considered
one-by-one.
   ``It may be public interest as well as special interest to
consider the problems'' of individual institutions, Cranston said.
   Riegle said he wants the conferees to finish by July 18, more
than soon enough for the full House and Senate to ratify the package
and send it to President Bush before leaving for their August
vacation.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
