<FIRST>r f PM-P&amp;GStock     07-12 0312</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-P&amp;G Stock,0322</SECOND>
<HEAD>Company to Offer Stock Split</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CINCINNATI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Procter &amp; Gamble Co. said it plans to ask
its shareholders to consider a two-for-one common stock split and to
increase quarterly dividents 13 percent to 90 cents a share.
   P&amp;G announced Tuesday that at its annual meeting on Oct. 10, its
board of directors will ask shareholders to consider increasing the
number of shares of common stock from 500 million to 1 billion and
converting shares of currently held stock from one share to two.
   The company also will ask shareholders to increase the number of
Class A preferred shares from 297.5 million to 600 million. Series A
ESOP Convertible Class A Preferred Stock, which is held by the
company's employee profit-sharing plan, will be split automatically.
   ``It is expected that the two-for-one common stock split will
result in a market price for common stock in a range which will be
more attractive to individual investors,'' P&amp;G said in a statement.
   The changes ``will benefit both the shareholders and the company
by creating a broader market for the stock,'' the company said.
   Shareholders of record on Aug. 11 will be able to vote at the
meeting.
   The board Tuesday declared a quarterly dividend of 80 cents per
share on common stock. It will be payable Aug. 15 to shareholders of
record July 21.
   The company also announced that depending on profits, the board
plans to declare a quarterly dividend of 90 cents per share that
will be payable to shareholders of record before the Oct. 20 common
stock split. P&amp;G said this payment would equal a 12.5 percent
increase in the dividend rate.
   The Cincinnati-based consumer products company had sales of $19
billion during fiscal 1987-88. The company makes and markets laundry
and cleaning products, personal care products, food and beverage
products, and products for business and industry.
</TEXT>
