<FILEID>AP-NR-07-12-89 0802EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-Princeton-Newport     07-12 0385</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Princeton-Newport,0400</SECOND>
<HEAD>Defendant Denies `Parks' Included Prearranged Prices</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEFAN FATSIS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Princeton-Newport Partners sold and then bought
back blocks of securities at the end of 1984 for the purchase price
plus a consistent 6.25-cent commission, a federal prosecutor said in
the first securities racketeering trial.
   Cross-examining former Princeton-Newport managing partner James
Sutton Regan, Assistant U.S. Attorney Mark Hansen sought to
demonstrate that the deals were prearranged and in violation of
federal tax and securities laws.
   Regan, one of six defendants in the case, repeatedly denied that
the partnership had contracts with investment firms to buy back
securities at prearranged prices.
   Also charged are four other Princeton-Newport officials and a
former Drexel Burnham Lambert Inc. trader. The case has attracted
wide interest because the defendants were the first securities
executives charged under the federal Racketeer Influenced and
Corrupt Organizations law.
   Hansen listed a series of late December 1984 transactions in
which Princeton-Newport sold corporate bonds to Merrill Lynch &amp; Co.
and bought them back a few days later at the same price plus 1-16,
or 6.25 cents. The deals were arranged by Princeton-Newport partner
Paul A. Berkman.
   ``Isn't it a fact that Mr. Berkman was told up front that it was
going to be 6 cents?'' Hansen asked.
   ``I have no knowledge of that,'' Regan said.
   The government is seeking to show that such a securities
``parking'' arrangement is illegal if it involved a predetermined
buyback date and price. Hansen said the 6.25 cent increase in the
buyback price indicated a set deal.
   The indictment in the case contends Princeton-Newport's
executives engaged in a racketeering conspiracy through bogus
securities trades to generate millions of dollars in false tax
losses.
   Regan has testified the firm arranged securities transactions but
without set buyback prices to generate short-term losses for tax
purposes. He testified under questioning from his lawyer that he
believed the deals were legal.
   Also on trial are Princeton-Newport general partners Charles
Zarzecki and Jack Z. Rabinowitz; the firm's controller, Steven B.
Smotrich; and former Drexel trader Bruce Lee Newberg.
   The jury trial is being held before U.S. District Judge Robert
Carter.
   Princeton-Newport was a small securities firm with offices in
Princeton, N.J., and Newport Beach, Calif., that went out of
business after the indictment was brought last August.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
