<HEAD>United Will Close Airline Reservations Office Employing 450</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CLEVELAND (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   United Airlines says it will close its suburban
regional ticket reservation office when its lease expires next June
30 and will guarantee the office's 450 employees jobs elsewhere with
the airline.
   The shutdown of the facility in Rocky River reflects an airline
trend toward fewer but larger reservation offices that are more
economically efficient, Mark Liberman, United's vice president for
reservations, said Tuesday.
   Liberman said the shutdown was announced early so employees will
have enough time to plan their futures.
   Employees choosing to relocate with United will receive moving
assistance, according to Liberman, who said job openings were
available in all of United's eight other domestic reservations
offices.
