<FILEID>AP-NR-07-12-89 0812EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-JapaneseBeef     07-12 0543</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Japanese Beef,0559</SECOND>
<HEAD>WSU Researchers Eye Japanese Cattle Breed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PULLMAN, Wash. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Washington State University researchers
want to find out whether a Japanese breed of cattle known as Wagyu
can be raised profitably in the United States.
   A yes answer could mean high stakes to beef producers in
Washington and elsewhere, who potentially could make hefty profits
producing beef for the lucrative Japanese restaurant market.
   ``We are shipping some of our prime beef over there now,'' said
Jerry Reeves, a WSU animal scientist involved in the Wagyu project.
``We get about $4 a pound for it. Their Wagyu cattle bring in $10 to
$40 a pound.''
   The highest grade Wagyu carcasses fetch as much as $16,000 in
Japan, about twice as much as the average carcass price in the
United States, Reeves said in a news release this week.
   ``It's a niche market, but at a different level, there may be a
market for Wagyu crossbreds, which Japan cannot produce
economically,'' said Ray Wright, a WSU animal physiologist heading
the research project. ``We also might have a market for Wagyu beef
in Japanese restaurants in the United States.''
   The scientists want to find out if Wagyu beef animals can be bred
in the United States profitably to meet Japanese preference for
erxtremely tender cuts used in sukiyaki and other Japanese dishes in
which the beef is cooked in boiling water.
   U.S. beef carcasses are a poor substitute because the fat tends
to concentrate on the outside, whereas Wagyu carcasses have a high
degree of marbling in the muscle, said Wright.
   ``If you drop our select grade beef into boiling water it comes
out tough,'' Reeves added. ``The interior fat of the Wagyu beef
protects it when it hits the water and makes it tender.''
   The WSU researchers have applied for permission to import live
Wagyu cattle, embryos and semen from Japan, but Wright said he is
not optimistic about getting approval anytime soon.
   ``You have to understand that the Japanese control the market for
Wagyu right now,'' he said. ``I think they'll be reluctant to allow
export of their animals...''
   As they await a response, the scientists have been negotiating
with a Texas cattleman to buy a couple of Wagyu heifers. The owner
might be the only person to possess Wagyus outside of Japan. His
animals are descendants of four Wagyu bulls imported to the United
States in the early 1970s.
   Once the scientists acquire some cattle, they plan to breed them
by embryo transfer processes. That would be the first step in
finding out exactly what U.S. cattleman have to do to rear the
cattle profitably.
   Even if they can gain access to the Japanese market, U.S. beef
producers will have to adapt their production systems to accommodate
the Japanese cattle, the WSU researchers say.
   U.S. cattlemen feed large numbers of animals ``all they can eat
to finish them out in 120 days,'' Reeves said. Japanese cattlemen,
he said, feed no more than six Wagyu at a time and don't market them
until they are four years old.
   ``We'll probably have to feed them the same amount of time,''
Reeves said, ``but it won't be economical to massage the animals and
feed them beer as is the custom in Japan.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890712-0257 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-12-89 0844EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-Japan-Trade     07-12 0383</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Japan-Trade,0398</SECOND>
<HEAD>Japan's Exports in June Up 2.7 Percent From Year Earlier</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Japan's world trade surplus narrowed 11 percent
overall in June, but continued to widen against its largest trading
partner, the United States, Finance Ministry officials reported
Wednesday.
   Japan posted an unadjusted trade surplus of $5.290 billion last
month, down from $5.950 billion a year earlier, but up from $3.760
billion in May.
   The trade surplus with the United States grew 0.3 percent to
$3.634 billion from $3.622 billion a year earlier.
   Exports to the United States grew 7.9 percent to $7.931 billion,
while imports from the United States rose 15.3 percent to $4.297
billion, the report said.
   The trade figures in June brought Japan's surplus in the first
six months of 1989 to $33.50 billion, down slightly from $33.7
billion in the same period last year.
   Ministry officials attributed the wider trade surplus from May to
June, to a 3-percent consumption tax that forced importers to buy
more before the new tax took effect April 1.
   From a year earlier, however, both exports and imports showed
moderate growth, though imports grew faster.
   Exports of products like machinery, non-ferrous metals,
television sets, video tape recorders and semiconductors were brisk,
while Japan imported more of U.S. goods such as meat, lumber and
pulp, business machines, audio equipment, semiconductors,
non-ferrous metals, cars and steel.
   Steel imports from the United States, for instance, jumped 212.4
percent from the year-earlier month to $19.768 billion.
   In June, the government report said, the yen declined against the
dollar, making the value of yen-denominated shipments smaller when
calculated in dollar terms. The dollar was valued at an average
143.06 yen in June, a slight gain from 143.06 yen a year earlier.
   Due to Japan's economic expansion that accompanied personal
consumption and corporate equipment investment, imports of
manufactured goods remained strong, accounting for 49.9 percent of
overall imports in June.
   In the first half of 1989, oil prices were generally lower,
although they began rising in May and June and pushed up overall
import figures.
   In addition to the introduction of the consumption tax, Finance
Ministry officials said, the death of Emperor Hirohito in January
and his funeral and other services in the following months dampened
business activities of many companies and hurt the country's trade.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
