<FIRST>r f PM-SmithKline-Projection     07-12 0296</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-SmithKline-Projection,0307</SECOND>
<HEAD>SmithKline Beckman Expects Second-Quarter Earnings Increase</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   SmithKline Beckman Corp., awaiting a vote on
a planned merger with Beecham Group PLC, announced its
second-quarter profit is expected to rise about 7 percent over the
same period last year.
   The pharmaceutical company announced Tuesday its operating income
is expected to increase by 30 percent to 35 percent, sales by about
10 perecent, and earnings per share to 92 cents to 95 cents, up from
79 cents in the second quarter of 1988.
   Net earnings are expected to increase at a lower rate than
operating income because of interest expenses, exchange losses and
other non-operating expenses, SmithKline said.
   The preliminary estimate was released before a scheduled July 26
meeting during which shareholders will vote on the proposed merger
between SmithKline and Beecham Group, forming SmithKline Beecham.
Beecham shareholders approved the merger June 20.
   Therapeutics sales are expected to increase about 10 percent in
the second quarter. Operating income for therapeutics is expected to
be up 40 percent to 45 percent, mainly because of slower growth in
operating expenses and improved sales of Tagamet and Dyazide, two of
SmithKline's most popular products.
   U.S. sales of those two drugs were weak during last year's second
quarter.
   Beckman Instruments sales are expected to be about 3 percent
higher than sales of the same quarter last year. Operating income is
expected to rise about 10 percent, while net income is expected to
drop about 6 percent.
   That decline is primarily due to interest expense related to
long-term debt incurred as part of Beckman's recapitalization in the
third quarter of 1988 and exchange losses.
   Clinical Laboratory Services sales are projected to be up about
19 percent in the quarter. Operating income is expected to rise
about 12 percent.
</TEXT>
