<FILEID>AP-NR-07-12-89 1107EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-AutoIncentives     07-12 0507</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Auto Incentives,0522</SECOND>
<HEAD>Analyst Says Extending, Boosting Incentives Is Mistake</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FREDERICK STANDISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Incentive packages on most of General Motors
Corp.'s cars and trucks have been boosted or extended in what one
analyst says may be the worst thing that the industry could do.
   GM issued new incentive offers for its Chevrolet, Pontiac, Buick
and Oldsmobile cars on Tuesday, and for GMC trucks today. Cash
rebates range from $500 to $1,500, depending on the model, or a
buyer may choose financing ranging between 2.9 percent to 10.9
percent, depending on the term of the loan.
   All are effective today and run indefinitely, except for
financing deals on Chevrolet cars and trucks, which expire Sept. 27.
   Auto industry analyst John Kirnan, of Kidder, Peabody &amp; Co. in
New York, said manufacturers may sacrifice future sales by using
generous incentives now.
   ``The reason why we think the amplification in incentive activity
is bad is ... that you are going to take away some buyers from the
fourth quarter and early next year,'' Kirnan said today.
   Late last week, before GM's announcements, Kirnan said: ``The
worst thing that could happen is that if the industry would raise
the incentive activity.'' Chrysler Corp.'s current incentive program
runs indefinitely and Ford Motor Co.'s expires at the end of this
month.
   Automakers have been wrestling with a three-pronged problem this
year _ sales below expectations, overly ambitious production
schedules and incentives that have lost their luster. All that has
added up to larger than desired dealer new-car inventories.
   These things, combined with expectations that interest rates will
drop further in the near future, might make the autumn a better time
to buy a car, economists say.
   Incentives have been used on and off all year, with the biggest
push being made during the spring. Within days of each other in late
March and early April of this year, GM, Ford and Chrysler announced
incentive programs that increased the number of qualified vehicles,
boosted cash rebates and drastically lowered interest rates.
   But sale figures through the second-quarter of the year and into
the third quarter indicated the enticements weren't boosting sales
to expectations and vehicles were getting backlogged on dealer lots.
The eight major domestic automakers had sold 19 percent fewer cars
and light trucks during the first half of this year compared with
the same time last year.
   According to this week's Ward's Automotive Reports, dealers for
those companies had a 75-day supply of cars on hand at the current
selling rate on June 30, the same level as they had two years ago
but far above the 60-day supply at the same time last year.
   Those companies made 72.6 percent of all the new cars sold during
the first six months of this year, and 72.1 percent last year.
Typically, inventories of imported cars are smaller.
   GM dealers had a new-car inventory of 79 days at the end of last
month, Ford had a 78-day supply and Chrysler's inventory was at 79
days, Ward's said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890712-0261 </DOCNO>
