<FIRST>u f PM-BoardofTrade Open   07-12 0366</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Board of Trade, Open,0380</SECOND>
<HEAD>Soybean Futures Plunge On Exchange-Ordered Selling</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soybean futures prices for July delivery recovered
slightly after falling sharply in early trading today on the Chicago
Board of Trade following the exchange's emergency order requiring
traders to reduce their holdings in that contract.
   Prices of other soybean contracts were moderately lower while the
corn and wheat markets were down slightly. Oat futures advanced.
   The Board of Trade issued the emergency order late Tuesday to
break up an apparent attempt by one large company to corner the
soybean market. Officials have not named the company.
   The July soybean contract tumbled 31 cents a bushel on heavy
selling at the opening. Analysts attributed much of that selling to
major grain companies holding large commitments to take delivery of
soybeans in July.
   But the losses were quickly trimmed, apparently on buying by
other parties holding large commitments to deliver soybeans in July.
The exchange's emergency order applies to those in either position.
   ``It's kind of wild and wooly here,'' said Gerald Zusel, manager
of floor operations for the trading company Balfour Maclaine Corp.
   Activity was relatively light in the other markets as traders
exercised caution ahead of this afternoon's Agriculture Department
report on planted crop acreage.
   In early trading, wheat was 1} cents to 4\ cents lower with the
contract for delivery in July at $3.90 a bushel; corn was unchanged
to 1} cents lower with July at $2.57{ a bushel; oats were 1 cent to
1} cents lower with July at $1.45{ a bushel; soybeans were 1 cent to
24 cents lower with July down 24 cents at $7.02 a bushel.
   Livestock and meat futures were mostly higher in early trading on
the Chicago Mercantile Exchange.
   Live cattle were .05 cent lower to .25 cent higher with August at
70.37 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .05 cent to .28 cent higher
with August at 81.75 cents a pound; hogs were .05 cent to .20 cent
higher with July at 47.05 cents a pound; frozen pork bellies were
.10 cent to .63 cent higher with July at 29.45 cents a pound.
   Cattle futures settled higher on Tuesday while pork futures fell.
</TEXT>
