<FIRST>r f BC-Earns-FannieMae     07-12 0241</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Earns-Fannie Mae,0249</SECOND>
<HEAD>Fannie Mae Reports Sharply Higher Quarterly Income</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Fannie Mae reported Wednesday that earnings
soared 60 percent in the second quarter as yields increased on its
mortgage portfolio and fee income rose.
   Fannie Mae, formally known as the Federal National Mortgage
Association, is a congressionally chartered, shareholder-owned,
company that provides money for homebuyers by purchasing mortgages
from lenders and packaging them into securities for sale to
investors.
   Fannie Mae's earnings totaled $193.0 million, or $2.28 per share,
on interest income of $2.7 billion, for the three months ended June
30. That compared with a profit of $120.7 million, or $1.53 a share,
on interest income of $2.54 billion, in the 1988 quarter.
   For the first six months of 1989, Fannie Mae earned $358.2
million, or $4.27 per share, on total interest income of $5.35
billion. The same period last year Fannie Mae earned $221.6 million,
or $2.82 a share, on total interest income of $4.98 billion.
   Fannie Mae President Roger Birk attributed the sharp rise in
second-quarter earnings to a widening in the spread between the
interest the company earns on its investment portfolio and what it
pays on its debt.
   Another factor was an increase in income from fees charged
lenders for guaranteeing morgage backed securities, he said.
   Fannie Mae purchased $4.5 billion in mortgages in the second
quarter, up from $3.4 billion in the first but down from $6.9
billion a year ago.
</TEXT>
