<FIRST>u f BC-BritainStocks 1stLd-Writethru   07-12 0259</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Britain Stocks, 1st Ld-Writethru,0267</SECOND>
<HEAD>London Shares End Higher</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: UPDATES throughout with closing prices</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   London shares again ended at a post-crash closing
high Wednesday, as traders continued to ponder the repercussions of
Tuesday's 13 billion pound, or $21 billion, bid for BAT Industries
PLC.
   At the close, the Financial Times-Stock Exchange 100-share index
was 5.8 points, or 0.3 percent, higher at 2,256.7, but sharply down
from an early high of 2,272.7. At its lowest, the index was 0.7
points lower at 2,251.6.
   The Financial Times 30-share index ended up 8.0 points at
1,858.3. The Financial Times 500-share index rose 3.19 points to
close at 1,276.98.
   The market closed at 4 p.m., one hour earlier than usual, because
of a strike by British transport workers.
   Dealers said early buying interest, which was a continuation of
the market's almost 60-point surge Tuesday, subsided as
profit-takers entered the fray.
   ``The market decided to consolidate recent gains,'' one London
dealer said. ``If it's going to push higher it needs to be sure it's
on a firm footing.''
   Many traders blamed the transport strike for containing activity,
although volume came to a buoyant 728.5 million shares by the close,
compared with 639.3 million shares Tuesday.
   ``The market's still in the bid frame of mind,'' one trader said,
``and looks pretty solid at these levels.''
   BAT shares fell 23 pence, or 37 cents, to finish at 877 pence. An
investor group led by financier Sir James Goldsmith is offering
securities worth 850 pence, or about $13.77, for each BAT share.
</TEXT>
