<FIRST>u f BC-Dollar-Gold     07-12 0328</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Dollar-Gold,0341</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar and Gold Drift Lower In Europe</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. dollar drifted lower in uninspired
European trading Wednesday as dealers awaited a spate of U.S.
economic figures due Friday.
   Gold prices also declined.
   Currency dealers said the dollar was pushed back to what they
called the middle of its present trading range.
   ``There was absolutely no reason (for the retreat) except that
people didn't want to go higher yet,'' said a dealer at a U.S. bank
in Frankfurt. ``They see no room to move on the upside or on the
downside, so everybody is waiting that something will come out
Friday that will revive the market.''
   Friday's figures, which include June producer prices, retail
sales, industrial production and capacity utilization, will be
scrutinized for further signs that the U.S. economy is slowing,
dealers said.
   They said they were keeping a close eye on the U.S. Federal
Reserve in case it decides to take further steps to relax monetary
policy after last week's slight easing.
   In Tokyo, where trading ends before Europe's business day begins,
the dollar rose 0.88 yen to a closing 140.50 yen. Later, in London,
it was quoted lower at 139.85 yen.
   In London, the dollar gained against the British pound. It cost
$1.6255 to buy one pound, cheaper than $1.6270 late Tuesday.
   Other late dollar rates in Europe, compared with late Tuesday:
1.8755 West German marks, down from 1.8795; 1.6135 Swiss francs,
down from 1.6160; 6.3645 French francs, down from 6.3740; 2.1160
Dutch guilders, down from 2.1180 1.1897 Canadian dollars, down from
1.1903; and 1,361.50 Italian lire, down from 1,364.50.
   Gold fell in London to a late bid price of $379.75 a troy ounce,
compared with late Tuesday's $380.25. In Zurich, gold fell to
$379.50 an ounce from $379.75 late Tuesday.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold fell 91 cents to close at a bid
$380.87 an ounce.
   Silver closed in London at $5.27 a troy ounce, unchanged from
late Tuesday.
</TEXT>
