<FIRST>u f BC-Spain-Drexel 1stLd-Writethru f0064 07-12 0399</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Spain-Drexel, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0064,0412</SECOND>
<HEAD>Securities Commission Probes Drexel Unit</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: INSERTS New grafs 5-6, However, Repsol ... legal action, to
UPDATE with Repsol statement. Picks up 5th graf pvs, Between April ...</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MADRID, Spain (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Spanish securities regulators are
investigating a unit of the U.S. brokerage firm Drexel Burnham
Lambert Inc. over allegations it misrepresented itself in the stock
sale of the petroleum giant Repsol S.A., a report published
Wednesday said.
   The newspaper El Pais quoted unnamed sources from the National
Securities Commission as alleging that last spring Drexel sold
Repsol shares intended for small investors to a few large private
institutions.
   The newspaper's sources said Drexel requested an estimated $59.8
million in shares of the state-controlled Repsol to be sold to 400
investors. But they claimed that on May 11, the first day of public
trading, Drexel improperly sold the shares to a small number of
large private investors, the newspaper said.
   There was no comment on the report at Drexel's Spanish office.
   However, Repsol issued a statement late Wednesday denying Drexel
formed part of the syndicate of 48 brokerages or investment firms
that took part in the stock sale.
   ``Drexel Burnham Lambert did not form part of the offering, thus,
there has been no relation at all between that firm and Repsol,'' it
said. ``Repsol has cooperated since the start of the (commission's)
investigation (in early June) and based on its outcome will then
take the appropriate legal action.''
   Between April 20 and May 6, Repsol, Europe's eighth-largest
petroleum company, sold 79.75 million shares at $14.70 each to
400,000 shareholders worldwide.
   The company sold 44 million of the total shares offered to
individual Spanish shareholders under a pro-rated system.
   El Pais said the sources confirmed the commission had contacted
at least 10 of the 400 investors Drexel had identified as original
buyers. They said they knew nothing about ordering the purchase of
Repsol shares.
   El Pais said if Drexel used the names of investors without their
consent the brokerage could face criminal fraud charges.
   The secretary of the NSC president Luis Carlos Croissier said
there was no one available to comment on the newspaper report.
   In the United States, Drexel recently agreed to plead guilty to
charges involving securities fraud violations stemming from the
insider trading scandals linked to the now-jailed speculator Ivan F.
Boesky. Drexel also agreed to pay $650 million in penalties.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890712-0273 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-12-89 1559EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-Earns-CBS     07-12 0262</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Earns-CBS,0274</SECOND>
<HEAD>CBS Earnings Fall 8 Percent</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   CBS Inc. posted an 8 percent drop in
second-quarter profit due mainly to higher prime time programming
costs, the company said Wednesday.
   For the April-June period, CBS's net earnings totaled $118.8
million, or $4.62 a share, down from $128.7 million, or $5.01 a
share, in the same 1988 period.
   Revenue rose to $771.9 million from $740.8 million in the
year-earlier quarter.
   For the first six months of 1989, the broadcasting company's net
income plunged to $174.9 million, or $6.80 a share, from $1.04
billion, or $40.43 a share in the first half of last year. The 1988
figure included an $866.6 million gain from the sale of CBS Records
to Sony Corp.
   CBS cited an extraordinary loss of $200,000 in the first six
months of 1989 to pay down debt.
   Laurence A. Tisch, CBS president and chief executive, blamed a
strike by the Writers Guild of America for forcing up prime time
programming costs. He said the CBS television network's operating
income dropped as a result.
   The CBS Broadcast Group recorded an 11 percent quarterly drop in
operating profits to $137.9 million from $155.2 million in the
second quarter of 1988.
   The writers' strike delayed the start of the 1988-89 television
season, causing an uncommonly high percentage of first-run regular
series programming on the network schedule during the second
quarter, Tisch said.
   He also attributed the lower operating profits in the broadcast
group to the quick four-game finish of the National Basketball
Association championship, compared the seven-game finals in 1988.
</TEXT>
