<DOCNO> AP890712-0274 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-12-89 1533EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f BC-BoardofTrade Close   07-12 0293</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Board of Trade, Close,0305</SECOND>
<HEAD>Soybean Futures Nosedive In Exchange-Ordered Selling</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soybean futures prices closed dramatically lower
Wednesday on the Chicago Board of Trade following the exchange's
emergency order requiring traders to reduce holdings in contracts
for July delivery.
   Corn and oat futures prices were narrowly mixed while wheat
futures fell moderately.
   The Board of Trade issued the emergency order late Tuesday in a
move widely perceived as an attempt to crush one company's attempt
to corner the soybean market. Exchange officials would not name the
company.
   Soybeans for delivery in July closed 40 cents lower at $6.86 a
bushel. Other contracts closed 25{ cents lower to 7 cents higher.
   Analysts noted that overnight rainfall in the western reaches of
the Corn Belt also may have prompted some selling of soybeans and
corn.
   ``Certainly the extent of the decline in July was precipitated by
this ruling. But I think the market had reason to drop despite this
ruling,'' said Ted Mao, a grain specialist with Shearson Lehman
Hutton Inc. in New York.
   Trading in other market was cautious ahead of an Agriculture
Department report on planted crop acreage. The report, released
after the close, pegged soybean acreage at 61.3 million acres and
corn acreage at 72.8 million acres.
   The soybean number was lower than expected and analysts said it
could spark buying of new-crop futures on Thursday. The corn number
was larger than expected and was pronounced bearish for the corn
market.
   At the close, wheat was 3{ cents to 7{ cents lower with July at
$3.88 a bushel; corn was 3{ cents lower to 6 cents higher with July
at $2.55{ a bushel; oats were { cent lower to } cent higher with
July at $1.43} a bushel.
