<FIRST>u f AM-Dollar-Gold     07-12 0471</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Dollar-Gold,0492</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar, Gold Fall</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Precedes LONDON BC</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar drifted lower in quiet dealings
Wednesday as traders awaited a barrage of government data expected
to shed more light on the economy's direction.
   Gold prices also declined. On the Commodity Exchange in New York,
gold bullion for current delivery fell $2.80 to $378.70 a troy
ounce. Republic National Bank of New York quoted a late bid of gold
at $377.40 an ounce, down from $379.
   Currency dealers said profit-taking and other internal market
influences were largely responsible for the dollar's decline.
   However, trading was described as thin, with many dealers keeping
a low profile until Friday's release of government reports on June
producer prices, retail sales, industrial production and capacity
utilization.
   The data will be scrutinzed to determine whether the Federal
Reserve will continue to loosen its credit policies by lowering
interest rates to prevent the economy from falling into a recession,
dealers say.
   ``After the news comes out the end of the week ... I would say
the Fed will err on the easier side,'' said Ronald H. Holzer, chief
dealer at Harris Trust &amp; Co. in Chicago.
   Lower interest rates tend to depress the dollar partly because
they make dollar-denominated securities such as stocks and bonds
less attractive to foreign investors, thereby decreasing the need to
convert their currencies into dollars.
   In Tokyo, where trading ends before Europe's business day begins,
the dollar rose 0.88 yen to a closing 140.50 yen. It was quoted at
139.85 yen in London, and at 139.60 yen in New York, down from
140.75 Tuesday.
   The dollar was mixed against the British pound. It cost $1.6255
to buy one pound in London, down from $1.6270 late Tuesday. Sterling
fetched $1.6300 in New York, up from $1.6235.
   Other late dollar rates in New York, compared with late rates
Tuesday, included: 1.8745 West German marks, down from 1.8835;
1.6135 Swiss francs, down from 1.6190; 1.18955 Canadian dollars,
down from 1.19055; 6.3575 French francs, down from 6.3840; and
1,359.00 Italian lire, down from 1,365.025.
   Late dollar rates in Europe, compared with late rates Tuesday,
included: 1.8755 West German marks, down from 1.8795; 1.6135 Swiss
francs, down from 1.6160; 6.3645 French francs, down from 6.3740;
2.1160 Dutch guilders, down from 2.1180; 1.1897 Canadian dollars,
down from 1.1903; and 1,361.50 Italian lire, down from 1,364.50.
   Gold fell in London to a late bid price of $379.75 an ounce,
compared with late Tuesday's $380.25. In Zurich, it declined to
$379.50 an ounce from $379.75.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold fell 91 cents to close at a bid
$380.87 an ounce.
   Silver prices were mixed. On the New York Comex, silver bullion
for current deliver lost 6.9 cents to close at $5.188. Silver closed
in London at $5.27 a troy ounce, unchanged from late Tuesday.
</TEXT>
