<FIRST>u f AM-OilPrices     07-12 0327</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Oil Prices,0340</SECOND>
<HEAD>Crude, Heating Oil Down; Gas Up</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Crude and heating oil futures prices fell
Wednesday, pushed down by technically motivated selling, while
gasoline futures moved higher.
   On the New York Mercantile Exchange, the August contract for West
Texas Intermediate dropped 38 cents to settle at $20.15 per
42-gallon barrel. The benchmark U.S. grade of crude went up 17 cents
on Tuesday after going down 39 cents on Monday.
   Other contract months of West Texas Intermediate crude also
declined.
   Refined petroleum products traded on the exchange posted mixed
results.
   The August contract for home heating oil slid 0.34 cent to 48.94
cents a gallon after jumping 0.49 cent on Tuesday, partially
offsetting a 0.98 cent loss in the previous session.
   Bucking the energy market's downtrend, wholesale unleaded
gasoline for August delivery rose 0.79 cent to 57.41 cents a gallon.
The gain added to Tuesday's 0.16 cent-increase, which followed a
drop of 0.13 cent on Monday.
   Chris McCormack, an energy analyst at Drexel Burnham Lambert
Inc., said technical factors were behind the selloff in the crude
and heating oil futures pits.
   ``I didn't see any news today that I would term bearish for the
market. I think the market just stalled out,'' said McCormack.
   He said the selling seemed to beget more selling as the contracts
moved to progressively lower levels.
   The decline in crude prices paradoxically occured despite report
of an unexpectedly sharp drawdown in crude oil inventories. In a
weekly report issued after energy markets closed Tuesday, the
American Petroleum Institute said the nation's crude oil stocks fell
2.3 million barrels to 331.6 million.
   Gasoline may have benefited from the latest inventory and
consumption statistics from the API. A perception that a surge in
summer gasoline demand might tax the operating capacity of U.S.
refineries also has supported gas futures.
   The API's weekly report showed gasoline inventories were down
nearly 5.2 million barrels in the latest week to 215.1 million.
</TEXT>
