<FIRST>u f AM-HungaryFund     07-12 0348</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Hungary Fund,0363</SECOND>
<HEAD>First Mutual Fund Set Up to Deal in Hungarian Stocks</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CARL HARTMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Communist-ruled Hungary has taken another step
along the capitalist road by letting its National Bank set up a
mutual fund that will include securities issued by the country's
private firms.
   The announcement was made Wednesday by the International Finance
Corp., a unit of the World Bank, which is owned by 133 governments
including both Hungary and the United States.
   It coincided with a visit to Hungary by President Bush, who
saluted that country's strides toward economic freedom and pledged
to open U.S. markets to Hungarian goods.
   Monique Amaudry, a spokeswoman for International Finance Corp.,
said the Hungarian government will own shares of some companies the
fund will invest in, but will not hold a majority stake.
   She said the fund, called the First Hungarian Fund Ltd., would be
the first of its kind among the Communist-ruled countries of eastern
Europe.
   ``The fund is an offshoot of Hungary's privatization program,''
Amaudry said.
   She said the fund will be closed-end, meaning no new investors
will be accepted after the corporation and financial advisor Bear
Stearns and Co. Inc. of New York have placed the shares. Amaudry
said the minimum investment is $500,000.
   The National Bank of Hungary is expected to protect investors for
about five years against the loss of their principal, and against
the possibility of the Hungarian forint, the national currency,
dropping in value against the U.S. dollar.
   Ms. Amaudry said it is not expected that the shares of the
Hungary fund will be traded on markets.
   The International Finance Corp. said it would invest $7.5 million
in the new fund, 15 percent of the fund's $50 million target.
   The corporation makes loans to private companies in Third World
countries, and to some companies run along private lines but owned
largely by Communist governments. It often buys a small number of
shares in such companies.
   Already it has made four investments in Hungary, including stock
in Unicbank, a Hungarian commercial bank opened two years ago.
</TEXT>
