<FIRST>u f AM-Eastern     07-12 0510</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Eastern,0529</SECOND>
<HEAD>Plans to File Reorganization Plan Before July 21</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: Deryck in 2nd graf is cq</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARCY GORDON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Eastern Airlines plans to submit a bankruptcy
reorganization plan before July 21, an attorney representing the
strikebound carrier said Wednesday.
   Attorney Deryck Palmer told U.S. Bankruptcy Judge Burton R.
Lifland at a hearing that the airline would file the plan prior to
the July 21 end of its exclusivity period, during which competing
plans may not be filed.
   Under bankruptcy law, a company has 60 days after it files a
restructuring plan to seek creditor approval of the plan. Rival
plans also can't be filed during that period.
   Last Wednesday, Lifland agreed to a joint request by Eastern and
its major creditors to extend the exclusivity period for two weeks,
through July 21, after they indicated they were nearing agreement on
a restructuring plan.
   A company seeking Chapter 11 protection has the sole right to
submit a reorganization plan to the court during the first 120 days
of its case, after which other parties may propose plans.
   Eastern's reorganization is centered around its plan for
operating at about two-thirds its pre-strike size and addresses how
creditors would be repaid and shareholders treated.
   Eastern wants to pay creditors with the proceeds of about $1.8
billion in asset sales, including several that already have been
approved by the bankruptcy court.
   The airline also announced Wednesday that its passenger traffic
in June exceeded expectations, apparently attempting to show the
success of their rebuilding despite the strike. The carrier said it
flew 252.2 million revenue passenger miles, a measurement of airline
capacity.
   At the hearing, Lifland postponed until Aug. 1 consideration of
the Eastern pilots union's request that a trustee be appointed to
take over operation of the airline.
   Miami-based Eastern filed for bankruptcy protection on March 9,
five days after the start of the strike.
   The pilots filed a motion seeking appointment of a trustee soon
after the strike began but consideration repeatedly has been
postponed by Lifland.
   The latest request for a postponement was made by David I.
Shapiro, the court-appointed bankruptcy examiner, because he is
conducting contract negotiations in Washington between the company
and the three striking unions. The talks began several weeks ago
with Eastern and the pilots union, and were broadened Monday to
include its Machinists and flight attendants.
   ``The parties are engaged in intense negotiation,'' Lifland said.
Appointing a trustee at this time ``would be like adding on a fifth
engine with reverse thrust; I don't see any point to that,'' he said.
   Also Wednesday, the Transport Workers Union, which represents the
6,200 Eastern flight attendants, announced it has contracted labor
strategist Ray Rogers and his firm Corporate Campaign Inc. to launch
a ``multidimensional offensive'' against Eastern owner Frank Lorenzo.
   The union said the actions against Lorenzo, chairman of Eastern's
parent Texas Air Corp., will include an ``international boycott'' of
Eastern, its sister carrier Continental Airlines and Scandinavian
Airlines System, which holds about a 10 percent stake in Texas Air.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
