<FIRST>u f AM-CommodityRdp     07-12 0738</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Commodity Rdp,0765</SECOND>
<HEAD>July Soybean Futures Plummet In Forced Selling</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Soybean Corner Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID DISHNEAU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Soybean futures prices tumbled Wednesday on the Chicago Board of
Trade following the exchange's emergency order that traders reduce
their holdings in contracts for July delivery.
   The order was perceived as a move to crush an alleged attempt to
corner the soybean market.
   Wheat futures also retreated while corn and oat futures ended
mixed ahead of an Agriculture Department crop report that traders
pronounced bullish for soybeans and bearish for corn.
   On other markets, coffee futures sank to a new eight-year low;
precious metals prices fell; energy futures were mixed; and
livestock and meat futures were mixed.
   In Chicago, soybeans for delivery in July settled 39{ cents lower
at $6.86{ a bushel in a session marked by fitful trading with the
heaviest selling near the opening and the close. Other contracts
ended 25{ cents lower to 7 cents higher.
   The Board of Trade issued an emergency order late Tuesday
requiring all traders to reduce their July soybean positions to 3
million bushels by the end of trading Tuesday and to 1 million
bushels by Thursday, the expiration date for the July contract.
   Exchange officials would not explain the reasons behind the move.
But a number of traders and analysts said it seemed designed to
prevent a single party from gaining control of the market.
   Published reports claimed the target of the exchange's order was
Ferruzzi SPA, a huge Italian agricultural and financial firm that is
one of the world's biggest soybean processors. But Ferruzzi stated
it had not tried to corner the market and protested the Board of
Trade's order.
   Analysts noted that overnight rainfall in the western Corn Belt
also may have prompted some selling of soybeans and corn.
   ``I think the market had reason to drop despite this ruling,''
said Ted Mao, a grain specialist with Shearson Lehman Hutton Inc. in
New York.
   Trading in other grain markets was cautious ahead of an
Agriculture Department report on planted crop acreage. The report
pegged soybean acreage at 61.3 million acres and corn acreage at
72.8 million acres.
   The soybean number was lower than expected and analysts said it
could spark buying of new-crop soybean futures on Thursday. The corn
number was higher than expected and was pronounced bearish.
   Wheat settled 3{ cents to 7{ cents lower with July at $3.88 a
bushel; corn was 3\ cents lower to 5\ cents higher with July at
$2.55} a bushel; oats were { cent lower to 2\ cents higher with July
at $1.43} a bushel.
   Coffee futures skidded on New York's Coffee, Sugar &amp; Cocoa
Exchange amid talk that Mexico had sold up to 300,000 132-pound bags
of unroasted coffee beans.
   Some traders perceived the rumored sale as an escalation of a war
for market share following the collapse of an international
price-support agreement last week.
   Coffee settled 2.34 cents to 3.63 cents lower with July at 85.25
cents a pound.
   Gold and silver futures prices fell moderately on New York's
Commodity Exchange in trading inspired by technical factors and the
absence of new supply-and-demand developments. The drop in soybean
and crude oil prices, portending lower food and fuel prices, may
also have prompted selling of the inflation-sensitive precious
metals, analysts said
   Gold settled $2.80 to $2.90 lower with August at $380.40 a troy
ounce; silver was 6.9 cents to 8.1 cents lower with July at $5.188 a
troy ounce.
   Crude and heating oil futures prices fell on the New York
Mercantile Exchange while gasoline futures moved higher.
   West Texas Intermediate crude oil settled 1 cent to 38 cents
lower with August at $20.15 a barrel; heating oil was .34 cent to
.57 cent lower with August at 48.94 cents a gallon; unleaded
gasoline was .32 cent to .79 cent lower with August at 57.41 cents a
gallon.
   Most cattle futures prices advanced on expectations that supplies
will decline sharply in August. Most pork futures retreated on signs
of sluggish retail demand.
   Live cattle settled .10 cent lower to .60 cent higher with August
at 70.75 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .28 cent to .80 cent
higher with August at 81.75 cents a pound; hogs were .33 cent lower
to .20 cent higher with July at 46.62 cents a pound; frozen pork
bellies were .40 cent lower to .02 cent higher with July at 28.87
cents a pound.
</TEXT>
