<FILEID>AP-NR-07-12-89 1808EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-DisneyLawsuit 1stLd-Writethru   07-12 0714</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Disney Lawsuit, 1st Ld - Writethru,0731</SECOND>
<HEAD>Settlements of $89.5 Million In Disney Shareholder Suits</HEAD>
<BYLINE>Eds: SUBS lede to reflect settlement was announced by all parties,
picks up 2nd graf bgng Suits brought... INSERTS 2 new grafs after 8th graf
pvs, The derivative...to UPDATE with Reliance statement, earnings charge.
Picks up 9th graf, Between March... ^By RICHARD DE ATLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Settlements totaling $89.5 million have been
reached in ``greenmail'' lawsuits by Walt Disney Co. shareholders
against the Disney board of directors and Wall Street financier Saul
Steinberg, the parties announced Wednesday.
   Suits brought by present and former Disney shareholders alleged
they lost millions when Disney ended a Steinberg-led takeover
attempt in 1984 by paying a premium price to buy out his Disney
stock.
   Of the settlements _ which are subject to court approval and
mainly will be paid by insurors _ $29.5 million will be split among
thousands of former Disney shareholders included in a class action
suit that claimed the stockholders sold their shares at a loss when
Disney stock plunged after the hostile bid by Steinberg's Reliance
Group Holdings Inc. was terminated.
   Burbank-based Disney will receive the other $60 million, although
a Disney attorney would not detail how that would happen. That
settlement stems from a derivative action brought by current Disney
stockholders.
   A statement the parties issued with the settlements and read by
Superior Court Judge Abby Soven said Disney acted ``in good faith''
during the takeover effort.
   Disney attorney Michael Diamond said the $60 million was ``a
recovery on behalf of the company,'' but he denied it was simply a
matter of money going into Disney's pocket.
   ``The company will not end up with cash out of the settlement,''
said Diamond. He did not address other kinds of consideration or
financing, but said the shareholders would be able to direct where
the company must use the money.
   The derivative action was to have been decided by the judge,
while jurors considered the case brought by former shareholders.
   Reliance, which has interests in insurance, real estate and
investing, issued a statement in New York saying its share of the
settlement was $20.8 million and it would take a pre-tax charge in
that amount against its second quarter earnings.
   The company stated it believed all its actions in the case were
lawful but it decided that settlement was more prudent than risking
the undertainties of a jury trial.
   Between March and June 1984, Steinberg bought up 12 percent of
Disney and announced his intent to take over the company and sell
off parts of it.
   The Disney board offered Steinberg $325 million for his shares, a
figure well above the market price. Steinberg accepted the offer and
made an estimated $60 million on the deal.
   Disney shares tumbled after news of Steinberg's buyout plunged
the stock almost 10 points. Thousands of shareholders who gambled on
a Disney buyout and change in management were caught unaware and
many decided to dump their stock at a loss.
   The lawsuit contended the Disney board violated a fiduciary trust
with its stockholders by paying ``greenmail'' to Steinberg. The
board replied that Steinberg was paid to prevent destruction of the
company.
   Attorneys for Disney and the plaintiffs declined to say how much
of the $29.5 million was being contributed by Disney, Reliance or
their insurers, but said shareholder reports and statements
eventually would disclose the amounts.
   ``Money is being paid on behalf of the directors, but no money is
being paid directly by Disney,'' Diamond said.
   Diamond said the principals in the matter, including Disney
banker Morgan Stanley, were indemnified against such actions.
   The settlements, ending five years of litigation in the matter,
came after three weeks of trial before Judge Soven. She told jurors
that attorneys in the matter were drawn to an agreement as the case
unfolded in court.
   The settlement ``contemplates a finding by the court that the
directors of the Walt Disney Co. in 1984 acted in good faith and in
what they believed to be in the best interest of the company,'' the
statement issued with the settlements read.
   Diamond said Disney would not have agreed to the settlement
without that statement of finding.
   In both cases, the settlement amounts include attorneys fees and
expenses.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890712-0283 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-12-89 1834EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-TaxBill 1stLd-Writethru f0199 07-12 0808</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Tax Bill, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0199,0826</SECOND>
<HEAD>Panel Approves $5.3 Billion Revenue Increases</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Updates in top 11 grafs, picking up in 5th graf pvs, Repeal
of</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM LUTHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Tax Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The House Ways and Means Committee on Wednesday
gave tentative approval to a catchall tax bill that would raise $5.3
billion for deficit reduction next year.
   Before endorsing the measure on a voice vote, the panel, b a
22-11 vote, rejected President Bush's proposal to reduce the tax on
capital gains. Committee aides said a capital-gains reduction is
likely to be considered again before the committee takes final
action on the bill.
   By voice vote at a closed-door session, the committee eliminated
from the package a proposed extension of the 3 percent tax on local
and long distance telephone service. The tax is due to expire Dec.
31, 1990.
   Earlier in the day, the committee voted to repeal a requirement
that employers use complex tests to prove that their
health-insurance plans do not discriminate against lower-paid
employees. The Senate has approved similar changes in the law, known
as Section 89, and the Bush administration also favors the changes.
   The bill would not wipe out anti-discrimination requirements. It
would, instead, greatly simplify how employers may prove their plans
are fair.
   Most of the three dozen-plus revenue-raising provisions in the
tax package, drafted by Rep. Dan Rostenkowski, D-Ill., the committee
chairman, are technical changes affecting corporations. Others would
raise taxes on users of snuff and pipe and chewing tobacco, halt a
scheduled reduction in taxes on airline tickets and air cargo, and
impose income tax withholding on some farm workers who now are
exempt.
   Committee aides said that before the package is completed, the
panel probably will vote on an amendment that would eliminate the
tobacco-tax increase. Also, members are likely to offer dozens of
amendments of their own, including one that would repeal the new tax
older Americans pay for insurance to protect against catastrophic
medical expenses.
   In addition, an effort will be made to retain at least some part
of a tax benefit for employee stock-ownership plans that
Rostenkowski has proposed to repeal.
   The bill tentatively approved by the committee would end the tax
exclusion that lenders now are allowed for half the interest earned
on loans used to buy company stock for an ESOP. It also would wipe
out the employer deduction for dividends paid on stock held by an
ESOP.
   Those two provisions would raise more than $1.6 billion of the
$5.3 billion that the committee is required to generate for deficit
reduction in the budget year that begins Oct. 1.
   Other parts of the bill, which are not subject to change, would
impose a 3-cent-a-barrel tax on domestic crude oil and imported oil,
repeal the completed-contract accounting break for defense
contractors, and require that certain types of deferred income be
subject to Social Security taxes.
   Repeal of the anti-discrimination tests for health-insurance
plans is a major goal of business organizations, which consider the
rules overly complicated and costly to administer.
   Congress enacted the rules in 1986 to expand the number of
workers covered by health insurance, but some employers say the
rules instead will force them to drop health plans.
   Members of Congress were concerned that highly compensated
employees should not receive an unduly large share of the
$30-billion-plus annual federal tax subsidy for employer-paid health
insurance. The law considers any worker who earns more than $54,300
a year to be highly compensated.
   The rules were to take effect Jan. 1 but became such a source of
controversy that the Treasury Department delayed their
implementation until Oct. 1.
   The Ways and Means Committee bill would delay any testing of
health plans until Jan. 1.
   After that date, a health plan would be considered
non-discriminatory if made available to 90 percent of all employees
and the employer paid at least 50 percent of the premium. In
addition, the annual premium charged a worker earning under $20,000
a year could not exceed $1,000 for a policy covering only the worker
and $2,000 for a family policy.
   A higher-paid worker who received a benefit greater than allowed
under the formula would have to include the excess in taxable income.
   The committee legislation includes a special break for small
business. The health plan of a business with fewer than 20 workers
would be considered non-discriminatory if the employer provides
coverage for all employees and contributes the same dollar amount or
percentage of premium to all.
   The House legislation includes separate requirements for
cafeteria plans, under which employees may choose from among
benefits that include cash and health coverage. A plan would be
acceptable if basic health coverage were available to 90 percent of
all employees and if the average benefit for higher-paid workers did
not exceed 150 percent of that given other employees.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
