<DOCNO> AP890712-0285 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-12-89 2021EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-Earns-Gannett     07-12 0253</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Earns-Gannett,0264</SECOND>
<HEAD>Earnings Rose 17 Percent in Latest Three Months</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Communications giant Gannett Co. Inc. said
Wednesday its second-quarter earnings rose 17 percent partly because
newspaper advertising revenues were up while production costs were
down.
   After-tax profit for the three months ended June 25 was $112.1
million, or 70 cents a share, on operating revenues of $904.1
million. That compared with earnings of $97.5 million, or 60 cents a
share, on operating revenues of $846.9 million for the same quarter
in 1988.
   Operating income advanced 15 percent in the second quarter to
$215.5 million from $188.1 million last year.
   Gannett's chairman and president, John J. Curley, said second
quarter earnings for the Rosslyn, Va.-based newspaper, broadcasting
and outdoor advertising concern were fueled by higher newspaper
operating income.
   ``Newspaper earnings benefitted from higher advertising revenues,
lower newsprint prices and the first-ever second-quarter profit at
USA Today,'' Gannett's national newspaper, Curley said in a letter
to shareholders.
   USA Today's first profitable quarter came in the last quarter of
1987.
   First half profits for 1989 were up 9 percent to $187 million, or
$1.16 per share, compared to $171.4 million, or $1.06 a share, last
year.
   Revenues also were up 7 percent to $1.7 billion from $1.6 billion
in the first half of last year.
   Gannett, which operates in 41 states, the District of Columbia
and seven overseas locations, publishes 84 daily newspapers,
operates 10 television and 16 radio stations, Gannett News Services
and the largest outdoor advertising company in North America.
</TEXT>
