<FILEID>AP-NR-07-12-89 2058EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-Hasbro-Coleco 1stLd-Writethru f0287 07-12 0329</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Hasbro-Coleco, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0287,0339</SECOND>
<HEAD>Hasbro Completes Purchase of Coleco Inc.</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 2 grafs to CHANGE dateline to conform with style,
ADD in 2nd graf that Hasbro is based in Pawtucket.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KAREN SCHWARTZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PROVIDENCE, R.I. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hasbro Inc. said Wednesday it had
completed the purchase of most of the product lines of financially
troubled Coleco Industries Inc., and would immediately begin
producing the popular Cabbage Patch Kids dolls.
   Hasbro, the nation's largest toymaker, agreed last week to
purchase Coleco's major assets for $85 million cash and an option
for Coleco to purchase 1 million shares of Pawtucket-based Hasbro at
$28.85 each after its bankruptcy reorganization plan was confirmed,
said Barry Alperin, Hasbro's executive vice president.
   Conneticut-based Coleco filed for protection from its creditors
under Chapter 11 of the federal bankruptcy act a year ago, citing
debts of $540.3 million.
   Hasbro stock closed at $20 Wednesday on the American Stock
Exchange, down 25 cents a share.
   Hasbro said it had reached agreement with Appalachian Artworks
Inc., creator of Cabbage Patch Kids, to begin manufacturing the
dolls immediately, in time to advertise them for Christmas.
   The dolls would be made overseas and packaged at Hasbro's Milton
Bradley division in East Longmeadow, Mass., Alperin said. Most of
Coleco's other lines, including the Scrabble and Parcheesi games
also would be produced in Massachusetts.
   Hasbro, which also bought the right to use Coleco's name, would
discontinue some of its products, including Alf and Wrinkles,
Alperin said.
   Chairman Alan G. Hassenfeld said the acquisition would add ``some
time-tested products which will enrich Hasbro's three divisions
without material additions to our cost structure.''
   Hasbro's third division is Playskool.
   Alperin said the Cabbage Patch line, which was the largest
selling toy of all time in 1985, ``has not had the attention it
deserved over the past couple of years.''
   Sales of Cabbage Patch peaked at more than $600 million in 1985
but slipped to $58 million by last year.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890712-0288 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-07-12-89 2248EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-Dunkin'Donuts     07-12 0296</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Dunkin' Donuts,0306</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dunkin' Donuts Challenges Bidders' Financing</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Dunkin' Donuts Inc. charged Wednesday in a federal
lawsuit that two Canadian companies have made false and misleading
statements about their financing for a $305 million bid to take over
the doughnut chain.
   In an amended complaint in U.S. District Court in Boston, Dunkin'
Donuts alleged that the financing arranged by Unicorp Canada Corp.
and Cara Operations Ltd. would not meet federal margin regulations,
which limit borrowing to buy stock.
   The board of directors of the Randolph-based doughnut chain also
issued a statement contending that the financing for the hostile
tender offer of $43 a share was preliminary and subject to
substantial conditions.
   ``Dunkin' Donuts continues to urge shareholders to reject (the)
highly conditional, illusory and inadequate offer,'' the statement
said.
   A spokesman for the Canadian companies said the allegations by
Dunkin' Donuts were ``totally baseless.''
   The spokesman, Elan Sober, said the companies discussed the offer
with federal regulators in Washington and that the companies ``are
satisfied that it complies fully with all applicable laws, including
the U.S. margin regulations.''
   Unicorp, a Toronto-based real estate, banking and energy firm,
holds about 12 percent of Dunkin' Donuts common stock. It formed a
partnership with Cara, a food services company, to launch the
hostile offer on June 15.
   Kingsbridge Capital Group, a subsidiary of Unicorp, and Cara have
said they would invest up to $80 million of equity and debt in the
takeover and have a firm commitment for an additional $275 million
of financing from Trilon Financial Group and Great Lakes Group Inc.,
both of Toronto.
   ``The commitment letter is a firm, written commitment to lend by
two major Canadian financial institutions,'' said Sober. ``Its
conditions are entirely standard. There is nothing preliminary about
it.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
